<DOCNO> APW19990526.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 05:51:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blitz Looms for Healthy Margarines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) --Two new margarines that can actually cut  
cholesterol and have no known side effects received a lukewarm 
response from the American Heart Association. 
</P>
<P>
	The group recommends that consumers with moderate to high  
cholesterol use the margarines only in consultation with their 
doctor and along with a healthy diet. It said people with normal 
cholesterol levels would get no benefit from either Benecol, made 
by Johnson &AMP; Johnson, or Take Control, made by Lipton. Both spreads 
were approved this spring by federal regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are taking a cautious conservative stance. We don''t want  
to be overzealous,'' said Robert Eckel, chairman of the 
association's nutrition committee. 
</P>
<P>
	A marketing fight between the two new cholesterol-lowering  
margarines starts today when Johnson &AMP; Johnson serves free bagels 
slathered with its spread Benecol to 200,000 morning commuters in 
10 cities. 
</P>
<P>
	J&AMP;J's big giveaway was taking place in Chicago, San Francisco,  
Boston, Dallas, Atlanta, Cleveland, Minneapolis, Miami, Portland, 
Ore. and Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	J&AMP;J also plans to leverage its experience selling drugs to  
doctors by having its 3,000 sales representatives pitch Benecol. In 
turn, J&AMP;J hopes the doctors will recommend it to patients with 
moderate to high cholesterol. 
</P>
<P>
	However, J&AMP;J has one big disadvantage in the marketing battle.  
The company, known most for selling baby powder, shampoo and 
Band-Aids, has little experience competing in the dairy food aisle. 
</P>
<P>
	Lipton's main business is marketing foods. It makes the popular  
margarine Promise, as well as other leading brands including Ragu 
pasta sauces and Wish-Bone salad dressings. 
</P>
<P>
	Lipton plans to kick off a national television advertising for  
Take Control in a few weeks, said spokesman David Blanchard. A 
celebrity, who Blanchard would not reveal, will be part of the ads. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also plans to send information on Take Control to  
doctors via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	But can consumers be convinced that the margarines are good for  
them? 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Vernon, president of J&AMP;J's McNeil Consumer Healthcare  
division, acknowledges the company will have to overcome skeptics. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no precedent for these two products as we have never  
seen a food that gives this significant a health benefit,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	To help counter skeptics, J&AMP;J has recruited 100 people in each  
of three cities -- Cleveland, Charlotte and Portland -- to use 
Benecol for four weeks. They will have their cholesterol tested to 
measure the results. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, J&AMP;J will point doctors to a study published in the  
New England Journal of Medicine, which found patients using Benecol 
three times a day had their LDL or bad cholesterol reduced by as 
much as 14 percent. A separate study found Take Control cut bad 
cholesterol by 7 to 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, Eckel, of the AMA, is doubtful doctors will be  
enthusiastic about the products since they can already prescribe 
cholesterol-lowering drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think doctors will doubt the value of a nutritional-related  
approach when they already have such powerful agents available,'' 
said Eckel. 
</P>
<P>
	Eckel said he doubts consumers will use enough of the spreads on  
a daily basis to get the significant cholesterol lowering results. 
Cholesterol-lowering drugs may be easier to use because patients 
only need to take them once a day, and such medicines typically can 
reduce cholesterol by more than 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Lipton and J&AMP;J acknowledge that their spreads should be used in  
conjunction with a healthy diet and exercise program to help lower 
cholesterol. 
</P>
<P>
	Benecol's price, at $4.99 for a package of 21 servings. J&AMP;J  
recommends three servings a day. Take Control sells for $3.79 for a 
package of 16 servings or a 10 ounce tub. Lipton recommends two 
servings a day. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
