<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Kosovo Air Plan Concerns US General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army's top general expressed uncertainty  
Wednesday over whether NATO's air campaign can succeed without 
ground forces -- a concern he said he made known in the weeks 
leading up to the bombing in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had adequate opportunity to make my views known and to raise  
all the issues I wanted to raise,'' Gen. Dennis Reimer said, 
referring to closed-door consultations among the Pentagon's top 
military and civilian officials leading up to NATO's decision in 
March to launch airstrikes against Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Reimer, the Army chief of staff, said in a question-and-answer  
session with reporters that the air campaign has been ``highly 
effective'' so far. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said, ``I had concerns about whether air power would do  
it by itself.'' He suggested that other members of the Joint Chiefs 
of Staff also had harbored doubts but that some members ``felt that 
air (power) might do it'' alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Reimer's comments reflect a concern publicly expressed by many  
retired military officers that the NATO campaign would have been 
more effective had ground troops not been excluded from the start. 
</P>
<P>
	Echoing the Clinton administration's view, Defense Secretary  
William Cohen said Thursday that airstrikes were the appropriate 
choice for NATO and insisted the alliance would not compromise on 
its objectives. 
</P>
<P>
	``The alliance decided to wage an air campaign to achieve our  
goals. It was the right decision then, and it is the right course 
of action now,'' Cohen told graduating midshipmen at the U.S. Naval 
Academy in Annapolis, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic ``the face of  
evil,'' Cohen said NATO's strategy was sound -- ``one that would 
inflict serious and sustained damage on Milosevic's military 
machine while minimizing the risk to our pilots and to innocent 
civilians.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Milosevic stands alone amidst the rubble and ruin of his  
failure,'' Cohen said. ``He is isolated from the world community. 
He has brought his economy to the brink of collapse, and he has 
consigned his troops to being hit harder with each passing day.'' 
Cohen made no allusion to how long the war might last. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Pentagon, Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles Wald told reporters  
that improved weather, combined with the recent arrival of more 
allied aircraft, means NATO can now sustain attacks against Serb 
targets in Kosovo 24 hours a day. That makes it harder for Serb 
troops to find sanctuary. ``And as he does move, it'll make it 
easier for us to find them and destroy them,'' Wald said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reimer, who is due to retire next month, did not explicitly say  
he argued against the air-only approach approved by President 
Clinton. He stressed that the strategic decisions had to be made by 
consensus within NATO and that by March there was no alliance 
consensus to use a ground invasion force. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only option that was available to us at that point in  
time, to NATO, I think, was the airstrikes,'' Reimer said. ``At 
that point in time, people felt the airstrikes might be sufficient 
to do the job, and they still may be. It's a matter of how much 
time is required.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about Reimer's comments, Cohen's spokesman, Kenneth Bacon,  
said the general was expressing the unanimous view of the service 
chiefs that ``it was preferable to go ahead with an air campaign 
than to sit idly by'' as Serb military and police forces expelled 
ethnic Albanians from their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Using ground troops was not an option because there was no NATO  
consensus for it -- then or now, Bacon said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Army's role in the Kosovo conflict so far has been limited  
to its much-publicized deployment of 24 Apache attack helicopters 
to neighboring Albania, where crews have trained for weeks but not 
seen combat. Reimer said he had expected the Apaches to have been 
used by now, but he believed they should remain in place in case 
they are needed either for combat or as part of a peacekeeping 
force. 
</P>
<P>
	Reimer said the need for consensus within NATO meant the optimal  
military strategy could not be employed. 
</P>
<P>
	``My view, in general terms, is that if you're going to use  
military force, using the total military force available to you is 
the right way to go,'' Reimer said. ``It works best if you have a 
good balance between'' air power and highly maneuverable ground 
forces, as the U.S. military trains to fight. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine weeks into the bombing campaign, Reimer said it remains  
unclear whether Milosevic will give in and meet NATO's demands for 
removing Serb troops from Kosovo and allowing refugees to return 
under the protection of an international military force. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know whether tomorrow he will,'' the four-star  
general said. ``The airstrikes have hurt him. I think it's hard not 
to make the case that when you get hit like that ... day and night, 
it makes you mad. ... I think it has been highly effective, the air 
campaign, in terms of not losing any airmen. Whether it actually 
will succeed in bringing him to his knees ... I just don't know 
yet, and that's the hard part about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reimer was asked his view of Britain's proposal for sending in a  
NATO ground force once Serb forces are battered into disarray, even 
without a peace agreement with Milosevic. The Clinton 
administration's position is that peacekeepers should enter Kosovo 
only if there is a peace deal or the Serb forces withdraw 
completely on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's obviously an option that ought to be, an option that  
could be looked at and assessed,'' Reimer said. ``I think it 
requires a great deal more analysis than maybe we've done at this 
particular point in time.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
