<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Greece Want Bombing Stopped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Greece called anew for a pause in the  
relentless NATO bombing of Yugoslavia on Wednesday while Russia's 
senior mediator insisted the attacks be halted until there is a 
settlement in the Kosovo conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou said a temporary  
suspension could promote diplomacy and eventual approval of a U.N. 
Security Council resolution on a settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Greece, being in the region and feeling the direct effects of  
what's going in the region, has put great emphasis in working on 
the diplomatic front and being helpful,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Resisting, but also complimenting Greece for endorsing NATO's  
demands, including safe return of ethnic Albanian refugees, 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the bombing would end 
only after Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic accepted them and 
started carrying out the demands. 
</P>
<P>
	Alluding to Greece's proposal, and other differences within the  
alliance, Albright said ``there are a variety of ideas'' among the 
diverse 19 NATO member nations. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer took up with  
Albright his government's strong objections to any consideration of 
sending NATO ground troops into the conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	But Albright said the allies remain determined that Milosevic  
meet NATO's demands for ending the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	In Moscow, Russian mediator Viktor Chernomyrdin, the principal  
diplomatic channel to Belgrade, pleaded for an immediate end to 
NATO airstrikes, now in their third month, and said the escalation 
of attacks while negotiations were under way was unprecedented. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin met with Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott  
and Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari to explore an approach to 
Milosevic, who has resisted demands that he withdraw Serb troops 
and paramilitary units from Kosovo and accept NATO and other 
peacekeepers to protect refugees returning to their homes after a 
settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is necessary to stop the airstrikes and negotiate, agree  
and at last come to a result,'' Chernomyrdin said, according to the 
ITAR-Tass news agency reported. ``At least a temporary pause is 
needed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even as diplomacy escalated, so did the intensity of NATO's  
bombardment, and it could derail the diplomatic effort, the former 
prime minister said. 
</P>
<P>
	From his vacation quarters in Yulee, Fla., meanwhile, President  
Clinton telephoned Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema of Italy, who 
also is seeking a bombing pause. 
</P>
<P>
	They discussed ``various signs that the campaign is biting,''  
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said. He told reporters he did 
not know whether Clinton tried to dissuade D'Alema or even talked 
to him about a bombing pause. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 19 NATO nations, Greece probably is the most skeptical  
that all-out bombing will bring Milosevic to his knees, reverse the 
Serb military offensive in Kosovo and clear the way for the return 
of ethnic Albanian refugees to the Serbian province. 
</P>
<P>
	Papandreou, the Greek foreign minister, is promoting a 48-hour  
pause in the bombing to give Milosevic some calm to consider a 
response to NATO's demands. He has taken his search for a 
diplomatic solution to China and Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentiment among the Greek people is hugely against the NATO  
airstrikes, according to poll, so even the measured support the 
Athens government has given the Clinton administration is 
appreciated by American officials. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Greek forces do not participate in the attacks on  
Yugoslavia, Greek officials have denounced the Serbs' treatment of 
ethnic Albanian civilians. Except for Germany, Greece provides more 
aid per capita to refugees than any other European country. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Albright and other administration officials declined  
to verify reports that Milosevic faced indictment by an 
international war crimes tribunal or to say what impact that might 
have on the pursuit of a settlement in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who has long advocated Milosevic's  
indictment, said it would be ``good news. It shows the war crimes 
tribunal means business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Specter said ``there is an abundance of evidence of atrocities  
and mass murders'' in Kosovo that can be tied directly to 
Milosevic. ``Those crimes should not go unpunished,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
