<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 16:31:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman To Play on Male Soccer Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Last year, Pete Petersen coached a team with players from 10  
countries covering four continents. So, he figures coaching a woman 
in a men's pro league can't be that much more difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll find out Friday when former U.S. national team forward  
Wendy Gebauer takes the field for his Raleigh Capital Express 
against the Boston Bulldogs in a second-division A-League match. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the first time a woman has played in a regular men's  
outdoor pro league game in the United States. A handful of women 
have played against men professionally indoors, including current 
U.S. national team midfielder Kristine Lilly. 
</P>
<P>
	Professional golfer Laura Davies made a 5-minute cameo  
appearance in 1997 for the Myrtle Beach SeaDawgs, a semi-pro team. 
</P>
<P>
	The Express, the United Soccer League -- which oversees the pro,  
semi-pro and amateur divisions below Major League Soccer -- and even 
Gebauer admit that Friday night's performance is little more than a 
marketing ploy, a publicity stunt. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have any unrealistic expectations, like I should be  
the one to win the game,'' said the 32-year-old Gebauer. ``It's 
just a sort of celebration of women's soccer with the World Cup 
coming here next month.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Petersen says he expects Gebauer, who played 26 times for the  
United States from 1987 to 1991, to start and play for about ``a 
half of a half.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She could play more, but as the captain and regular forward for  
the Raleigh Wings, Gebauer is expected to play Wednesday night 
against the Brazilian women's national team in an exhibition match; 
Friday night's game and again Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Petersen realizes soccer has an obligation to promote, and  
considering his experience last season with the A-League's 
Jacksonville Cyclones, he's just going with the flow. 
</P>
<P>
	``I grew up in Nigeria and Ghana. My dad was a Presbyterian  
missionary,'' he said. ``Last year at Jacksonville, we had the 
United Nations. I've just come full circle, dealing with so many 
different people. It's just something we adapt to in soccer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Having drawn about 300 fans a game last year, the Express, then  
called the Raleigh Flyers, was sold. This year they're attracting 
about 1,600 a game and expect to draw a capacity crowd of more than 
3,000 Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously we want to create some excitement,'' said Express  
general manager Dean Linke. 
</P>
<P>
	At 5-foot-7, 135 pounds, Gebauer has no illusions about muscling  
her way past a couple fullbacks and trying to score. She's played 
against men before, in pickup games and in scrimmages with the 
Wings against local club teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to adapt my game,'' she said. ``I'm not expecting to  
start dribbling and beat two or three defenders. I have to 
tactically read the game, which is my strength anyway, and combine 
it with my skill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Petersen knows somebody must sit to give Gebauer the start.  
</P>
<P>
	``The guys haven't rebelled against it,'' he said. ``I haven't  
gotten any reaction really, except `Only in America.''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 06:32:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Candidates Respond to China Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- First it was Kosovo, then Littleton. Now, GOP  
presidential contenders are seizing on reports of Chinese espionage 
as a hot-button campaign issue. 
</P>
<P>
	A round of potential Republican candidates pointed fingers at  
the Clinton administration Tuesday after a congressional panel 
reported that China had stolen classified information about every 
U.S. nuclear weapon for two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``Previous administrations must share in the blame, but this  
administration knew more and still chose not to take action,'' 
declared Elizabeth Dole. ``The Clinton-Gore administration needs to 
get a grip on the gravity of this crisis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., long a critic of President Clinton's  
China policy, said the report will prompt questions about why the 
administration did not do more to intervene. 
</P>
<P>
	``I find it troubling that too little action was taken too late  
by this administration, resulting in the fact that the Chinese may 
have been able to build nuclear weapons comparable to ours,'' 
McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican presidential candidates, who have touted remedies for  
school violence and criticized U.S. policy in Yugoslavia, quickly 
turned their attention to the sweeping three-volume report, which 
concluded it is ``exceptionally likely'' that Chinese spying 
continues to this day. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact is you had Kosovo, Littleton, and now you have China,  
which is quickly overcoming both of them,'' said McCain spokesman 
Howard Opinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush used the issue to offer his sharpest  
criticism yet of Clinton, saying the White House failed to take the 
reports seriously and was slow to react. ``I'd do something about 
it immediately,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush acknowledged that the problem has been going on for years,  
including the 12 years when his father was vice president and 
president. But he said he doesn't believe that gives Clinton an 
excuse. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfortunate that China has been stealing secrets during  
Carter, Reagan, Bush and Clinton. But there is only one 
administration that has been given the news; only one 
administration knew, and that's the Clinton administration. The 
interesting question is, when did they know?'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Bauer, who has made China policy a cornerstone of his  
campaign, accused the administration of failing in ``its most basic 
duty to protect our nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is time for new American leadership, it is time for a new  
foreign policy, and it is time for new congressional hearings to 
investigate who is directly responsible -- politically and 
commercially -- for endangering America's national security,'' he 
said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Forbes said the administration had demonstrated  
``incompetence, ineptitude and insincerity on a scale never before 
witnessed in the history of U.S. defense,'' making a point to 
target not just Clinton but also Vice President Al Gore, who is 
seeking the Democratic presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	The espionage report sounds a clear warning, said Rep. John  
Kasich of Ohio. ``Only time will tell if we take heed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lamar Alexander has called for an independent, blue-ribbon  
commission to ``get to the bottom of the current China mess.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire is urging creation of a Senate  
select committee to investigate Chinese espionage. ``We will get to 
the bottom of this,'' he said. ``Nobody in this Senate worth his or 
her salt should have any objection to that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also called for a congressional investigation into ``what  
went wrong and why.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the balance of power is going to shift as a result of  
this,'' Bush said. ``I think it's going to accelerate China's 
emergence as a nuclear power. And the next president and presidents 
after that are going to have to deal with that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
