<DOCNO> APW19990526.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 00:21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft To Question Gov't Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A lawyer for Microsoft Corp. will question one  
of the government's final witnesses for its antitrust trial, a 
computer expert hired to cripple the Internet browser included 
within Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Edward Felten, a computer science professor at Princeton  
University, previously testified as one of the Justice Department's 
dozen witnesses. Microsoft expected to question him again under 
oath today at the federal courthouse. 
</P>
<P>
	The government wants Felten to take the stand again next month --  
during the trial's upcoming rebuttal phase -- to rebut earlier 
testimony from Microsoft executive James Allchin. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial resumes Monday after a 13-week break.  
</P>
<P>
	Felten's deposition was the first of three scheduled this week.  
The others will take place in North Carolina and California. 
Reporters are allowed to attend under an obscure 1913 law covering 
antitrust depositions, which are normally conducted in private. 
</P>
<P>
	Allchin, a senior vice president and a top Microsoft scientist,  
argued in court previously over the benefits of the company's 
decision to include its Web browser software within its dominant 
Windows operating system. 
</P>
<P>
	But Felten, who studied the closely guarded technical blueprints  
for Windows in a court-ordered examination, believes there is no 
justification for the way Microsoft bundled its browser in Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	The government alleges that Microsoft illegally ``tied''  
consumer use of its browser to the use of Windows to undermine 
rival Netscape Communications Corp., whose Web software is 
Microsoft's biggest competitor. 
</P>
<P>
	Felten's testimony is important because Microsoft contends that  
Windows and its browser are so closely integrated to make it 
impossible to remove the Web software without crippling Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	But Felten showed the judge how he was able to modify some files  
to prevent Microsoft's Internet software from starting up in all 
but a few instances. Since Felten last testified, he's been 
improving his technique. 
</P>
<P>
	Felten's last deposition with Microsoft -- conducted in October  
without reporters in the room -- was painfully arduous, as reflected 
by 238 pages of recently released transcripts. 
</P>
<P>
	In one tedious exchange, Felten and Microsoft lawyer David  
Heiner argued whether ``Internet browser'' was technically 
synonymous with ``Web browser.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think when people use the term 'Internet browser,' they  
typically mean a Web browser, but that's not a term I myself like 
to use,'' said Felten. That provoked Heiner into showing him that 
the government itself called the software an ``Internet browser'' 
in its lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	And when Heiner pressed Felten whether he considers Windows also  
to be a type of Web browser -- which, on one level, is an argument 
over semantics -- the two argued until Justice Department lawyer 
Melvin Schwarz threatened to end the questioning. 
</P>
<P>
	``You are taxing my patience, and soon we will end the  
deposition if you can't move on,'' Schwarz said. ``I think you know 
exactly what his answer is. It's entirely argumentative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heiner didn't let up, and Schwarz accused him a few minutes  
later of harassing Felton. 
</P>
<P>
	``... And don't laugh, or we're out of here!'' Schwarz said.  
</P>
<P>
	``You are at risk of obstructing this deposition,'' Heiner  
answered a few minutes later. ``This is a very important deposition 
in this case, and it relates to matters as to which the Department 
of Justice has been obfuscating for nine months. We're going to 
need to spend some time on some of these questions.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 18:51:31 </DATE_TIME>
