<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASCAR To Open New Mechanics School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- The governing body for stock car racing  
announced today it's expanding into the education business. 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR is forming a partnership with Universal Technical  
Institute to build a school in the Charlotte area to train people 
to become automotive technicians. 
</P>
<P>
	The NASCAR Technical Institute is to open in 2001 on a  
yet-to-be-determined site. Officials say the school should 
initially be able to accommodate 1,800 students. 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR and UTI's long-term agreement calls for the establishment  
of multiple schools around the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Courses at NASCAR Technical Institute are to focus on training  
core skills needed to succeed as an automotive technician, with 
students also getting instruction on how to apply the information 
to a NASCAR-oriented environment. 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR Tech should meet what Mike Helton, the sanctioning body's  
senior vice president, called a continuous need for qualified 
mechanics. 
</P>
<P>
	``The more supply you have, the bigger the pool is, the better  
off you are,'' Helton said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to being a partner in NASCAR Tech, UTI will offer  
six-week NASCAR electives to students at its six other campuses. 
The first class will be offered in spring 2000 at the UTI campus in 
Houston. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	FUND GROWS: There was an unusual contribution Wednesday to a  
fund set up by Lowe's Motor Speedway at Charlotte for victims of a 
fatal spectator accident at the track earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Trab Crews, a driver in NASCAR's Goody's Dash Series, collected  
$750 during an open house held at his race team's shop in his 
hometown of Leoma, Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	More than $35,000 has been donated to the fund, set up after  
three spectators were killed and eight injured when hit by flying 
debris from a wreck at an Indy Racing League event on May 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the donations have come from other spectators who asked  
that their ticket refunds from the race be targeted for the fund. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we heard what had happened at Lowe's we felt we needed to  
do something, because when something like this happens it affects 
the entire community of racing,'' Crews said. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	FAVRE'S NEW VENTURE: Green Bay Packers quarterback Brett Favre  
was on hand at the speedway Wednesday to announce his partnership 
with Winston Cup driver Dale Jarrett. 
</P>
<P>
	The two are forming the Jarrett-Favre Driving Adventure, a  
business that will allow people to ride in or drive Winston Cup 
cars at North Carolina Speedway in Rockingham, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Packages start at $75 for a three-lap passenger ride and go to  
$1,450 for four sessions as a driver. 
</P>
<P>
	The venture is to open in July.  
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	BY THE NUMBERS: Bobby Labonte's Coca-Cola 600 pole-winning speed  
of 185.230 mph Wednesday night was an event record, surpassing the 
mark of 184.300 set by Jeff Gordon two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The track qualifying record is a 185.759, set by Ward Burton in  
October 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon, winner of the previous five Coca-Cola 600 poles, was  
10th-fastest Wednesday with a 184.162. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon attributed his relatively slow speed to the fact that he  
was the fifth of 52 drivers to make qualifying runs in the 
early-evening session. The track generally produces higher speeds 
as dusk approaches. 
</P>
<P>
	``At Charlotte you've got to draw a late number to qualify on  
the pole,'' Gordon said. ``This place gets faster as it gets darker 
and cools down.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
