<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> La. Candidate's Grandson Missing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CASCADE LOCKS, Ore. (AP) -- Despite an impending runoff election  
that will decide whether he goes to Congress, former Louisiana Gov. 
Dave Treen says he will stay in Oregon until his missing grandson 
is found. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 30 people combed the steep, wooded trails and  
waterfalls in the Columbia Gorge on Tuesday, searching for 
20-year-old Jason Neville, who failed to return from a solo hike. 
The search was to resume this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Treen, 70, faces a runoff Saturday back in Louisiana against  
fellow Republican David Vitter to succeed former Rep. Bob 
Livingston. Treen canceled all campaign appearances Tuesday and 
flew to Oregon with his daughter Jennifer Neville, the missing 
hiker's mother. 
</P>
<P>
	``The campaign is not on my mind at this point,'' Treen said  
Tuesday, standing near the trailhead where his grandson began his 
trip. ``There's nothing I would not do or give up to find Jason.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Treen and Vitter were the top two vote-getters in a May 1  
primary in which former Ku Klux Klan leader David Duke finished 
third. 
</P>
<P>
	Neville, a student at Louisiana State University, had taken time  
off from college to work for AmeriCorps, the domestic equivalent of 
the Peace Corps, teaching poor children in Portland to read. 
</P>
<P>
	He set out alone Thursday evening on the Eagle Creek trail, one  
of Oregon's most popular hiking routes, near the river town of 
Cascade Locks, about 40 miles east of Portland. Officials said he 
wanted to be by himself in the wilderness when he turned 20 at 
midnight Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The worst-case scenario is that he took a fall,'' said Stan  
Hinatsu, a Forest Service spokesman. ``The best-case scenario is 
that he's sitting on a trail somewhere, disoriented and not sure 
which way to go.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
