<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricanes To Extend Coach's Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Paul Maurice will be rewarded with at least  
a three-year contract extension after leading the Carolina 
Hurricanes' franchise to the NHL playoffs for the first time since 
1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Details of the multi-year contract will be finalized by general  
manager Jim Rutherford and Maurice within the next few weeks, team 
spokesman Chris Brown said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Maurice, 32, is the youngest head coach in the NHL, but ranks  
third in tenure with the same club. At $300,000 a season, he is 
also one of the lowest paid coaches in the league. However, the new 
contract is expected to pay him around $500,000 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``There won't be any negotiations,'' said Maurice, who has no  
agent. ``I'll be more than happy to sign it. I've been here a long 
time and there are other considerations other than trying to get as 
much money as you possibly can. This is an opportunity to work with 
some great people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maurice, 128-143-45 in four seasons, likely would have been  
fired had the Hurricanes not made the playoffs for the first time 
since the early '90s, when the team played in Hartford, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	But Maurice and his coaching staff implemented a new trapping  
system in 1998-99 that allowed the team to capture the Southeast 
Division with a 34-30-18 record. The team was in first place for 
175 days out of the 192-day schedule and Carolina's 86 points was 
the second highest in the 20 years of the franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has always been some sort of potential for failure,''  
said Maurice, referring to the team's move to North Carolina and 
subsequent 160-mile round trip to Greensboro for home games for two 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody said I was going to get fired all the time. That was  
the easy part. I've done a good job of blocking that out and 
learning how to handle it to the point that I don't think about it 
either way now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maurice has been a part of owner Peter Karmanos' Compuware  
hockey organization for 14 years, joining the then-Hartford Whalers 
as an assistant coach in June 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never met anybody who can put his finger on a problem as  
quick as he can, and he fixes it as quick as he can,'' Rutherford 
said of Maurice. ``He's not vocal about it, he doesn't rant and 
rave about it, he doesn't do it through the media, but he does it 
through the appropriate character players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rutherford said Maurice was able to hold the team together  
through some serious injury problems, especially on defense late in 
the regular season and through a 4-2 series loss to Boston in the 
opening round of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The three teams that went through the injuries we went  
through, they got buried. We didn't,'' Rutherford said. ``I think 
that is a real credit to him. He's earned the right to coach this 
team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of Maurice's failures this past season was a power-play unit  
that scored 11 percent of the time -- last in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't hold the power play failures against the coach. I  
can't do that,'' Rutherford said. ``It's a matter of we feel the 
players out there should have gotten it done.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
