<HEADLINE> Detroit P.D. Has Squares To Spare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- There's plenty of TP for the P.D.  
</P>
<P>
	An alleged toilet paper shortage at Detroit police stations  
prompted a radio station to donate rolls on Wednesday, but city 
officials say there's no need. There are squares to spare. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're somebody in need at a particular time, and you're  
sitting there, it's an emergency to you, but we just have not been 
able to detect that there hasn't been toilet paper,'' said Greg 
Bowens, spokesman for Mayor Dennis Archer. 
</P>
<P>
	City Council Member Key Everett said Tuesday the situation is an  
example of a supply problem throughout city departments caused by 
Detroit's new computer system. Bowens said that was news to him. 
</P>
<P>
	As word of the shortage spread Wednesday, officers in one  
precinct called a radio station in search of donations and received 
420 rolls. The precinct never called building maintenance first to 
request toilet paper, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sgt. Roslyn Beard said: ``I've been carrying my own since I was  
a little girl ... My mama taught me that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
