<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Akosua Busia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Spend just a few moments chatting with  
actress Akosua Busia, and it's enough to chase away the image of 
the tragic African torture victim she played this season on ``ER.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even the message on her telephone answering machine is buoyant.  
</P>
<P>
	``Faith is not a jump in the dark, but a walk into the light,''  
says Busia's lilting voice, a combination of her native Ghana and 
the trio of countries (England, Switzerland and Mexico) where she 
was educated. 
</P>
<P>
	In conversation, she leans toward the wry. Asked if publicity  
about her royal roots is accurate, Busia replied: ``I'm a princess 
of a small island just on the outskirts of Scotland.'' OK, it's a 
joke, she admits. Her late father, Kofi Abrefa Busia, was an 
Ashanti chief and a prime minister of Ghana. 
</P>
<P>
	If Busia is enjoying life, it's easy to see why.  
</P>
<P>
	Her first film was a cushy gig with Michael Caine. She gained  
the role of Nettie in ``The Color Purple'' not long after braving 
Hollywood. Her acting career was interrupted, but for a very good 
reason: to give more attention to her infant daughter, now 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Busia did manage to combine professional creativity with  
motherhood. She is working on the screenplay adaptation of her 
novel -- about a man's quest for love and belonging -- and is 
completing her second book. She also contributed to the screenplay 
for the film version of Toni Morrison's ``Beloved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Busia's appearance on ``ER'' marked her return to acting, just a  
bit shy of her self-imposed two-year moratorium. She was attracted 
by the script about a Nigerian husband and wife who were victims of 
political oppression. 
</P>
<P>
	The chance to appear opposite the handsome Djimon Hounsou  
(``Amistad'') also was a draw, Busia admitted with a laugh. ``He's 
a wonderful man. A wonderful actor, too,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	1. Does being a princess have cachet in America?  
</P>
<P>
	Busia: It means nothing. It doesn't even mean a good table at a  
restaurant. And I'm really upset about that (laughs). 
</P>
<P>
	2. How did you decide to become an actor?  
</P>
<P>
	Busia: I really got into acting by accident. My father was the  
first black man in history to go to University College, Oxford. All 
my brothers and sisters went there. I was visiting and heard they 
were doing 'Romeo and Juliet' in the playhouse at Oxford. I was 
doing it at the time for my O-level exam (equivalent to junior high 
school), and I auditioned for it because I thought it was a great 
play. They cast me as Juliet. I had a great time, and then I found 
out people got paid. I could not believe it. 
</P>
<P>
	3. You left the Central School of Speech and Drama in London  
early to do your first film. What was it? 
</P>
<P>
	Busia: 'Ashanti.' Do not rush out and rent it. But I had a  
fabulous time making it. It was the most lavish film to date that 
I've done, so I got a horribly false impression of producers. It 
was with Michael Caine, who was wonderful, and was shot in Kenya 
and Israel. They shot for three months and I worked for nine days. 
Never to be repeated in the history of my career. 
</P>
<P>
	4. What brought you to the United States?  
</P>
<P>
	Busia: I came to America on a whim. I had done a miniseries in  
England and was offered another that was much the same. I said, 
'No, I'm going to America to make a Spielberg movie.' I'd like to 
say it was premonition, but that would be a lie. It was just a 
symbol of Americanism. ... Two months later, I got the role of 
Nettie in 'The Color Purple.' My English agent was saying, 'I can't 
believe it.' 
</P>
<P>
	5. What are you working on post-''ER''?  
</P>
<P>
	Busia: I am so late on my screenplay and novel I can't even  
describe how much I need to sit myself at a computer. My first 
novel was 'The Seasons of Beentoo Blackbird' -- 'beentoo' is a 
phrase used in Ghana for a person who's been around the world: been 
to Paris, been to London. 
</P>
<P>
	5 1/2. Do you consider yourself primarily an actress or a writer?  
</P>
<P>
	Busia: It took me a long time to say I was a writer. Calling  
oneself an actress is nothing, but calling oneself a writer ... 
After my first book came out and got comments and attention, my 
sister said, 'Finally, you can call yourself a writer.' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
