<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Chiquita Lawyer To Stand Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- A former Chiquita attorney will stand trial on  
charges he gave the banana company's voice-mail codes to a 
reporter. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Ann Marie Tracey cleared the way for the trial Tuesday  
when she refused a request by George Ventura to dismiss five of the 
10 felony charges against him. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, now an attorney in Salt Lake City, is accused of  
providing the secret codes that allowed a reporter for The 
Cincinnati Enquirer to gain access to the voice-mail system of the 
Cincinnati-based Chiquita Brands International Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura's attorneys had argued that five charges of intercepting  
or procuring another to intercept a wire communication did not 
match the crimes he is alleged to have committed. But the judge 
concluded that the law's definition of ``interception'' also would 
apply to illegally accessing a voice-mail system. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura also faces five counts of unauthorized access to  
computer systems. He is scheduled for trial July 6, and could be 
sentenced to 12 1/2 years in prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say Ventura provided the codes to reporter Michael  
Gallagher, who quoted the voice mails in articles he wrote for the 
Enquirer last year about Chiquita's business practices. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper later renounced the series, fired Gallagher and  
paid Chiquita more than $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallagher faces sentencing that could range from 2 1/2 years in  
prison to probation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
