<DOCNO> APW19990526.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 17:01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Different Plans for Fenway Emerge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- State House Speaker Thomas Finneran hosted a group  
of preservationists today who want to save Fenway Park, while 
baseball commissioner Bud Selig came to town and pushed for a new 
stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Selig, speaking at a press conference before meeting with  
members of a Red Sox fan club, said renovation was not a practical 
option. 
</P>
<P>
	``Renovation has not worked anywhere. It can't work,'' he said,  
adding that he liked the team's plan. ``They've done what you try 
to do in baseball. You preserve the history and tradition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The preservationists said Finneran gave them a sympathetic ear.  
</P>
<P>
	``He was open to seeing our plan and hearing more about it,''  
said Albert Rex, a member of the board of directors of Save Fenway 
Park! ``He left us with the sense that there would be a public 
dialogue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Finneran said he had no preference yet as to whether Fenway Park  
should be renovated or a new stadium built. 
</P>
<P>
	``The intent is to be pro-active, not reactive,'' he said.  
``We're open and receptive to any fair proposal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Save Fenway Park! has an architect, Charles P. Hagenah, who has  
drawn up plans to renovate the existing facility by adding seats, 
luxury boxes and concession areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the week, Save Fenway Park! representatives met with  
John Harrington, the team's chief executive officer. But Red Sox 
officials have said they don't think saving the park is feasible. 
</P>
<P>
	Save Fenway Park! says its plan would increase the number of  
seats to 44,000, about the same as the new stadium proposed by the 
team. The preservationist group would also build 73 luxury suites, 
compared to 100 for the team's proposed facility. 
</P>
<P>
	The existing park, opened in 1912, has just 33,000 seats. The  
team believes its new park will fit into the neighborhood and 
maintain the essence of the current park. It will also turn 
portions of the old field -- including the Green Monster left-field 
wall -- into a public park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
