<DOCNO> APW19990526.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 16:21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds' Neagle Out 4-6 Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Surgery was ruled out Wednesday for Cincinnati  
Reds starter Denny Neagle, who's on the disabled list for the 
second time this season with weakness in the back of his shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. James Andrews examined Neagle in Birmingham, Ala., on  
Wednesday and concurred with seven other doctors that a 
strengthening program is needed, not an operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Neagle will be out for four to six weeks as he rebuilds his  
shoulder, general manager Jim Bowden said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dr. Andrews agreed completely with the other doctors'  
opinions,'' Bowden said. ``We hope that after the All-Star break 
he'll be ready to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neagle will remain in Birmingham for a couple of days to begin a  
strengthening program. He'll work on building up the muscles for 
two or three weeks and then resume throwing. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds got Neagle from Atlanta last November in a five-player  
deal that sent Bret Boone to the Braves. Neagle had won at least 16 
games in each of the past three seasons and was expected to become 
the Reds' top starter. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he pulled thigh muscles during the first full-squad  
workout and weakness was detected in the back of his left shoulder 
during routine testing. 
</P>
<P>
	He went on a strengthening program, opened the season on the  
disabled list and was activated April 21. He struggled in six 
starts with the Reds, going 0-3 with an 8.17 earned run average. 
Opponents hit .340 off him. 
</P>
<P>
	Magnetic resonance imaging tests found no problem with the  
shoulder other than the weakness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
