<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mostly Higher; Dow Up 58.99 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher today as buyers  
cautiously returned to a turbulent market following the biggest 
losing streak since late March. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was dow  
was up 58.99 at 10,590.08. It had been up as much as 105 points in 
morning trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Going into today's session, the Dow had fallen four straight  
sessions, including a combined 298-point drop in the past two days, 
and is off 5 percent from its May 13 record of 11,107.19. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market was oversold,'' said Tony Dwyer, chief equity  
strategist at Ladenburg Thalmann &AMP; Co. ``It's ready for a bounce.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators mostly higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was up 10.66 at 1,295.06. The technology-dominated Nasdaq 
composite index was up 10.75 at 2,391.65 in a session that saw it 
repeatedly turn into negative territory. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks have sustained the worst losses recently, as  
concerns about potentially higher interest rates draw investors 
away from the high-priced shares that have fed the market's massive 
gains. The Nasdaq index has tumbled 10 percent from its all-time 
record of 2,652.05, set April 26. A decline of 10 percent or more 
is viewed as a ``correction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Today, several industry leaders continued to languish. Intel,  
which plans to unveil a new chip design later today, dipped 3/8 to 
52 1/2. Computer seller Dell fell 15/16 to 33 5/8. 
</P>
<P>
	The market jitters and the move away from Internet stocks  
created a poor climate for the initial public sale of DLJ Direct, 
the online brokerage unit of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc. Its 
shares were priced at 20 and rose to 26 1/8, a modest showing for a 
Web-related new issue. DLJ's debut mirrored the IPO Tuesday of 
barnesandnoble.com, which rose 27 percent in its first day of 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Several sectors rebounded today. Drug stocks were higher, led by  
Bristol Myers Squibb, which gained 1 7/8 to 66 5/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Banking and financial stocks also rose. Morgan Stanley Dean  
Witter rose 1 13/16 to 90 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 403.9 million 
shares at midday, well ahead of Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 3.34 at 620.68, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 0.18 at 779.02. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:42:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 171.07 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rebounded from a four-day slump Wednesday  
as the banking and Internet shares that faltered earlier this week 
roared back. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose 171.07 points, a rise of  
1.6 percent, to close at 10,702.16. At one point late in the 
session, the Dow was up 190. 
</P>
<P>
	In a single, volatile session, the index of blue-chip stocks  
wiped out more than half its losses since Friday. Four straight 
losses had pushed the Dow 5 percent below its May 13 record of 
11,107.19. After Wednesday's rally, the Dow is 3.6 percent off the 
all-time high. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader indicators rose, recovering early losses. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 gained 20.36 to 1,304.76, and the technology-heavy 
Nasdaq composite index rose 46.28 to 2,427.18. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the market was ready for a bounce, as the U.S.  
economy remains strong and the outlook for corporate profits 
remains rosy, at least for the next quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Conditions are quite good,'' said Tony Dwyer, chief equity  
strategist at Ladenburg Thalmann &AMP; Co. ``IBM is solid, and the 
financials are very strong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IBM contributed heavily to the Dow's gains, soaring 15 1/16, or  
by 6.8 percent, to 236 1/4. Big Blue drew attention as a 2-for-1 split 
took effect after the market closed Wednesday. Stock splits often 
prompt a rally, as investors expect the lower price to entice more 
buyers, but analysts were reluctant to pin IBM's gains solely on 
the split. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, market watchers said, IBM's stock was unfairly battered  
in recent sessions, as the entire technology sector faltered. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks were hit hard as concerns about potentially  
higher interest rates drew investors away from the high-priced 
shares. Through Tuesday, the Nasdaq index had tumbled 10 percent 
from its all-time record of 2,652.05, set April 26, meeting the 
conventional definition of a market correction. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, several industry leaders continued to languish.  
Intel, which unveiled a new chip design, fell 1 3/16 to close at 51 
11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	But many Internet-related shares resumed their dizzying gains.  
Yahoo rose 13 15/16 to 140 7/8, and America Online rose 5 5/16 to 120 
5/16. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those stocks were hurt by panic selling,'' Dwyer said. ``They  
were ready to come back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DLJ Direct, the online brokerage unit of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;  
Jenrette Inc., rose steadily in its initial public offering. The 
shares were priced at 20 and rose to 30, a far cry from the 
triple-digit gains of previous Internet IPOs but better than the 
Tuesday debut of barnesandnoble.com. 
</P>
<P>
	The online bookseller had disappointed some traders with a  
modest 27 percent gain in its first day of trading. On Wednesday, 
however, barnesandnoble.com tacked on an additional 2 15/16 to 25 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Banking and financial stocks, which have been hit by concerns  
over interest rates and the Year 2000 computer bug, surged as old 
merger rumors hit the market. Merrill Lynch, often mentioned as a 
takeover target, soared 10 5/16 to 78 11/16. Chase Manhattan Bank, 
the rumored suitor, rose 1 9/16 to 75 3/8. Both companies denied the 
rumors. 
</P>
<P>
	A. Marshall Acuff, equity strategist at Salomon Smith Barney,  
said investors were merely revisiting the stocks that fed market 
gains earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The stocks that have been hit pretty hard are rebounding,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Benefitting from a steady gain in oil prices this week, most  
petroleum companies rose. Mobil, up 3 1/4 to 103 1/16, paced the 
sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's market took a measure of support from a Commerce  
Department report that factory orders for big-ticket manufactured 
goods fell an unexpectedly sharp 2.3 percent last month. The figure 
offered new evidence that the economy is not overheated and cooled 
inflation fears. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet analysts were far from enthusiastic about the rally on Wall  
Street. Aside from IBM's outsized gains and strength from the 
financial companies, most Dow components were fairly flat. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the healthiest of rallies,'' Acuff said, noting that  
declining stocks outnumbered advancers on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE consolidated volume totaled 1.06 billion shares, compared  
to 992.98 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 7.50 to 624.84, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 3.82 to 782.66. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.96 to 435.41. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.1 percent.  
Germany's DAX index rose 0.3 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 fell 0.2 
percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 0.1 percent higher. 


</P>
</TEXT>
