<DOCNO> APW19990526.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 14:51:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russia May Delay Space Station Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Because of Russia's chronic money  
crunch, space shuttle Discovery's flight could end up being the 
only trip to the new international space station this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Discovery was set to blast off Thursday morning on a 10-day  
mission with more than 4,300 pounds of spare parts, cranes, tools, 
laptop computers and clothes to be used by the first permanent 
crew. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, an unmanned Russian rocket is scheduled to launch  
the next piece of the space station, a service module containing 
life-support systems. Then, NASA's space shuttle Atlantis is 
supposed to follow in December with more equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	However, everything is on hold until the Russian component --  
already more than 1 1/2 years behind -- is in orbit. And many question 
whether the Russians can finish building and testing it by 
November, given the country's economic crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it does fly in November, maybe it shouldn't,'' said James  
Oberg, an independent consultant on Russian space affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Oberg pointed to problems with the Russian-built component that  
was launched last fall. Its batteries are not charging properly; 
Discovery's crew will replace 18 electrical meters to try to solve 
the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``The failures that have occurred, the problems with the battery  
charge, are inexcusable,'' Oberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA and the Russian Space Agency already are debating what to  
do if something goes wrong and the service module, once launched, 
cannot dock with the two station pieces already in orbit. 
</P>
<P>
	An emergency mission would have to be launched, probably within  
three weeks, said Tommy Holloway, space station program manager. 
The big question is: Who would go? 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a subject that we're working with the Russians today,  
and tomorrow, and probably the day after tomorrow,'' Holloway said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Holloway's predecessor, Randy Brinkley, said before leaving NASA  
a month ago that he and others should have paid more attention to 
political and economic events in Russia and never allowed the 
Russians to supply a critical component so early in assembly. That 
way, he said, any Russian delays would not have disrupted 
everything. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the best of circumstances, NASA figures it will take five  
years -- and some 40 U.S. and Russian launches -- to complete the 
space station. 
</P>
<P>
	On this mission, Discovery's seven astronauts will not only  
unload supplies, they will also fix broken U.S. and Russian 
equipment and install mufflers to reduce the noise caused by 
clattering Russian-made fans. Two of them will also take a 
spacewalk to attach one crane and parts of another to the outside 
of the station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0046 </DOCNO>
