<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Police Torture Case Nears End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The judge in the city's police torture case  
rejected motions for a mistrial Wednesday and told the jury that 
the trial would go on without the officer who pleaded guilty the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Eugene Nickerson explained to the jurors  
that Justin Volpe's plea of guilty to violating the civil rights of 
a Haitian immigrant shouldn't be used as evidence in determining 
the guilt or innocence of the remaining four officers charged in 
the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes earlier, with the jury out of the courtroom, two defense  
attorneys had asked Nickerson to declare a mistrial. They said the 
jury, knowing that the lead defendant was guilty, would assume the 
worst of the remaining defendants. Nickerson rejected the argument 
without comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe, 27, was the central figure in a case that has shocked the  
city and sparked demonstrations against police brutality. 
</P>
<P>
	After being faced with damaging testimony against him from four  
fellow officers, Volpe admitted that he violated Abner Louima's 
civil rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe admitted ramming a stick into the handcuffed victim's  
rectum, pulling it out and putting it up to his face to humiliate 
him. He said he was angry because he believed, mistakenly, that 
Louima had punched him while police tried to quell a disturbance 
outside a nightclub on Aug. 9, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe, who was dismissed from the force Tuesday, is in federal  
custody awaiting sentencing, which has not been scheduled. He faces 
up to life in prison, although the judge can impose a lesser term. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the remaining defendants, Officer Charles Schwarz is accused  
of holding down Louima, 32, in the bathroom assault, which caused 
severe internal injuries. Schwarz, and Officers Thomas Wiese and 
Thomas Bruder also are charged with beating Louima in a patrol car 
en route to the police precinct after his arrest on false charges 
he punched Volpe; Sgt. Michael Bellomo, their supervisor, is 
charged with covering up the incident. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, jurors heard testimony from laboratory experts who  
said DNA found in the bathroom was probably that of Louima. The 
prosecution, which has two remaining witnesses, was expected to 
rest its case on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 17:11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House GOP Try To Protect Surpluses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans, trying to protect their  
party's flanks on a volatile social issue, pushed through 
legislation Wednesday that would put new obstacles in the way of 
spending government surpluses that come from Social Security taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Workers should have the confidence that the money they pay  
into Social Security and Medicare is used only for Social Security 
and Medicare, not bigger government or new spending,'' said House 
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP legislation passed 416 to 12. Most House Democrats voted  
for it, saying they believe it won't do much to help the nation's 
retirement system, but it couldn't hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although this bill will probably not make things any worse, it  
won't make them any better,'' said Rep. Joseph Moakley, D-Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	A stricter version of the legislation has been stalled in the  
Senate by Democrats' objections and faces a veto threat from the 
Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's budget surplus, expected to be $80 billion to $110  
billion, will come entirely from Social Security taxes. Under 
current projections, income tax surpluses aren't anticipated until 
after 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The House-passed legislation would forbid Congress and the  
president from including Social Security surpluses in their 
budgeting for other programs or for tax cuts. Instead, it would 
have to be used to pay down the government's debt to private 
bondholders -- something economists say could help promote economic 
growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Separate votes on the House floor would be required for most  
exceptions. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers could tap the money to help prepare Social Security or  
Medicare, the health insurance program for the elderly, for a cash 
shortfall expected after baby boomers, now in middle age, retire. 
</P>
<P>
	Skepticism has been growing, however, that Congress can pass a  
full-scale overhaul of the retirement programs in the politically 
charged year and a half before the 2000 presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP drive to formally wall off Social Security surpluses is,  
in part, a fallback plan to counter Democrats' accusations that 
Republicans want to spend money that could help shore up the 
nation's retirement system on tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Public opinion polls, including polling by the Republican  
National Committee, indicate that Americans, by a double-digit 
margin, consider Democrats more likely than Republicans to make the 
right decisions about Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, RNC polling found that legislation to  
safeguard Social Security surplus dollars offered some cover, 
commanding strong support, with 87 percent of Americans in favor. 
</P>
<P>
	But it is unclear whether the GOP strategy can succeed.  
</P>
<P>
	A Senate version of the legislation is opposed by Democrats  
there and by the Clinton administration. It would lower the 
government's statutory debt limit, something administration 
officials say could hinder borrowing flexibility the Treasury 
Department needs in times of economic trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	And already, the conflict in Yugoslavia, with its $9  
billion-and-growing price tag, suggests that lawmakers are sure to 
face necessary -- or at least tempting -- exceptions to any new 
spending restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Democrats are challenging Republicans to set aside  
even more money, from expected income tax surpluses, for Medicare. 
The Clinton administration wants about $700 billion over 15 years 
for Medicare -- close to the same amount Republicans have budgeted 
for tax cuts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 04:12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Family: Wrestler Leery About Stunt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Professional wrestler Owen Hart was  
leery about the flashy stunt he was supposed to perform to land 
inside the ring, but was convinced to do it anyway, his family 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	``They put you into compromising positions where they let you  
know you have no choice,'' father Stu Hart said Tuesday of the pro 
wrestling circuits. 
</P>
<P>
	Owen Hart, known as the Blue Blazer, died Sunday after plunging  
70 feet, hitting his head on the padded metal coupling that holds 
the ring's ropes together. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said Tuesday the fall may have been caused when  
his elaborate, feathered costume caught on a quick-release cord as 
he was being lowered from the Kemper Arena rafters during a show. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is believed at this point in time that the quick release  
was activated. Either it was snagged on his clothes or he pulled it 
too soon,'' police spokesman Floyd Mitchell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart, 34, who wrestled for the World Wrestling Federation, had  
planned to descend 90 feet into the ring in a stunt he had done 
before and had practiced at the arena hours earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said Hart may have lost his balance while preparing for  
his drop and somehow activated the release. Police plan to perform 
strength testing on the equipment he was wearing, Capt. Jerry 
Gallagher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart had done the stunt before, and his widow, Martha Hart, told  
NBC's ``Today'' show on Tuesday that she was never comfortable with 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``This particular one we did discuss,'' Mrs. Hart said. ``I had  
told him that I didn't thin k he should do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other members of Hart's family members attacked the sport's  
increasing reliance on flashy, can-you-top-this stunts. 
</P>
<P>
	What once was a small-time regional show circuit has become  
dominated by two national organizations -- the WWF and World 
Championship Wrestling -- which rely on dangerous gimmicks for 
increased TV ratings and revenues, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a campaign to outdo each other,'' said his brother,  
Smith Hart, 50. ``There is no respect for the sport anymore. There 
used to be (wrestling) heroes for children. I don't see any 
heroes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All seven Hart boys followed their father, a former Olympic  
wrestler, into the sport as amateurs and professionals. Owen Hart 
was the youngest member of the prominent family. 
</P>
<P>
	WCW President Eric Bischoff said Tuesday that criticism of  
wrestling after the accident is a ``knee-jerk, uneducated reaction 
to a very tragic incident.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 17:05:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Gets No Break From Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla. (AP) -- President Clinton played a round of golf and  
went biking with the first lady Wednesday on a secluded plantation 
in northern Florida. But it wasn't all fun in the sun for the 
commander in chief. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton received his daily security briefing on the Yugoslavia  
campaign, called the Italian prime minister and named Nobel 
laureate Elie Wiesel a special envoy to Macedonia to check up on 
refugees from Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``He will stay in touch, as you've already seen today,'' White  
House press secretary Joe Lockhart said. ``But it's important from 
time to time to take a chance to get away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any president vacationing during a military conflict opens  
himself to questions about priorities. President Bush was 
criticized for taking two weeks off to golf and fish during the 
build up to the Persian Gulf War. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush told reporters as he headed to his summer home in  
Kennebunkport, Maine, in 1991 that ``what you don't want to do is 
appear to be held hostage in the White House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton's vacation site offered one advantage over the coast  
of Maine: there was little chance any media pictures would be taken 
of his leisurely pursuits on the densely wooded, 7,500 acre White 
Oak Plantation located 20 miles north of Jacksonville. 
</P>
<P>
	The vacation was planned long before release of a report on  
China's espionage was released Tuesday by a special committee led 
by Reps. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., and Norman Dicks, D-Wash. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jim Nicholson, the Republican National Committee chairman,  
said through a spokesman that it was appropriate Clinton was 
vacationing at a nature preserve: ``He's joining the ostriches with 
his head in the sand the day after the Cox committee exposed the 
worst case of espionage in U.S. history under his watch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House has stressed that most of the spying detailed in  
the report occurred in the 1980s, when Republicans held the 
presidency, and Lockhart noted that Clinton spoke to the report in 
Texas on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's any worry on our part about the  
appearances here,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton arrived Tuesday at  
the private wildlife conservation area inhabited by giraffes, 
cheetahs and white rhinos. The Clintons were traveling without 
daughter Chelsea, who is still in school at Stanford University. 
The president's Labrador, Buddy, did make the journey. 
</P>
<P>
	White Oak is located off an unmarked dirt road about 20 miles  
north of Jacksonville and sports a nine-hole golf course and a 
swimming pool, as well as 14 dwellings. The Clintons were staying 
at Roseland, a two-story, cedar paneled, five-bedroom house. 
</P>
<P>
	``It offers it all, with the ability to get away from what  
they're normally faced with on a work day,'' Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	The president brought a bagful of books to help pass the time,  
including ``Sudden Mischief'' by Robert Parker and Carl Hiassen's 
``Lucky You.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton spoke with Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alemma for  
about 30 minutes on Tuesday night about the NATO campaign against 
the forces of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	After receiving his briefing Wednesday morning from a National  
Security Council staffer traveling with him, he called Wiesel, a 
Holocaust survivor and author, and asked him to travel to Macedonia 
on May 31. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants to get a sense of the conditions there and have a  
chance to talk to some of the refugees about the conditions on the 
ground,'' Lockhart said. Wiesel will report back directly to 
Clinton after his trip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
