<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Murder Charges for Florida Mom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- An elderly woman accused in her daughter's  
shooting will not face a murder charge following the victim's 
decision to be taken off life support, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shirley Egan, who suffers from emphysema and is blind in one  
eye, already is charged with attempted murder for the shooting of 
Georgette Smith. Ms. Egan, 68, could have been charged with murder 
after her daughter died May 19 when her ventilator was removed at 
Ms. Smith's own request. 
</P>
<P>
	But State Attorney Lawson Lamar cited Ms. Egan's health and her  
closeness with her daughter for his decision not to pursue the 
higher charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan's ``deteriorating health and her relationship to the  
victim, do not ... provide an appropriate circumstance for me to 
exercise my discretion by charging murder in this case,'' Lamar 
said in a statement Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Wesley, a lawyer for Ms. Egan, said Ms. Smith did not want  
her mother charged with murder. 
</P>
<P>
	``This takes a burden off her,'' he said of his client. ``It  
shows dignity and respect for the wishes of Georgette Smith.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan is accused of shooting her 42-year-old daughter in  
March after overhearing a discussion about putting her in a nursing 
home. 
</P>
<P>
	The bullet that struck Ms. Smith in the neck tore through her  
spinal cord, leaving her unable to speak without effort, incapable 
of swallowing and unable to control her bladder. She was fed 
through a tube and ran a high risk of pneumonia, infections, ulcers 
and bedsores. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan supported her daughter's decision to be taken off life  
support, but her attorney fought it to avoid the murder charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan didn't mean to shoot her daughter and didn't want to  
see her suffer, Wesley said. 
</P>
<P>
	She remains in jail with a trial date set for Aug. 9.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
