<HEADLINE> Wounded Ga. Student Leaves Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- The most seriously injured victim of last  
week's shootings at Heritage High School says she bears no ill will 
toward the boy who shot six of his schoolmates. 
</P>
<P>
	``I forgive him,'' Stephanie Laster, 15, said after being  
released from Hughes Spalding Hospital in Atlanta on Tuesday. ``I 
don't like what he did, but I won't go hating him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	T.J. Solomon, also 15, was charged in Thursday's shooting. Ed  
Garland, the boy's lawyer, has said the defense does not contest 
that he was the shooter. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephanie, who was shot in the abdomen, was the last of the  
victims to be released. 
</P>
<P>
		   ''I have eight weeks of lifting nothing heavier than a fork,''  
Stephanie later told reporters in front of her home. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday, a victim of the shooting in Littleton, Colo.,  
Richard Castaldo, left Swedish Medical Center in Englewood, Colo., 
and was transferred to Craig Hospital in Denver for physical 
rehabilitation. Castaldo, 17, suffered a spinal cord injury and 
partial paralysis from multiple gunshot wounds. His family and 
doctors hope the paralysis is not permanent. 
