<DOCNO> APW19990526.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 17:31:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins Want Void on Arena Lease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- One day after prospective team owner Mario  
Lemieux offered to buy out the Pittsburgh Penguins' Civic Arena 
lease, the team asked U.S. Bankruptcy Court today to void the arena 
agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The lease with SMG, the management company that also runs Three  
Rivers Stadium, costs the Penguins an NHL-high $6 million a year to 
play in the league's oldest arena. 
</P>
<P>
	The cumbersome contract, which resulted from past renegotiations  
between SMG and former Penguins owner Howard Baldwin, is viewed as 
one of the major impediments to keeping the bankrupt team in 
Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	If approved, the motion filed by the Penguins' lawyers with U.S.  
Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz would allow any potential buyer 
-- most likely, Lemieux -- to negotiate a new lease to play in the 
38-year-old arena. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both the judge and the NHL have identified the lease as the  
key to the case and the key to saving the Penguins for 
Pittsburgh,'' said Greg Cribbs, the Penguins' vice president and 
legal counsel. ``We believe this motion opens another door of 
opportunity to make the franchise economically viable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's group offered Tuesday to buy out the remaining eight  
seasons on the lease for $15 million. SMG president Wes Westley 
said that the lease was not for sale, but that concessions were 
possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's group and SMG then met Wednesday to discuss the lease,  
with Lemieux offering to retain SMG as the arena manager even if 
the lease is bought out. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, whose revised reorganization plan was praised Tuesday  
by the NHL, said the current lease with SMG will not work. And the 
NHL has said that no potential buyer is interested in keeping the 
team in Pittsburgh under the current terms of the lease. 
</P>
<P>
	SMG and Fox Sports Net Pittsburgh, the team's TV rights holder,  
have filed their own reorganization plan in bankruptcy court. But 
the NHL has expressed concern about that plan because Fox is an 
investor in the New York Rangers, and league rules bar an entity 
from holding a financial stake in more than one team. 
</P>
<P>
	Markovitz has scheduled a June 24 confirmation hearing on  
Lemieux's plan. The NHL also has asked that its own plan, called a 
backup in case the Lemieux bid is rejected, be placed on the same 
timetable. 
</P>
<P>
	The league's plan calls for an unidentified investor, believed  
to be NFL and NBA team owner Paul Allen, to pay $85 million to 
creditors. The investor then would move the team, presumably to 
Portland, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL originally wanted the Penguins' situation settled by May  
31 so the team could begin selling tickets and the final schedule 
for the 1999-2000 season could be given to its clubs. The league 
has since backed off that deadline and now wants a resolution by 
June 27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
