<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Bad-Loan Ratio Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- The bad-loan ratio of Philippine  
commercial banks rose in March to its highest level since the start 
of Asia's financial crisis, mainly because of slow credit growth, 
the central bank said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The non-performing loan ratio of the country's 53 commercial  
banks climbed to 13.18 percent of total loans in March from 12.87 
percent in February. 
</P>
<P>
	March's bad-loan ratio was sharply higher than the year-earlier  
level of 7.58 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said banks must extend more loans for the  
non-performing loan ratio to go down. This has not occurred despite 
a steady decline in interest rates, in which the average yield of 
benchmark 91-day treasury bills has fallen to 9.843 percent, its 
lowest in over two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Risk-adverse banks continue to be wary of lending to borrowers  
still vulnerable to the effects of Asia's financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Total loans in March reached $38.9 billion. Of that, $5.1  
billion were non-performing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
