<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Police Investigate Calif. Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Three days after a distraught woman was  
reported missing along with her children, the bodies of a woman and 
two children were found submerged in a car that plunged into the 
Sacramento River. 
</P>
<P>
	Divers with the Yolo County Sheriff's Department found a smashed  
car containing the bodies Tuesday in the river that serves as a 
boundary between Sacramento and Yolo counties. 
</P>
<P>
	A 31-year-old woman from nearby Walnut Grove and two children  
had been missing for three days. Police did not release their 
names. 
</P>
<P>
	A man told authorities that his wife was distraught and  
threatened to harm herself and her two children. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a strong possibility this was a suicide situation, but  
we don't know that yet,'' said Sheriff Ed Prieto. 
</P>
<P>
	The automobile, a Honda compact with a smashed roof and  
shattered rear window, was spotted Tuesday morning. Prieto said the 
bodies were those of an adult female, a boy about 2 years old and a 
girl about 5 or 6 years old. 
</P>
<P>
	His descriptions match those of the missing family.  
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said the car swerved off the isolated road Sunday  
evening and dropped down a steep 60-foot-long embankment into the 
water in an area popular with fishermen and water skiers. 
</P>
<P>
	One witness told the Highway Patrol that ``there was a little  
boy who seemed terrified in the right front seat,'' CHP Officer 
Kelly Baraga said. Others told authorities that the woman reached 
toward the rear seat just before the car entered the river. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no tire marks on the road indicating an attempt to  
stop the car, Prieto said. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities noted that the narrow stretch of highway was  
dangerous. Less than an hour before the three bodies were 
recovered, a car containing a man and woman plunged into the river 
about eight miles to the south. Both were rescued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
