<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Confronting IBM Executive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. will get its final  
opportunity to confront a government witness before its trial 
resumes when it questions an IBM executive today who negotiated the 
computer maker's sales contracts for Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	The government alleges as part of its antitrust case that  
Microsoft bullied the nation's computer manufacturers, who must buy 
Windows at a reasonable wholesale price to survive in a highly 
competitive industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Garry Norris, a former software director at IBM Corp., was to be  
questioned today at the federal courthouse in Raleigh, N.C. He 
negotiated important sales contracts for Windows in 1995 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris' deposition was the second of three scheduled this week.  
The government will depose a Microsoft witness, software executive 
Gordon Eubanks, on Friday in California. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters are allowed to attend the depositions under a 1913 law  
covering antitrust depositions, which are normally conducted in 
private. 
</P>
<P>
	Government lawyers contend that Microsoft, whose Windows  
software runs most of the world's personal computers, wields its 
prices to punish its enemies and reward its friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the exact price that Microsoft charges computer makers  
for Windows is one of the industry's most closely guarded secrets, 
previous testimony indicated that favored companies, such as Compaq 
Computer Corp. and Dell Computer Corp., generally pay less than 
IBM. 
</P>
<P>
	Court papers indicate Norris will testify about threats  
Microsoft made over IBM's support of rival products, such as its 
own OS/2 operating system and Internet browser software from 
Netscape Communications Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM's OS/2 operating system was considered a potential rival to  
Windows until 1994, when its popularity waned. 
</P>
<P>
	When Norris negotiated his first IBM contract for Windows, a  
year later, Microsoft was aggressively pushing its own Internet 
browser over Netscape's, which was far more popular. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle Times reported that Microsoft told IBM at the time  
that if it continued to support those rival products then Microsoft 
wouldn't sell Windows for less than its retail price, a decision 
that would have devastated IBM's computer sales. The newspaper did 
not say where it got the information. 
</P>
<P>
	A Microsoft spokesman, Mark Murray, said the company licensed  
Windows to IBM ``at a competitive price, and IBM continued to ship 
a variety of competing software programs alongside the Windows 
operating system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IBM and the Justice Department declined to comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Norris will be the government's second witness during the  
rebuttal phase of the trial, which resumes Tuesday after a 13-week 
recess. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers will use Norris to refute testimony from Microsoft  
executives, including Joachim Kempin, a senior vice president who 
negotiated contracts for the software giant. 
</P>
<P>
	Until the government named Norris as a witness, legal experts  
had questioned why the Justice Department had failed to persuade 
any computer maker to testify about Microsoft's influence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Testimony from IBM will provide a missing link to the theory  
that the government is asserting, that Microsoft has monopoly power 
and abuses it,'' said Richard Gray, an antitrust lawyer in San 
Jose, Calif., who has been following the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris also was expected to testify about restrictions Microsoft  
places on computer makers that want to modify the opening screen 
consumers see when they launch Windows. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
