<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Slip Early / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices slipped Thursday morning as  
investors turned cautious amid corporate earnings announcements. 
The dollar rose against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 19.64 points,  
or 0.12 percent, to 16,210.88 at the end of the morning session. On 
Wednesday, the average gained 16.29 points, or 0.10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.42 yen, up 0.32 yen from late in Tokyo on  
Wednesday and also above its late New York level of 122.17 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices started moderately higher  
following a rise on Wall Street, but moved into negative territory 
by mid-morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market lacks energy to test higher levels,'' said Kazunori  
Jinnai, deputy general manager of the equity department at Daiwa 
Securities SB Capital Markets. ``There is a lack of incentive to 
trade, and volume is low.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Contributing to the low volume and lack of movement was caution  
on the part of institutional investors amid earnings announcements, 
market players said. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 171.07  
points, or 1.6 percent, to 10,702.16. The high-tech-heavy Nasdaq 
Composite Index jumped 1.9 percent to 2,427.17 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 0.20 points, or 0.01 percent, to 1,303.12. 
The TOPIX closed down 5.36 points, or 0.41 percent, Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar edged higher against the yen as  
some Japanese institutional investors covered, short, or oversold 
dollar positions. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 128.09 yen, down  
from 129.36 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.4600 percent from 1.4150 percent late Wednesday, driving its 
price down to 99.47 yen from 99.86 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
