<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Approves New Diabetes Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Diabetics are getting a long-awaited new  
treatment that promises to help control their disease with less 
risk -- and a cheaper price tag -- than a popular but sometimes 
dangerous drug. 
</P>
<P>
	SmithKline Beecham Pharmaceuticals said Avandia, approved for  
sale by the Food and Drug Administration, will reach pharmacy 
shelves within a few days. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors have awaited Avandia as a possible alternative to the  
competing diabetes drug, Rezulin, which has destroyed some 
patients' livers. And now that Avandia is here, the question is 
whether the FDA will continue to allow the unfettered sale of 
Rezulin. 
</P>
<P>
	The two drugs have not been directly compared to see if they're  
equally effective, FDA endocrinology chief Dr. John Jenkins said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Most drugs that treat Type 2, or adult-onset, diabetes work by  
increasing insulin production or lowering blood sugar. Avandia and 
Rezulin, in contrast, are related chemicals that resensitize the 
body to insulin -- thus targeting the underlying cause of the 
disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Rezulin, sold since 1997, has helped many people who failed  
other treatments, and an estimated 750,000 people use it. But it 
also can damage the liver: The FDA lists 43 Rezulin patients who 
suffered acute liver failure and warns that they may account for 
only 10 percent of Rezulin-related liver damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Avandia, in contrast, has not shown signs of liver damage in  
studies of over 4,000 patients. 
</P>
<P>
	No one can say for certain that Avandia will never damage  
diabetics' livers, the FDA warned Wednesday. If there is a rare 
side effect, it may appear only after hundreds of thousands of 
people try the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	So the FDA stressed that diabetics who try Avandia should have a  
liver test before beginning the new drug and every two months 
during the first year of therapy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until we know more, it's prudent to monitor your patients to  
be safe,'' the FDA's Jenkins cautioned. ``We don't know yet that 
(Avandia) doesn't have the side effect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anyone with symptoms suggesting liver problems should contact a  
doctor for a liver test, the FDA warned. Symptoms include 
unexplained nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, fatigue, anorexia and 
dark urine or jaundice. If jaundice occurs, Avandia should be 
stopped. 
</P>
<P>
	With Avandia's approval, the question is Rezulin's future. The  
agency's scientific advisers said in March that Rezulin should 
remain on the market but be more tightly controlled so that only 
people who need it the most use it. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to understand, though, that Rezulin has a place in  
the treatment of diabetes. ... We're trying to manage the risk,'' 
Jenkins said. ``I hope we're going to be ready to make some 
decisions on that very soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	SmithKline said it would sell Avandia for a cheaper price than  
its competitor, setting the wholesale price of Avandia's 
recommended starting dose at $2 a day. The published wholesale 
price of Rezulin is $2.48 to $3.95 a day. 
</P>
<P>
	Avandia, known chemically as rosiglitazone, is only for Type 2  
diabetes, which afflicts about 14 million Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Avandia also can cause side effects, including mild to moderate  
swelling, an increase in blood cholesterol and anemia, but the FDA 
said the problems usually were not severe enough to require 
stopping the drug. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
