<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Florida To Flood Fire-Filled Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Mucky, smoke-billowing fires had  
authorities manning the pumps as they tried to bring an end to 
flames that scorched thousands of acres in south Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	South Florida Water Management officials planned to install  
30-inch pumps today to flood the burning muck and douse the flames 
in the Rotenberger Wildlife Management Area. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven pumps, each capable of spewing at least 25,000 gallons per  
minute, will be arranged in a horseshoe to funnel water from canals 
and over levees. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the muck that's putting out all the smoke. The muck fire  
will not go out unless it's flooded,'' said Sue Congelosi, a 
spokeswoman for the state Division of Forestry. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoke from the fire cut visibility to zero over much of a  
30-mile stretch of U.S. 27. One person was killed and 20 others 
injured Tuesday when five tractor-trailers crashed into an 
overturned truck on the highway in southwestern Palm Beach County. 
</P>
<P>
	About 26,000 acres of flaming sawgrass, brush and muck in the  
management area sent heavy smoke into the skies for a fifth day. 
</P>
<P>
	Forestry rangers believe lightning ignited the fire Friday but  
it went unnoticed until Sunday when west winds blew the smoke 
toward the coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoke from the fire would likely linger for another day or two  
since rain was not expected until the latter part of the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters working the massive blaze dropped ping pong balls  
filled with explosive chemicals from a helicopter to set a back 
fire that would help contain the flames. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire was contained by late Tuesday, said Bernadine Thomas,  
duty officer with the state Division of Forestry. 
</P>
<P>
	In North Florida's Baker County, about 50 miles west of  
Jacksonville, firefighters battled a remote blaze that swelled to 
nearly 15,000 acres in the Osceola National Forest. The fire jumped 
across Florida Highway 2 and into the 400,000-acre Okefenokee swamp 
that extends into Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, 3,636 wildfires have scorched 274,969 acres.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
