<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Casino Could Be Set Up at O'Hare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) -- The millions of travelers who find  
themselves at O'Hare Airport with a couple of hours to kill may 
soon be able to fill them by playing blackjack or pouring coins 
into slot machines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Illinois Legislature has approved casino gambling in Cook  
County, and the likely location is in Rosemont -- minutes from the 
world's second-busiest airport with 200,000 passengers a day. 
Atlanta Hartsfield Airport is the busiest. 
</P>
<P>
	No other major U.S. air hub has a casino so close, although at  
airports in Las Vegas and Reno, Nev., gamblers can start losing 
money at slot machines located right in the terminals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have the opportunity to attract these visitors from across  
the nation who fly into O'Hare,'' said Peter Lombardi, the 
executive director of the Rosemont Convention Bureau. ``If they're 
delayed two or three hours, they can hop in a cab or the train and 
be here in a minute. Then they can get back on a plane.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Travelers coming through O'Hare or stopping in Chicago may even  
extend their vacations by hours or even a day to give them time to 
make a run to the casinos, said Barbara Cappaert, a gambling 
industry analyst with KDP Investment Advisors. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is going to be a unique situation,'' Ms. Cappaert said. ``I  
could see it as something like the Mall of America (near 
Minneapolis), that's 10 minutes from the airport and they have 
shuttles over there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Rosemont casino is sure to attract hordes of Chicagoans  
because it would be closer than other Illinois casinos, and 
Rosemont is accessible by the city's elevated trains. Whether a 
casino near the airport will pull most of its money from travelers' 
wallets is open to debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland Heights, Mo., is a suburb of 25,000 people about a  
10-minute drive from the St. Louis airport. Like Rosemont, it has a 
thriving hospitality industry, with 1 million visitors a year 
staying in its hotels, said City Administrator Mark Levin. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, ``the casinos estimate perhaps 20 percent of their  
patrons come from outside of the immediate region,'' Levin said. 
``Most of the money comes from in and around the St. Louis metro 
area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gambling critics disregard the notion that casinos attract  
tourists and help boost the local economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gambling really hasn't brought in tourism,'' said Steve Taylor  
of Casino Watch, an anti-gambling organization. ``All you're 
getting is local convenience gambling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. George Ryan, a Republican, says he will probably sign the  
bill allowing casino gambling in Cook County. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten casinos have been licensed to operate in Illinois. Only one  
licenseholder would be eligible to take advantage of the 
Legislature's action -- the owners of a failed riverboat casino in 
East Dubuque, Ill. Rosemont officials are eager for their business. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rosemont casino would be allowed to stay permanently  
situated in a makeshift moat. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Don Stephens has pledged to share gambling proceeds with  
neighboring communities, and Chicago Mayor Richard M. Daley 
endorses a Rosemont casino. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
