<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Urge Attention to Euro Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Many of the 11 countries in  
Europe's new common currency pact aren't doing enough to comply 
with an accord aimed at ensuring the stability and growth of their 
economies, the Dutch Central Bank warned Wednesday in its annual 
report. 
</P>
<P>
	The pact calls on countries in the ``euro zone'' -- Austria,  
Belgium, Finland, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the 
Netherlands, Portugal and Spain -- to have budgets that are nearly 
balanced or have a surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	The Central Bank didn't specify which countries are not in line  
with the targets. But other economic forecasts have said Germany, 
France and Italy are among the larger countries unlikely to meet 
the key requirement for monetary union: limiting their budget 
deficits to 2 percent of gross domestic product. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this already vulnerable budgetary environment, it is  
disappointing to note that, on the whole, countries are 
insufficiently complying with the pact,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank said a more ambitious policy on deficit reduction would  
help offset cyclical downturns or other economic setbacks that 
could weaken the fledgling currency, which made its debut Jan. 1 on 
financial markets. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Netherlands, the Central Bank said it was unfortunate  
that the budget deficit is expected to rise to 1.7 percent of GDP 
after having dropped to 0.9 percent in both 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank called the Dutch government's target of a deficit of 1  
percent of GDP in 2002, based on an average economic growth rate of 
2.25 percent per year, ``insufficiently ambitious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Netherlands' three-party coalition government collapsed last  
week, and Central Bank President Nout Wellink warned that prolonged 
political instability could make it more difficult for the Dutch to 
comply with the stability pact. 
</P>
<P>
	The three leading Dutch political parties are currently involved  
in an effort to restore the coalition. If they fail, general 
elections are likely to be held in September or October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
