<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's former ambassador to the United  
States, Jesus Silva Herzog, says he is considering running for 
mayor of Mexico City next year for the governing party, newspapers 
reported Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am ready if the rules are reasonable; I am ready to risk  
it,'' he was quoted as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	The comments appear to end speculation that he might quit the  
ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, to run for the 
presidency as head of an opposition alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexico's most famous novelist, Carlos Fuentes, recently  
suggested such an alliance with Silva Herzog as its candidate and 
the politician has been holding meetings with opposition leaders in 
recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Tuesday he met with Francisco Labastida, the leading PRI  
candidate for president next year and hinted at support for him. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Argentina's opposition Alliance  
has unveiled a platform for October presidential and general 
elections vowing to tackle corruption and unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan, unveiled at an independence day rally Tuesday and  
published Wednesday, vowed to achieve progress in education, combat 
crime and crack down on corruption. It offered few specifics for 
achieving such goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``My job as president will be to investigate government  
corruption and put corrupt people in jail,'' said Buenos Aires 
Mayor Fernando de la Rua, the alliance's presidential nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	The opposition group is made up of the centrist Radical Civic  
Union and the left-of-center Frepaso party. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- The U.N. World Food Program said  
Wednesday it has asked Nicaragua to investigate a possible black 
market in products donated to help victims of last year's Hurricane 
Mitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Olaga Moraga, spokesman for the agency, said it wanted to  
investigate reports raised by local newspapers that donated canned 
fish and bags of milk meant for children had appeared in a local 
marketplace. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear how widespread the problem was.  
</P>
<P>
	Moraga said the program had distributed more than 5,500 tons of  
food to more than 400,000 people affected by the hurricane. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Thousands of people on Wednesday  
inaugurated the new headquarters of a Jewish community center on 
the site where the previous one was destroyed by a terrorist bomb 
in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The July 18, 1994 car bomb attack left 86 people dead and some  
300 injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Relatives held up candles and photographs of the victims during  
Wednesday's ceremony inaugurating the new AMIA community center, a 
20-story building of solid cement. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel has long contended that pro-Iranian terrorists were  
behind both the Jewish center attack and the 1992 bombing of the 
Israeli embassy here, which claimed 29 lives. Tehran has repeatedly 
denied the claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities had detained the man who sold the vehicle used as  
the car bomb, but have made no direct arrests in the investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 10:41:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Editorial Roundup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers in the  
United States and abroad: 

</P>
<P>
	May 21  
</P>
<P>
	Akron (Ohio) Beacon Journal, on NATO bombing in Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	Cracks in the NATO strategy for returning hundreds of thousands  
of ethnic Albanians to their homes in Kosovo appear wider than bomb 
craters in Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	It is time to try a pause in bombing.  
</P>
<P>
	Serbian leader Slobodan Milosevic has demanded a halt to bombing  
so that a diplomatic solution may be attempted. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO, of course, wants Milosevic's head. The problem is, it has  
never had a workable military plan to get it. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO doesn't have to abandon its objectives if it halts the  
bombing and gives diplomacy another chance. It can enter 
negotiations while making clear to Milosevic that if he doesn't 
accede to NATO-Russian peacekeeping protection for the Kosovars and 
show a willingness to compromise on other issues, the bombing will 
resume, redoubled. 

</P>
<P>
	May 21  
</P>
<P>
	The State, Columbia, S.C., on NATO leadership:  
</P>
<P>
	German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder outdid Bill Clinton ... in  
giving the upper hand to Slobodan Milosevic, doing his best to 
prevent NATO from even considering ground troops as an option, much 
less as a credible threat to the Serbian leader. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder's statement reflects the sincere and profound postwar  
pacifism that has been axiomatic throughout German political 
culture since 1945. The past, and shame about the past, are very 
much alive in Germany today. ... 
</P>
<P>
	So German reluctance to go to war is laudable and is to be  
encouraged on a certain level. ... 
</P>
<P>
	But the chancellor's remarks underline the desperate need for  
strong leadership within the 19-nation alliance, leadership that 
can only come from a U.S. president. ... 

</P>
<P>
	May 23  
</P>
<P>
	Quad-City Times, Davenport, Iowa, on welfare and states:  
</P>
<P>
	When the states began rewriting welfare laws a few years back,  
more than a dozen of them decided to impose limits on the amount of 
public assistance new residents could collect. 
</P>
<P>
	These limits restricted the new residents' welfare checks,  
typically for about a year, to the amount they had collected in 
their previous state. Those who supported such restrictions claimed 
it would discourage border-hopping welfare recipients from choosing 
their state of residence based on the amount of welfare they could 
collect. ... 
</P>
<P>
	It also assumes, since the restrictions apply to all new  
residents, that every welfare recipient, without exception, moves 
to another state for no other reason than to reap the financial 
benefits of a more generous public-assistance program. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortunately, the Supreme Court ruled ... that new-resident  
restrictions on welfare payments are illegal -- and each of the 15 
states that have such laws must now set them aside. That's as it 
should be. ... 

</P>
<P>
	May 21  
</P>
<P>
	Marin Independent Journal, Marin County, Calif., on metal  
detectors: 
</P>
<P>
	Is it any wonder if many of us become schizoid about life in  
these Violent States of America? 
</P>
<P>
	On the one hand, police reports to the FBI reassure us that  
violent crimes have declined for the seventh year in a row. On the 
other, it's enormously unsettling when the news flashes remind us 
that yet another suburban high school has been terrorized by the 
crackle of gunfire. 
</P>
<P>
	The spray of bullets at Heritage High School in Conyers, Ga.,  
injured six schoolmates, one month to the day after the Littleton, 
Colo., massacre that left 12 pupils and a teacher dead. 
</P>
<P>
	It's debatable the extent to which counseling, disciplinary  
crackdowns and finger-pointing at root social causes can curtail 
this kind of violence. 
</P>
<P>
	What can be done, in the short run? The sooner our local  
authorities think seriously about installing metal-detectors and 
imposing rigid security ... the sooner our schoolchildren can be 
safer and more of us can begin to be unshackled from our fears. ... 
</P>
<P>
	As unthinkable as weapons interceptors and police presence at  
our schools can be to most of us, they should no longer be 
unthinkable to all of us who insist that our schoolchildren and 
their educators must be safe. 

</P>
<P>
	May 25  
</P>
<P>
	The Charleston (W.Va.) Gazette, on the death penalty:  
</P>
<P>
	Back in 1985, a Chicago woman was raped and stabbed to death.  
Ronald Jones confessed -- but later said police beat the confession 
out of him. Nonetheless, he was sentenced to death. 
</P>
<P>
	Now DNA tests have proven that semen in the woman's body didn't  
come from Jones, and he has been set free. He's the 12th Illinois 
death-row inmate to be cleared in a dozen years. 
</P>
<P>
	Think of that: 12 Illinois men were waiting to be killed, but  
new evidence showed they were innocent. All those right-wing, 
``pro-death'' legislators who are eager to execute prisoners should 
think earnestly about this record. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Amnesty International issued another report last week  
saying that racism pervades America's death penalty system. 
</P>
<P>
	Of 500 prisoners executed since 1977, four-fifths were accused  
of murdering whites, even though the number of white and black 
murder victims are virtually equal. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Two days after the Amnesty report, the Nebraska legislature  
voted to halt executions in that state for two years while a 
fairness study is conducted. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nebraska action is heartening. We hope more states consider  
joining in the effort to end the barbaric practice of killing 
people. 

</P>
<P>
	May 22  
</P>
<P>
	The Advocate, Baton Rouge, La., on federal judge's legacy:  
</P>
<P>
	Few men have done more to change society for the better in their  
own time than Judge John Minor Wisdom, who died last week at 93. 
...
</P>
<P>
	Wisdom obviously grappled with many other difficult issues  
during his long service on the bench, but civil rights decisions 
form the legacy for which he most will be remembered. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Those efforts in the cause of civil rights could not have borne  
fruit were it not for Wisdom and others like him. They tore down 
statutory barriers that gave the weight of law to a tradition and 
culture of racial division and oppression. Their courage gave 
racial justice a foothold and an opportunity to grow in the South. 
</P>
<P>
	The cancer of racial hatred has not been fully excised in any  
part of our nation -- North, South, East or West. But that 
malignancy is in remission today, in no small part because of 
Wisdom and others who shared his courage and his dedication to the 
notion of equal justice for all. ... 

</P>
<P>
	May 23  
</P>
<P>
	The Florida Times-Union, Jacksonville, on presidential pay  
raise: 
</P>
<P>
	A House subcommittee was quite generous when it approved  
legislation that would give the next president a $200,000-a-year 
pay raise. ... 
</P>
<P>
	This is being proposed as a cost-of-living adjustment;  
presidential pay has not gone up in 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	But maybe that's because presidents don't have a lot of  
expenses. Taxpayers provide the first family's room and board ... 
and transportation. 
</P>
<P>
	Surely the $200,000 salary and $50,000 annual expense account  
are more than adequate to cover miscellaneous expenses and pocket 
change. 
</P>
<P>
	The average American, who pays the bill, certainly gets by with  
less. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, there is more to a job than the salary. Benefits and perks  
are compensation, too. So is power -- and no other job has more of 
that than the presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	While it is true the job entails a huge responsibility, the  
person in it does not always exercise responsibility commensurate 
with the salary. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe it should be like any other job. If applications become  
too few, raise the amount of compensation. 

</P>
<P>
	May 20  
</P>
<P>
	South County Journal, Kent, Wash., on emergency spending:  
</P>
<P>
	House and Senate negotiators have agreed on a $15 billion  
emergency spending bill. Unfortunately, this isn't good news for 
the budget as a whole. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is that emergency bills are exempt from normal  
budget measures and this one nearly doubled in size once it was in 
Congress' hands. A number of lawmakers' special projects got added 
on in the process. And, despite a last-minute show of resolution by 
House Speaker Dennis Hastert, neither Hastert nor his counterpart, 
Senate Republican leader Trent Lott, appears to have the clout to 
stop members from running away with the non-emergency spending 
bills. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Only $1.6 billion of this emergency bill is paid for with such  
offsets, mostly from food stamps, but even that is not really a 
sacrifice. Thanks to the booming economy, the food stamp fund has a 
surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the bill is $1 billion in hurricane relief for Central  
America and $556 million for farm relief, measures that were 
supposed to have passed last year but got caught up in political 
bickering. 
</P>
<P>
	The bulk of the bill is $11.8 billion for the war in Yugoslavia,  
twice what President Clinton asked for, but that amount, too, is 
deceptive. It includes a military pay raise and money for more 
equipment that should have received the normal budget scrutiny. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The money to pay for all of this will come from the Social  
Security surplus. Later this year Congress will take up the real 
spending measures. Keep your hand on your wallet. 

</P>
<P>
	May 24  
</P>
<P>
	La Stampa, Turin, Italy, on Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	The war is not over yet and, what's even worse, nobody knows  
when it's going to stop. 
</P>
<P>
	While Serbia's industry and infrastructures have been destroyed,  
and even the military has suffered serious damage, there are no 
signs that (Yugoslav President Slobodan) Milosevic will accept the 
conditions outlined by NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	The West wonders whether or not to send ground troops. The  
matter is made even more crucial and urgent by the upcoming summer, 
quickly followed by the fall, which in the Balkans is very much 
like winter. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea of hundreds of thousands of Kosovo refugees being kept  
in Macedonian and Albanian camps in the cold is intolerable. There 
is also a risk of destabilization in Albania and Macedonia, which 
is the ultimate goal of Serbia's ``ethnic strategy.'' ... 

</P>
<P>
	May 25  
</P>
<P>
	Le Temps, Geneva, Switzerland, on NATO bombing of Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	... NATO, which at the end of March expected the Belgrade  
government would swiftly give in to its demands, is looking ahead 
anxiously to winter before summer has even begun. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The results of 60 days of `sorties' is, objectively speaking,  
disastrous, and the generals can no longer hide their fears under 
statistical optimism. ... 
</P>
<P>
	So NATO is getting ready for a change of strategy, or at least  
to give Serbian authorities the impression that it's changing. ... 
</P>
<P>
	No doubt the United States is prepared to go all the way.  
</P>
<P>
	The superpower couldn't countenance a semi-failure, which would  
amount to a defeat, in a conflict that is so decisive for the 
alliance it leads. 

</P>
<P>
	May 25  
</P>
<P>
	Sueddeutsche Zeitung, Munich, Germany, on NATO and Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	NATO must explain what it's doing. When the war against Serbia  
began exactly two months ago it explained to the Serbs and the 
world that it was a war against the regime and not against the 
people. But when it now systematically destroys infrastructure 
systems, when because of that electricity is cut and there is a 
water shortage, then it has distanced itself fairly far from its 
postulating. It is not striking the center of power, these are not 
strikes at the power machinery -- it is a strike against the people. 
</P>
<P>
	The goals of NATO in this war are as before valid and justified.  
The government of Slobodan Milosevic delivers daily to NATO the 
legitimacy: through murder and massive expulsions. Alone on 
Pentecost (Whitsun) weekend thousands of Albanians were again 
forced over the borders. NATO not only has the justification, it 
has the duty to intercede for these people. But it also bears the 
responsibility not to let the goals and the methods of the war to 
drift apart. ... 

</P>
<P>
	May 23  
</P>
<P>
	The Nation, Bangkok, on Western double standards in Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	For many Africans, the flood of refugees forced to flee Kosovo  
is not so much a humanitarian crisis as an example of Western 
double standards. The number of white Kosovars now receiving aid in 
camps along Yugoslavia's borders -- 700,000 -- is roughly the same 
number of blacks who were killed in a few short, bloody months in 
Rwanda in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The atrocities being committed in places like Sierra Leone,  
where children are being hunted down and mutilated in most horrific 
fashion, are as appalling as any in Kosovo. So why no relief, no 
air lifts, no air strikes and only the occasional expressions of 
outrage? The sad truth is that the Kosovo action is not hypocrisy. 
The West, like the rest of the world, reacts when its interests are 
imperiled. Africa's curse is neither a matter of politics nor 
economics to the rest of the world. ... 

</P>
<P>
	May 25  
</P>
<P>
	Haaretz, Tel Aviv, on Israeli educational system:  
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak's promise to change the face of  
the nation cannot be realized without making far-reaching changes 
in the educational system. 
</P>
<P>
	Public concern is largely focused on the expansion of the  
ultra-Orthodox educational systems, which are raising -- with 
government funds -- a generation that turns its back on the 
fundamental values of Israeli society. 
</P>
<P>
	The networks ... educate their students entirely by Jewish law,  
promoting theocracy and nurturing disdain for the rule of law in 
the state that nourishes them. 
</P>
<P>
	A central core of improved curricula must be the common ground  
for all teaching institutions in the country. It can no longer be 
acceptable for the schools of the ultra-Orthodox to refuse to give 
instruction in entire branches of knowledge and to ban the hiring 
of nonreligious teachers. 

</P>
<P>
	May 25  
</P>
<P>
	The Jordan Times, Amman, on new Israeli government:  
</P>
<P>
	As Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak proceeds to put the  
final touches on his negotiating plan with the key Israeli 
political parties that could be invited to join his government, it 
appears that whether he is going for a left-of-center coalition or 
a right-of-center one, he has to include Likud, the second-largest 
party after his own Labor in the Knesset. 
</P>
<P>
	If he decides on a core coalition of Labor-Likud then he has to  
select, either Meretz for a choice of a left-leaning government or 
Shas for a rightist one. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Shas is for peace with the Arabs, the choice of Meretz  
will send a stronger signal to the Palestinians and Arabs that 
Barak means to move full speed on the peace front, despite the fact 
that the record of the Likud on the peace process is a cause of 
concern for many. ... 

</P>
<P>
	May 22  
</P>
<P>
	Asahi Shimbun, Tokyo, on Indonesia's general election:  
</P>
<P>
	The general election epitomizes a shift from the dictatorship  
for the sake of economic development to democratic rule, and from 
power politics to genuine party politics. 
</P>
<P>
	At such a juncture, suspicion resurfaced over the fortunes  
amassed by members of the Suharto family. No doubt the people will 
more vociferously demand the truth. 
</P>
<P>
	Although no political leader has called for extreme nationalism,  
it is worrisome that there has been a flurry of clashes among 
overly enthusiastic campaign workers. In addition, religious and 
ethnic conflicts are flaring in many parts of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	If violent incidents and vote buying take place on a massive  
scale, trust in general election will be lost, increasing the 
likelihood of political chaos and more serious economic crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	If a step is taken toward a democratic society and progress is  
made for unity among diversity, it will be very fitting for the 
future of the country. 

</P>
<P>
	May 24  
</P>
<P>
	The Irish Times, Dublin, on Hillary Rodham Clinton:  
</P>
<P>
	What to do after a spell in the White House? It is a problem  
which has troubled recent former U.S. presidents. ... 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton, on the other hand, at only 54, will be way  
ahead of retirement age when he steps down. ... He had hinted that 
he and Hillary might find suitable postings in academia but that 
was before Judge Starr put him through the wringer. Now, he will 
need to make serious money to pay his legal debts so his options 
are more limited. But the options open to Mrs. Clinton have widened 
and she is said to be ``seriously interested'' in running for the 
U.S. Senate from the state of New York. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The wonder is that Mrs. Clinton wants it. She has never  
disguised her disdain for Washington and the Congress. Now, she 
seems prepared not just to remain on in Washington but to work in 
the Congress. ... 
</P>
<P>
	But it would be a high profile position guaranteeing her much  
publicity were she to use it as Robert Kennedy did, making the 
camera lights shine into dark places of neglect. Mrs Clinton may be 
taking the long view. Could not the first woman senator from New 
York, should she prove successful, become eight years later the 
first woman candidate for the Oval Office? 

</P>
<P>
	May 25  
</P>
<P>
	Le Monde, Paris, on Cannes film festival:  
</P>
<P>
	The awards ceremony at the 52nd annual Cannes film festival -- as  
beautiful as the winning films were -- without a doubt dealt a blow 
to a broader view of cinema. And there was plenty of opportunity to 
express that view with this year's selection. As with other older 
arts, cinema suffers from a tension that separates the boldest 
works on an artistic level, from more conformist mass production. 
</P>
<P>
	Films by Pedro Almodovar, Raoul Ruiz, Takeshi Kitano and David  
Lynch showed that it is still possible to marry creative ambition -- 
without concessions -- and a desire to share it with a large public 
happy to see a film. With systematic provocativeness, the jury on 
the contrary chose to take the side of only the most radical 
(films). 
</P>
<P>
	Art cinema finds itself very much alone, and so does the Cannes  
festival. 
</P>
