<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Wants Campaign Finance Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defying the GOP leadership, five House  
Republicans on Wednesday threw their support behind a 
Democratic-led push to force campaign finance legislation to a vote 
this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to act on campaign finance reform now, not tomorrow,''  
Rep. Chris Shays, R-Conn., said at a news conference where he and 
others dismissed as inadequate Speaker Dennis Hastert's offer of 
floor action in September. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would ban ``soft money,'' the large, unregulated  
donations that the parties and some politicians seek to fund their 
political activities. 
</P>
<P>
	It also would limit so-called ``issue ads,'' which are governed  
more loosely than other commercials because they do not directly 
advocate a candidate's election or defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leadership aides expressed cautious confidence they  
could defeat the drive for accelerated vote on the measure. In an 
announcement that appeared designed to slow momentum for an 
accelerated vote, one committee announced plans for hearings on 
campaign finance proposals in early June. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a prerogative of the majority to establish a calendar for  
legislation, and a decision to side with Democrats on so 
fundamental an issue could have repercussions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you put yourself on a leadership track,'' Shays  
said at one point when asked about possible retribution. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining him in signing were Reps. Mike Castle of Delaware, Greg  
Ganske of Iowa, Michael Forbes of New York and Connie Morella of 
Maryland. Their signatures brought to 201 the number of names on a 
parliamentary device -- known as a ``discharge petition'' -- that 
would force the measure to the floor. 
</P>
<P>
	It takes 218 signatures to succeed, and comments by other  
Republican supporters of campaign finance legislation underscored 
their reluctance to follow the lead set by Shays and others. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Marge Roukema of New Jersey, said she had not decided  
whether to sign. Rep. Zach Wamp, R-Tenn., who has clashed with 
party leaders often on the issue, said, ``for now, I'm 
uncommitted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the news conference, Shays and Ganske both made direct  
references to the impact of contributions on Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Ganske said he had ``seen the power of soft money on influencing  
political decisions.'' Pressed for specifics, he said ``the way the 
HMO debate worked out last year,'' when the insurance industry 
successfully opposed Democratic-drafted legislation to strengthen 
the rights of patients in dealing with their HMOs. 
</P>
<P>
	Shays said, ``sadly, members of Congress are purchasing  
influence over their colleagues'' by creation of one particular 
type of political action committee and then ``accepting unlimited 
amounts of soft money'' for it. 
</P>
<P>
	That was a reference to leadership PACs, which are allowed to  
accept soft money donations, and then make donations to the 
campaigns of candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Republicans oppose the legislation, citing both  
constitutional and political grounds. They say restricting 
contributions is a violation of the free speech guarantee of the 
Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	They also express concern that without soft money donations,  
Republicans would be at a disadvantage compared with Democrats, who 
receive substantial support from labor unions. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, the campaign legislation is virtually certain to pass  
the House once it comes to a vote. Shays and others want it passed 
as quickly as possible because a Republican-led filibuster is a 
strong possibility in the Senate. There is no date for the Senate 
to consider its version of the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar legislation was passed in the House last year, but only  
after a monumental struggle. Then-Speaker Newt Gingrich vowed to 
keep the issue from the floor, but ultimately capitulated when it 
became apparent that enough Republicans would join with Democrats 
and bring the measure to a vote over his objections. 
</P>
<P>
	Roukema and Wamp helped arrange a meeting with Hastert recently  
at which members of the rank-and-file urged him to allow a debate 
and vote by July. 
</P>
<P>
	But shortly after Shays and the others signed the petition, she  
said she wasn't ready to. 
</P>
<P>
	``Conditions were very different when Gingrich was here,'' she  
said. ``There was no alternative and he was absolutely adamant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The maneuvering unfolded in the House as two Oregon lawmakers,  
Democratic Sen. Ron Wyden and Republican Rep. Greg Walden, proposed 
legislation requiring candidates to appear in their TV attack ads 
or pay 35 percent more for future ads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
