<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Outline of Truck-Safety Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Key provisions to cut the number of truck-related deaths in half  
over the next decade, from about 5,000 to about 2,500 annually, as 
announced by the Clinton administration on Tuesday: 
</P>
<P>
	--Shut down ``unfit'' motor carriers. A provision in the highway  
bill enacted last year allows commercial vehicle inspectors to shut 
down truck and bus operators for a single instance of misconduct, 
instead of having to show a pattern of misconduct. The federal 
Office of Motor Carriers, which regulates trucks and buses, will 
issue an interim rule this summer to implement that policy, with a 
final rule taking effect thereafter. 
</P>
<P>
	--Increase penalties for violations. Until now, serious  
violations of commercial vehicle laws could be punished with a fine 
of up to $1,000 per violation, with an overall cap of $10,000. 
Record-keeping violations, such as falsifying log books, could be 
punished with a fine of up to $500 per instance, with an overall 
cap of $2,500. Based on a memo issued in April by the Office of 
Motor Carriers, serious offenses can now be punished with a fine of 
up to $10,000 per instance, with no overall cap. Record-keeping 
infractions can now be punished with fines of up to $5,000 per 
violation, again with no overall cap. 
</P>
<P>
	--Increase inspections. The Office of Motor Carriers has about  
260 safety inspectors in the field. On average, they each completed 
about 24 ``compliance reviews'' at truck and bus companies in 1997. 
They will now be required to conduct at least 48 reviews per year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
