<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Points Finger at Ex-IBM Worker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An IBM secretary who knew of the company's plans  
to take over Lotus Development Corp. tipped off her husband, 
leading 25 people to pocket more than $1.3 million from insider 
trading, the Securities and Exchange Commission charged today. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC said the illegal trades -- many by novices to the  
securities markets who did not even have accounts when they 
received the tip -- were touched off when Lorraine K. Cassano told 
her husband about the Lotus acquisition, which occurred in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	In papers filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, the SEC  
said Mrs. Cassano told her husband, Robert M. Cassano, a paging 
communications company salesman, who then told two friends who 
agreed to purchase stock for him. 
</P>
<P>
	Those two friends told others and soon the insider information  
had spread through a wide network of family members, friends and 
stock brokers, the SEC said in the civil action. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, a rash of illegal insider trading among the 25  
individuals occurred during a 6 1/2 period on June 2, 1995, the SEC 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three days later, International Business Machines Corp.  
announced its takeover offer for Lotus and the value of Lotus 
common stock leaped from $32.50 per share to more than $61 per 
share, an increase of nearly 90 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Cassano, a secretary in the Volumes and Revenue Department  
of the Software Group at IBM in Somers, N.Y., at the time of the 
insider trades, was suspended when IBM learned of the 
investigation. The North Salem, N.Y., resident was later fired, the 
SEC said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those charged in the case was a pizzeria owner, a bank  
vice president, a private school teacher, a grocery store owner, a 
lawyer, the president of a direct-mail marketing company, a doctor, 
an engineer and several stockbrokers. Of those charged, 13 live in 
Staten Island, N.Y., and six live in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC said Mrs. Cassano first learned of the pending Lotus  
deal when she was asked to copy documents in late April or early 
May 1995. On May 5, 1995, her supervisor told her that IBM would be 
taking over Lotus, the SEC said. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 31, 1995, Mrs. Cassano learned that the board of  
directors had authorized the company to make an offer for Lotus and 
that it would be announced on June 5, the SEC said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Cassano then violated strict policies at IBM forbidding  
employees from disclosing nonpublic information, especially about 
the Lotus deal, the SEC said. 
</P>
<P>
	In its court papers, the SEC asked the court to order the  
defendants to obey all securities laws, return any illegally 
obtained profits and be fined civil penalties up to three times 
their ill-gotten gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC said Mrs. Cassano's husband, Robert, pleaded guilty to  
insider trading on Jan. 15, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cassanos could not immediately be reached for comment on the  
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the defendants tried to conceal their trades or the  
illicit nature of their trading activity by lying under oath about 
the reasons for their trades and falsely denying they knew the 
others in the group, the SEC said. 
</P>
<P>
	Others who have pleaded guilty in the case thus far include  
lawyer Carmine DeSantis of Staten Island, salesman Michael Paul 
Green of Edison, N.J., computer technician P. Gerard Mazzone of 
Staten Island, delicatessen owner Peter G. Mazzone of Staten 
Island, computer technician Joseph Petrosino of Brooklyn, N.Y., and 
Dr. Gary Spierer of Staten Island. 
</P>
<P>
	DeSantis pleaded to conspiracy to commit obstruction of justice,  
Green to obstruction of justice, both Mazzones to insider trading 
and perjury, Petrosino to perjury and Spierer to obstruction of 
justice. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 09:11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Exile's Life: Bobbie Ann Mason </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAYFIELD, Ky. (AP) -- The world has closed in on the Mason family  
farm. The dirt road that once ran along front is now a noisy 
highway. The cornfield across the way has been replaced by a 
towering feed mill, which crowds the reflection on the farm's pond. 
</P>
<P>
	These are the roots of author Bobbie Ann Mason, or what's left  
of them. Strangers rent the house she grew up in and other 
strangers work the fields. On this gray afternoon, even the soil 
looks foreign, more fertile for weeds than for the soy beans 
usually grown here. 
</P>
<P>
	For Mason and this land, it's been a long, complicated  
relationship. As a young woman, she left for the North, and the 
open, rootless life of the city. That's where writers were made, 
she believed. That's where she'd free herself from the South's 
narrow, fated ways. 
</P>
<P>
	But the longer she was gone, the more home spoke to her. She has  
written three novels and dozens of short stories, virtually all set 
in Kentucky and many taking on the same issues and feelings she 
dealt with personally: the differences between generations, the gap 
between those who left and those who stayed. 
</P>
<P>
	And so, in a way, she has returned.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have these opposing images in my mind,'' the 59-year-old  
Mason says over the buzz of a car hurrying by. ``I'm walking down 
Park Avenue, but I'm also thinking back to my earlier self, the cow 
pastures. All the juxtapositions are jarring; that's the exile 
mentality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mason lives about a hundred miles from here, on a 100-acre farm  
where the land is used for walking, not tilling. She comes to 
Mayfield often, especially to see her mother, who has suffered a 
few mini-strokes over the past couple of years. Her father died in 
1990. 
</P>
<P>
	The author of such acclaimed works of fiction as the novels ``In  
Country'' and ``The Feather Crowns'' and the short story 
``Shiloh,'' Mason has been reticent about herself -- until now. She 
has written a memoir, ``Clear Springs,'' in which she looks back 
both on her own life and the lives of her ancestors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clear Springs'' isn't so much a confession as a meditation on  
the modern spirit, the difference between what she wanted, and was 
allowed to have, and what her ancestors settled for. It's a book, 
for more reasons than one, that her mother would not have written. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's not especially interested in my efforts to make some  
kind of coherent pattern out of everything,'' Mason said. ``She's 
been a farmer all her life. She has the kind of wisdom that 
transcends these feeble efforts.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Turn right on the highway and you'll find Clear Springs, the  
tiny town where the author's ancestors lived and are buried. Turn 
left and drive just up the road and you'll find the assisted living 
facility where Mason's mother, 79-year-old Christy Mason, moved in 
early this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Even leaning on a walker, the elder Mason looks as durable as  
the earth she used to work. She is a solidly built woman with a 
playful smile and shining blue eyes, a contrast to her soft-spoken, 
slightly built daughter, who kneels at her side. 
</P>
<P>
	``She always wanted to write, but I thought that would pass,''  
Christy Mason says, as the author shakes her head and laughs. 
</P>
<P>
	``She always had a book, always had a pencil. She was always  
writing down things. She'd walk along and see things and write them 
down. And she couldn't stand anybody not using their time: `Oh, 
mama, make 'em do something. They're just wasting their time.''' 
</P>
<P>
	As in a work of fiction, one of the characters took over Mason's  
memoir: her mother. Christy Mason is the heroine of her daughter's 
story, a ``remarkable'' woman who gave up the life she could have 
had to let her daughter live it instead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel that she had this exuberant spirit that the Masons  
tried to beat out of her and she never got much opportunity to 
follow that exuberant nature,'' the author said. 
</P>
<P>
	A journalist when she was young, Mason investigated her mother's  
life. She discovered that her grandfather was just 16 and five 
years younger than her grandmother when they married. Her 
grandfather ran away before Christy was born and four years later 
her grandmother died in childbirth. 
</P>
<P>
	``My mother would get so weary with me because I would always  
have my notebook and always ask her questions,'' the author said. 
``She always told me everything she could and I finally decided I 
had gone as far as I could with it. I didn't bother her anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like her father, Christianna Lee married young; she was not  
quite 17 when, in 1936, she ran off with 20-year-old Wilburn Mason. 
They were so worried his family wouldn't approve that they drove to 
Tennessee, wedded quickly and snuck back to his house after his 
parents had gone to sleep. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Masons were rooted and conservative and the Lees came from  
a different social class,'' Bobbie Ann Mason said. ``They didn't 
have as much property and status to protect. The Lees were not 
known to be as thrifty and dependable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By nature ``sassy and full of fire,'' Christy Mason lived with  
her in-laws as a newlywed, feeling confined by their quiet 
lifestyle. She pulled weeds and gathered peas and corn. She worked 
for a while in a men's suit factory. At times, she wondered if she 
should have married. 
</P>
<P>
	In the mid-1960s, with two of her four kids still in the house,  
her father-in-law died and the family moved back in with her 
mother-in-law. Not until 1981, when her mother-in-law died, did 
Christy and Wilburn Mason get to spend a night in their house 
alone. 
</P>
<P>
	``Possibility'' is a favorite word of the author's and it's how  
she defines the difference between her life and her mother's. The 
author had choices; her mother didn't. Mason wonders if the reason 
she turned out so differently is because she was born 20 years 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	``You think of yourself as independent,'' she said. ``You read  
books and go traveling. But those things weren't there in my 
mother's time and they weren't possible. You wonder if you'd have 
the same energies if you lived then.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bobbie Ann Mason, the eldest child, was born in 1940. The farm  
filled her senses, but stories turned her head. She read the 
Bobbsey Twins and was shocked that they went on vacations and never 
did chores. She read and re-read ``Little Women'' and dreamed of 
being Jo, the sister who writes and writes and eventually leaves 
for New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me,'' Mason recalled in her memoir, ``it was and still is a  
fundamental question. Why work? Does everybody have to sweep? Could 
I get out of it somehow?'' 
</P>
<P>
	She seemed to have been born in the wrong part of the world. She  
didn't want to cook and she hated country music. She listened to 
rock 'n' roll, read philosophy and questioned the existence of God. 
``Give up these strange ideas of yours,'' one teacher told her. 
``Your field is mathematics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike her parents, Mason attended college, majoring in English  
at the University of Kentucky. In 1962, she moved to New York. She 
imagined herself as Holly Golightly, to the point of showing up for 
a job interview in a large black Panama-straw hat, like the one 
Audrey Hepburn wore in ``Breakfast at Tiffany's.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were happy, funny memories. Mason wrote for a fan  
magazine, where Robert Vaughn, Robert Goulet and other celebrities 
would stop by for interviews. Ann-Margret, dressed in a 
``smashing'' Kelly-green outfit, complimented Mason's ``sweet 
little accent.'' The teen idol Fabian surprised his interviewer by 
talking about literature, from ``Franny and Zooey'' to Thucydides' 
``The History of the Peloponnesian Wars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But to be a Southerner in Manhattan in the 1960s was like  
showing up at a poetry reading in a debutante's dress. Her demeanor 
was too soft, her accent too strong. From boyfriends to teachers to 
colleagues, Northerners couldn't stop lecturing her on how she 
should talk and how she should think. 
</P>
<P>
	``I questioned my intelligence, my sanity, my identity,'' Mason  
wrote. ``I believed wholeheartedly in my own inferiority, and 
people treated me accordingly, like a wadded-up dishrag.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like a good bohemian, Mason listened to jazz, painted her radio  
bright orange and wore beads, bell-bottoms and sandals. She wrote 
``experimental'' fiction and endured graduate-level English 
studies, where the goal was to say obscure things and say them in a 
Northern accent. 
</P>
<P>
	But only by getting this far from herself did she get an idea of  
who she was, and what she was called to write. She wasn't meant to 
live in the city and she wasn't meant to tell stories about city 
life. Her literary sources, she discovered, were back home. 
</P>
<P>
	``How could I have failed to recognize them? They have claimed  
me all along,'' she wrote. ``And my mother was my chief 
inspiration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From ``In Country'' to ``The Feather Crowns,'' Mason tells  
stories of spirited country women. At the end of the novel ``Spence 
+ Lila,'' based on her parents, she describes Lila's face as 
``dancing like pond water in the rain, all unsettled and stirring 
with aroused possibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mason herself waited until her late 20s to marry. While a  
graduate student at the University of Connecticut, she met Roger 
Rawlings, a fellow English major and a Northerner who didn't talk 
down to her. They were married in 1969, moved to rural Pennsylvania 
in the early 1970s and then to Kentucky in the early '90s. 
</P>
<P>
	Back in her home state, the idea was to return, but not relapse.  
She has no children and there is no talk of her mother moving in. 
Their fates are close, but not identical. Because, the qualities 
Mason admires in her mother are part of the reason she doesn't want 
to live like her. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was such a wonderful mother and so maternal, and yet we  
saw her sacrifice and slaving and suffering and that didn't give me 
a good image of having children and neither did the culture in 
general,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw women being trapped by that. My mother had compensated  
for the loss of her mother by being this wonderful mother. So I at 
least felt fulfilled and didn't have to do that. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' Mason said with a sigh, ``times have changed.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
