<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Details of Poll on Clinton, Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some results on a CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll released Wednesday  
about President Clinton, Congress and Kosovo. When results don't 
total 100 percent, the remainder didn't know or refused to answer. 

</P>
<P>
	--Do you approve or disapprove of the way Bill Clinton is  
handling his job as president? 
</P>
<P>
	Approve, 53 percent; disapprove, 42 percent. This is his lowest  
rating in this poll since August 1996; it has been above 60 percent 
for months. 

</P>
<P>
	--Do you think the country would be better off if the Republicans  
controlled Congress, or if the Democrats controlled Congress? 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans, 36 percent, Democrats, 37 percent; neither, 14  
percent; same, 4 percent. In mid-December, Democrats were preferred 
to lead Congress over Republicans by 41 percent to 30 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	--How confident are you in President Clinton's ability to handle  
the situation in Kosovo -- very confident, somewhat confident, not 
too confident, or not at all confident? 
</P>
<P>
	Very confident, 17 percent; somewhat confident, 40 percent; not  
too confident, 17 percent; not at all confident, 25 percent. The 
number who are very confident in Clinton's ability on Kosovo 
dropped from 27 percent in late March to 17 percent now and the 
number not at all confident increased from 13 percent to 25 
percent. 

</P>
<P>
	--If the current NATO air and missile strikes are not effective  
in achieving the United States' objectives in Kosovo, would you 
favor or oppose President Clinton sending U.S. ground troops into 
the region along with troops from other NATO countries? 
</P>
<P>
	Favor, 40 percent; oppose, 57 percent. In mid-April, 52 percent  
favored sending in ground troops if airstrikes didn't work and 45 
percent opposed that step. 

</P>
<P>
	--Would you approve or disapprove if the U.S. and NATO were to  
temporarily suspend the airstrikes and attempt to resolve the 
matter through negotiations and other means? 
</P>
<P>
	Approve, 82 percent; disapprove, 15 percent.  

</P>
<P>
	The phone survey of 1,050 adults was taken Sunday and Monday and  
has an error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
