<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Questions Arise in Amtrak Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- In her final act, Julia Toledo tried to  
snatch her son out of the way of an oncoming train. 
</P>
<P>
	But as she raced across the tracks to reach him, her three other  
sons trailed after her, and the whole family was struck from behind 
by the locomotive, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Toledo, 46, and sons Pedro, 3; Angel, 6; and Carlos, 12,  
were killed, authorities said. Her 10-year-old son, Jose, was in 
critical condition today at Bridgeport Hospital. Authorities 
originally said it was the 6-year-old had survived, but after the 
coroner's office identified the remains they corrected that today 
to say it was Angel's brother Jose who was alive. 
</P>
<P>
	The family had been walking along the train tracks at 2:20 a.m.  
Tuesday when they were hit by an Amtrak train moving at 71 mph. At 
the scene, rescue workers found backpacks, books, report cards and 
a Bible strewn among body parts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's obvious they weren't going for a joy ride. This was a  
family in distress,'' said Fairfield First Selectman Ken Flatto. 
</P>
<P>
	The family, natives of Ecuador, had lived in a Bridgeport  
apartment a few doors away from Julia's sister, Maria, and brother, 
Carlos. But last week they moved into the YMCA Families In 
Transition shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	The sister said in today's Hartford Courant that she had  
persuaded her sister to move from Ecuador 1 1/2 years ago. She said 
they were not citizens, but were in this country legally. The dead 
woman had worked as a janitor at Fairfield University. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Toledo had told a shelter case worker that the burden of  
child care and a demanding job had become too intense, the Courant 
reported. She told the case worker she had quit her job and needed 
a place for her and the boys to sleep. 
</P>
<P>
	The three older boys attended Luis Munoz Marin elementary  
school. Timileida Martorony, 11, a fifth-grader at the school, said 
the boys walked to school together. She said she was in the same 
class with Carlos. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was nice. He liked to draw,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened as the family crossed a trestle over a  
two-lane street. The engineer reported seeing a child on the right 
side of the tracks at about 2:20 a.m. A split second later, he saw 
a woman and three other children on the left side of the tracks, 
said James O'Donnell, police chief for the Metropolitan 
Transportation Authority. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman crossed the tracks in front of the oncoming train to  
reach the lone child on the right, and the other children followed, 
O'Donnell said. Apparently, in the confusion the boy on the right 
moved toward his mother at the same time, and all were struck. 
</P>
<P>
	``Her last act was an attempt to save her other child,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenneth Gambardella of the state Department of Transportation  
said it would have taken more than a mile for the engineer to stop 
the train. 
</P>
<P>
	``His only option would have been to blow the whistle, put the  
train into emergency (braking) and pray,'' Gambardella said. The 
train's recorder shows the engineer did indeed sound the horn and 
apply the brakes. 
</P>
<P>
	The train was headed by two electric locomotives, which are much  
quieter than diesel models, Gambardella said. The welded track in 
the area also reduces train noise. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes you can't hear these trains at all until they're  
right on top of you, and by then, of course, it's too late,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Ronald Gross, a trauma surgeon at Bridgeport Hospital, said  
the accident scene was horrific. The front of the train was 
splattered with blood, and lying amid the shattered bodies were a 
small tennis shoe and Sesame Street figurines, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no injuries on the train, which carried about 185  
passengers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
