<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls, Japanese Stocks Mixed / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen today for a second  
consecutive day on selling by overseas investors, retreating from 
last week's seven month high. Japanese stocks turned mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.10 yen in the late afternoon, down 0.62  
yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York 
level of 122.70 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 16.29  
points, or 0.10 percent, closing the day's trading at 16,230.52 
points. On Tuesday, the average shed 176.26 points, or 1.08 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar fell against the yen in Tokyo  
as U.S. funds cut overbought dollar positions, but buying from 
Japanese life insurers and trust banks at around 121.50 yen 
supported the downside, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar started the Asian day on a weak note after another  
big drop on Wall Street overnight prompted Japanese institutional 
investors and overseas funds to sell on fears that the fall might 
continue. 
</P>
<P>
	``U.S. funds have long dollar positions and they want to further  
unwind the long positions,' said Shuji Takano, assistant manager of 
foreign exchange at ABN AMRO Bank, referring to the funds 
overbought in the greenback. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar remained under selling pressure as domestic investors  
continued to lock in profits following recent gains. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 19, the dollar rose to a seven month high against the  
yen, climbing above 124 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar has now shed a total of 1.94 yen in two days. The  
currency ranged between 121.60 yen and 122.46 yen in today's 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 129.36 yen, down  
from 130.35 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the Nikkei average edged higher with  
domestic institutional investors buying some blue chips, including 
Sony Corp. and Fujitsu Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	But the broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on  
the exchange's first section was down 5.36 points, or 0.41 percent, 
to 1,303.32 points. The TOPIX lost 8.83 points, or 0.67 percent, 
the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market lacks direction,'' said Yoshihiko Kuroichi, an  
analyst in the investment information department at Kankaku 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the exchange's first section was estimated at 452  
million shares, compared with Tuesday's turnover of 445.08 million 
shares. Declining issues outnumbered advancers 688 to 496, with 132 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 123.58  
points, or 1.2 percent, to close at 10,531.09 on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank shares in Tokyo were mixed after the nation's major lenders  
announced record losses this week. The 15 largest banks said they 
spent 10 trillion yen ($82 billion) over the last year writing off 
failed loans from the speculative 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.4300 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.3550 
percent, driving its price down to 99.73 yen from 100.39 yen. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
