<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Group Says Ratings Spark Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Television programming is more violent and  
vulgar today than before the networks in 1997 adopted voluntary 
ratings, a conservative parents' group said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The ratings system, which was intended to help parents choose  
suitable shows for their children, has prompted some in the 
industry to push the envelope even further, said L. Brent Bozell 
III, chairman of the Parents Television Council. 
</P>
<P>
	``Plainly put, television is the raunchiest it has ever been in  
spite of, or perhaps because of, the unintended consequences of the 
ratings system and those who abuse it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The council studied two weeks of November sweeps programming for  
each of the past three years on NBC, CBS, ABC, Fox, WB and UPN. 
Sexual content, foul language and violent content grew by nearly 31 
percent over that time, Bozell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadcasters have contended just the opposite, cited a  
network-funded UCLA study from 1998 showing that networks had 
tempered the amount and nature of violence on their programs over 
the previous three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., fired another salvo  
at the entertainment industry, saying the content of a TV station's 
programming should help determine whether its federal license is 
renewed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's time we look directly at programming content,''  
Lieberman said at a Capitol Hill news conference that included 
Bozell. 
</P>
<P>
	But Lieberman and Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., lauded steps taken  
in Washington since two students rampaged through a Colorado High 
School, killing 12 classmates and a teacher. 
</P>
<P>
	Brownback sponsored provisions in the juvenile justice bill the  
Senate passed last week authorizing the Federal Trade Commission 
and the Justice Department to investigate whether Hollywood is 
marketing violent shows and games to children. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is in the public interest to know whether entertainment  
companies are making a killing off our kids,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another provision encourages TV networks, cable companies and  
the movie, music and video game industries to enter into a 
voluntary code of conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pleading with the networks, please do that,'' Brownback  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Brownback's spokesman said later the senator rejects as too  
heavyhanded Lieberman's idea that the Federal Communications 
Commission renew or yank TV station licenses based on programming 
content. 
</P>
<P>
	Bozell and the lawmakers said there are signs the entertainment  
industry is getting the message. They pointed to CBS's decision 
last week to leave off its schedule a pilot series about a mob war 
in New York City because of concerns about its violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
