<HEADLINE> Wheat, Soybeans Down; Corn Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat and soybean futures retreated Wednesday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade, while corn futures finished mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn, spring wheat and soybean futures were pressured by  
forecasts for warm, dry weather over the next week that should 
speed the pace of farmer plantings and put producers in a good 
position for another year of bumper crops. 
</P>
<P>
	But corn found buying support on reports of new export sales to  
Asia, which continues to reinforce ideas that demand for the U.S. 
commodity remains relatively strong. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 1 1/4 cents to $2.47 1/2 a bushel; July  
corn was unchanged at $2.14 3/4 a bushel; July oats rose 1 cent to 
$1.20 1/2 a bushel; July soybeans fell 4 1/4 cents to $4.55 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meat and livestock futures were mostly higher on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .97 cent to 63.67 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .73 cent to 75.30 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose .40 cent to 54 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose 1.10 
cents to 54.47 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
