<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Milosevic May Be Indicted  
</P>
<P>
	THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- The U.N. court's chief prosecutor,  
Louise Arbour, has called a news conference for tomorrow but will 
not comment on a CNN report that a war crimes indictment against 
Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic is imminent. However, a 
diplomatic source at NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, told 
The Associated Press today that an indictment appeared to have been 
in the works for several weeks. Meanwhile, the Yugoslav war crimes 
tribunal today urged the gathering of proof of wrongdoing in Kosovo 
before the evidence can be destroyed. 

</P>
<P>
	Dolly the Sheep May Age Prematurely  
</P>
<P>
	EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) -- Dolly the cloned sheep may be  
susceptible to premature aging and disease because her genes were 
copied from a 6-year old sheep, Scottish scientists say. Dolly is a 
healthy 3-year-old sheep, but the DNA in her cells shows telltale 
signs of wear that are more typical of an older animal. Geneticists 
said the finding, published in Thursday's issue of the journal 
Nature, provides further evidence that cloning has its limits and 
that researchers cannot endlessly manufacture copies of animals 
without the original genetic blueprint wearing out. In 1996, Dolly 
became the first large animal to be cloned from genetic material 
extracted from an adult cell. 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan Charges India With Bombing  
</P>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- Indian jets fired upon suspected Islamic  
separatist hideouts along the disputed Kashmir border, but wary 
neighbor Pakistan said Indian aircraft bombed its territory and 
threatened to retaliate. Indian officials said jets and helicopter 
gunships fired at what they described as Pakistan-backed separatist 
guerrillas, entrenched in the mountains of Indian-held Kashmir. 
Pakistan called the airstrikes a grave escalation of tensions. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Rejects Base-Closing Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate today decisively rejected the  
Clinton administration's request to close more military bases as a 
cost-saving measure. The 60-40 Senate vote rejected a move by Sens. 
John McCain, R-Ariz., and Carl Levin, D-Mich., to authorize a new 
round of base closings in 2001 as part of an $288.8 billion defense 
spending bill for the fiscal year that begins Oct 1. ``The timing 
could not be worse'' for additional base closings, said Senate 
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. He said that, with the military 
already stetched thin by the conflict in Kosovo, it was no time to 
be closing down any military installations. 

</P>
<P>
	La. Candidate's Grandson Is Found  
</P>
<P>
	CASCADE LOCKS, Ore. (AP) -- The missing grandson of former  
Louisiana Gov. Dave Treen was found in good condition today by a 
news helicopter flying over the rugged Columbia Gorge area where he 
had been lost since Saturday. Jason Neville, 20, appeared to have 
set up a camp with a blue tarp and tent and tended to a nearby 
fire. He set out alone Thursday evening on one of Oregon's most 
popular hiking routes, about 40 miles east of Portland. He had been 
missing since Saturday. Treen faces a runoff Saturday for the 
Republican congressional nomination to succeed Bob Livingston. But 
he'd stopped campaigning and went to Oregon while rescue parties 
searched for his grandson. 

</P>
<P>
	NTSB Recommends MD-11 Modifications  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government's transportation safety panel  
is recommending that the autopilot system in the Boeing MD-11 
jetliner be modified to prevent severe reactions when pilots try to 
make flight course changes. The National Transportation Safety 
Board said overreactions caused severe pitching during two 
incidents in 1996 and 1997, seriously injuring four passengers and 
a flight attendant. Boeing has warned of the potential problem in 
flight crew operating manuals. But the safety board wants the FAA 
to order that Boeing place the warning in its agency-approved 
flight manual. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 65  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 65.19 to 10,596.28. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,644-1,229. The Nasdaq was up 16.15 to 
2,397.05. 

</P>
<P>
	Kafelnikov Loses, Agassi Survives  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Top-seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov, struggling since  
gaining the world No. 1 ranking, was ousted from the French Open 
today by unseeded Dominik Hrbaty. Kafelnikov was booed off the 
court after losing the second-round match in straight sets. But 
women's No. 1 Martina Hingis had no trouble. She showed she clearly 
deserves her top ranking with a 6-3, 6-3 victory over Amelie 
Mauresmo. Also advancing was No. 13 Andre Agassi, who fought off 
Frenchman Arnaud Clement 6-2, 4-6, 2-6, 7-5, 6-0. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
