<HEADLINE> Effort To Rush Gun Bill Foiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans blocked a Democratic attempt  
Wednesday to force a vote on new gun restrictions this week, saying 
the House needs to consider changes to the proposals passed by the 
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the National Rifle Association, the father of a girl  
murdered at Columbine High School and the mother of a Virginia boy 
executed a decade ago by a classmate with an AK-47 were scheduled 
to testify Thursday before a House subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	The proceedings are part of what Republicans say will be a  
cautious deliberation over mandatory background checks for all gun 
show transactions and other new restrictions passed last week by 
the Senate in the wake of school shootings in Colorado and Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Judiciary Committee, in a 19-13 vote, rejected ranking  
Democrat John Conyers' effort to rush the Senate's proposals to the 
House floor this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman Henry Hyde said the panel will hold to its plan to  
consider how the Senate bill would affect constitutional rights and 
send a bill to the floor in mid-June. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a Second Amendment, there is a fundamental right that  
we're dealing with and therefore we should move expeditiously but 
not in a stampede,'' Hyde, R-Ill., said. ``We're going to do this 
and we're going to do it right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said the correct action would be to quickly place new  
restrictions on gun purchases. ``This is not a rush but a response 
to the crisis at hand,'' said Rep. Sheila Jackson-Lee, D-Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, cracks continued to appear in Republicans ranks a day  
after House Speaker Dennis Hastert and Hyde voiced support for the 
concept of the Senate bill's restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., said he had problems with many  
details in the Senate bill. Four students were killed in a March 
24, 1998 shooting spree at a Jonesboro, Ark., school. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the Senate's approach last week is what the  
American people expected of a deliberative body,'' Hutchinson told 
the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans are expected to use a Thursday hearing before the  
crime subcommittee of Hyde's panel to grill Clinton administration 
officials on their enforcement of current gun laws and the White 
House's proposed firearms restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans also had scheduled testimony from Wayne LaPierre of  
the National Rifle Association and from Darrell Scott, the father 
of murdered Columbine student Rachel Joy Scott. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats, meanwhile, planned to call as a witness Adam  
Deutchman, a Denver trauma surgeon who treated some of the victims 
of the Littleton, Colo., shootings, aides said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
