<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trial Ordered in Kuralt Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- A trial must be held on whether the  
longtime secret companion of Charles Kuralt is entitled to the late 
television correspondent's Montana fishing retreat, the state 
Supreme Court ruled Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The court overturned a judge's decision that the property  
belonged to Kuralt's widow instead of the woman he shared a secret 
life with for 29 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 4-1 ruling, the court said a trial must be held to  
determine whether a letter written by Kuralt shortly before he died 
two years ago was meant to give the property to Patricia Shannon. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Shannon, a divorced mother of three, met Kuralt in Reno,  
Nev., in 1968, and they began a secret relationship that lasted 
until his death July 4, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	He paid her money and financed her children's schooling. They  
vacationed together and shared a cabin near Twin Bridges, on the 
Big Hole River. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1985, Kuralt gave her a home in Ireland. Four years later, a  
handwritten will by Kuralt gave Ms. Shannon all his Montana 
property. 
</P>
<P>
	But a 1994 will revoked that decision and gave all the holdings  
to Suzanna, his wife of 35 years, and his children. 
</P>
<P>
	In April 1997, Kuralt gave Ms. Shannon a cabin and 20 acres, but  
he did not change his 1994 will dealing with the remaining Montana 
property. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Shannon sued his estate, saying the letter he wrote while  
hospitalized for the last time indicated he wanted her to have the 
holdings -- 90 acres, a refurbished schoolhouse and other buildings 
on the land. 
</P>
<P>
	The widow of the broadcaster known for his ``On the Road''  
series argued that the letter merely showed her husband planned to 
have a lawyer draw up the papers so that Ms. Shannon could inherit 
the property. That never happened and the letter was not a legal 
will, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	James Goetz of Bozeman, attorney for Ms. Shannon, said he was  
pleased by the high court's decision that evidence of the 
``long-standing relationship of the parties and their almost 
family-like situation'' can be used in the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``That bodes pretty well for our case,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Todd Hillier, the Bozeman lawyer for Mrs. Kuralt, declined to  
comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
