<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woodard Retires From WNBL To Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) -- Lynette Woodard, the all-time collegiate  
scoring leader and first woman to play for the Harlem 
Globetrotters, said today she will retire from professional 
basketball and return to Kansas as an assistant coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Woodard will work with her college coach, Marion Washington, who  
just completed her 26th season with the Jayhawks. 
</P>
<P>
	Woodard, from Wichita, scored 3,649 points during her career at  
Kansas from 1977-81 and was the Big Eight's player of the decade 
for the 1980s. She also captained the 1984 Olympic gold-medal team. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides playing with the Globetrotters, Woodard played for pro  
teams in Japan and Italy and was an elite draft pick of the WNBA's 
Cleveland Rockers in 1997. She played for the Detroit Shock last 
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
