<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Are Secluded on Fla. Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla. (AP) -- His dog Buddy scampering nearby, President  
Clinton strode up to greet a few people awaiting his arrival at the 
White Oak Plantation. Then he disappeared onto the grounds for a 
secluded vacation far from Washington's glare. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton arrived in Florida's backwoods late Tuesday with few  
plans beyond rest and relaxation -- except maybe playing golf on 
White Oak's nine-hole course or catching a glimpse of a rare white 
rhino that is nesting with a cub near the cottage where he is 
staying with first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's got a better (golf) game than the rhino,'' joked  
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the Clintons rose early and went biking together on White  
Oak's grounds, Lockhart said. Clinton also made calls to Italian 
Premier Massimo D'Alema and Nobel Peace laureate Elie Weisel, then 
went out for a round of golf. 
</P>
<P>
	At some point during his break, Clinton can pore over a fat  
binder of information on Medicare, or select from a stack of books 
he brought with him: ``Lexus to the Olive Tree,'' by New York Times 
reporter Tom Friedman; ``Lucky You,'' by Miami Herald columnist 
Carl Hiaasen; ``The Pivotal Strategy,'' a tome about the developing 
world by Robert Chase, Emily Hill and Paul Kennedy; and ``A 
Reasonable Faith,'' the latest book by the Rev. Tony Campolo, one 
of Clinton's spiritual advisers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart said the Clintons needed this vacation, five months  
into a year in which Clinton was acquitted in an impeachment trial 
and the first lady is entertaining thoughts of launching a campaign 
for the Senate seat being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan, 
D-N.Y. They are vacationing without daughter Chelsea, who still has 
classes at Stanford. 
</P>
<P>
	``It comes at the right time,'' Lockhart said. ``They've both  
been going nonstop since the beginning of the year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons were spending the vacation in seclusion at White  
Oak, a 7,500-acre conservation area inhabited by giraffes, cheetah 
and other rare animals. As soon as Clinton turned in for the night, 
reporters traveling with him were told he would not venture off the 
grounds today. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton had already arrived by the time Clinton flew in  
from Edinburg, Texas, where he spent the day with Vice President Al 
Gore at Gore's annual empowerment zone conference. 
</P>
<P>
	On the way in to White Oak, Clinton -- still in his business suit  
-- halted his bronze Suburban to greet a dozen local residents in 
shorts and T-shirts waiting in front of a small house. 
</P>
<P>
	He turned to leave and discovered an important member of his  
party was missing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hey, where's Buddy?'' Clinton asked. Buddy was off meeting a  
bulldog that was among the well-wishers. Buddy pursued the bulldog 
briefly, but scampered back to Clinton's side when the president 
called him. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons planned to stay in Yulee until late Sunday so they  
can participate in a conference at White Oak by the Democratic 
Leadership Council and its think tank, the Progressive Policy 
Institute. Conference participants are due to begin arriving 
Friday, Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	White Oak is located off an unmarked dirt road about 20 miles  
north of Jacksonville. The Clintons were staying at Roseland, a 
two-story, cedar-paneled, five-bedroom house. 
</P>
</TEXT>
