<HEADLINE> Wis. Man Charged With Hate Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) -- A white man accused of running his car onto  
a sidewalk to hit two black teen-agers on bikes was charged 
Wednesday with hate crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	James G. Langenbach, 27, intentionally swerved his car and sped  
toward the 14-year-old boys as they rode their bicycles, police 
allege. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the boys has been released from the hospital. The other  
was in satisfactory condition Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Langenbach originally faced two counts of intentionally causing  
great bodily harm to a child while armed with a dangerous weapon, 
and two counts of leaving the scene of an injury accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Charges were upgraded Wednesday to two counts each of attempted  
murder while armed with a dangerous weapon, causing great bodily 
harm to a child with a dangerous weapon, and leaving the scene of 
an injury accident. 
</P>
<P>
	The new charges also include the hate crime provision, which can  
add up to 5 years in prison and $5,000 in fines to each charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Robert Jambois would not comment Wednesday on why the  
he sought the hate crime charges in addition to the original 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``The charges in a case are always based on the facts of the  
case,'' Jambois said. 
</P>
<P>
	Langenbach has a history of run-ins with police and has been  
treated for psychiatric problems, records show. He had been placed 
on probation for ramming his car into a van carrying five black men 
eight years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Langenbach remained jail in lieu of $200,000 cash bond. Public  
defender Dennis Egre, Langenbach's attorney, said Wednesday he 
could not comment on a pending case. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, Langenbach faces 120 years in prison on the  
attempted murder charges, 60 years on the assault charges and 16 
years on the flight charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
