<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 09:11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rock Beat: Jonatha Brooke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Singer-songwriter Jonatha Brooke is no  
stranger to loss. 
</P>
<P>
	During three months in 1997, the 35-year-old former dancer  
mourned her father's death and divorced her husband. She left her 
native Boston and headed to Los Angeles for a fresh start. 
</P>
<P>
	Just when she was certain it couldn't get any worse, it did.  
</P>
<P>
	MCA Records, Inc., which had released Brooke's critically  
acclaimed second solo album, ``Ten Cent Wings,'' dropped her in 
February 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was really struggling at first,'' she recalled, sipping  
herbal tea in her dressing room before a show at the Fillmore. 
``How could this happen?'' 
</P>
<P>
	She was midway through a nationwide tour and ``Ten Cent Wings''  
was just beginning to tease the charts when her label asked for a 
``compromise.'' MCA offered half the budget for her next studio 
album. She thought the timing unusual. 
</P>
<P>
	``That implies that this record is already over,'' Brooke said.  
``Why would I want to be involved with you if you want to skimp on 
the next record?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The label had promised to release two singles and make a video.  
Now, all bets were off. Brooke asked for a six-month contract 
extension to give the record time to gain momentum. Little did she 
know that MCA was about to get swallowed up by the corporate merger 
that created the Universal Music Group. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never heard back from them,'' she said. ``That was a Friday;  
the following Monday everyone at the label was told I was 
dropped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stunned, Brooke used her week off to regroup.  
</P>
<P>
	``I so believed in 'Ten Cent Wings' and I was devastated that it  
wouldn't be heard,'' she said. ``The thing that really pulled me 
out was that nothing had changed. ... I was still selling out 
theaters, still getting beautiful audiences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So she headed back out on the road, bringing along a multitrack  
digital recorder for her last few shows. Those concerts ended up 
becoming the basis for her third solo album, ``Jonatha Brooke 
Live.'' It includes songs from the Story, the duo Brooke formed 
with college pal Jennifer Kimball during the early 1990s, as well 
as material from ``Wings'' and ``Plumb,'' her first solo release. 
</P>
<P>
	Spending about $30,000 -- her life savings -- Brooke released the  
live album on her Web site in December. She sold more than 2,000 
copies during the first two weeks, autographing and shipping the 
CDs herself. 
</P>
<P>
	Now available in stores, ``Live'' has sold more than 30,000  
copies, nearly earning back Brooke's savings. Just three months 
ago, she says, Brooke hired a business manager and stopped writing 
checks to the band and paying all the bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooke admits she's unusually well off for an artist who created  
a label to promote herself. She can afford to travel with a 
four-piece band and ``people already know who I am and I do have an 
audience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buoyed by that confidence, Brooke and her manager, Patrick  
Rains, struck a deal with Koch Distribution, a Port Washington, 
N.Y.-based outfit that also handles fellow indie folkie Ani 
DiFranco. That got ``Live'' to record stores and radio stations; 
they've already shipped more copies than MCA did for ``Wings,'' 
Rains said. 
</P>
<P>
	Like DiFranco, Brooke said her career is flourishing without a  
major label and sees no reason to seek out a new contract. She and 
Rains do lament Brooke's lack of mainstream airplay -- something 
smaller, independent labels often find almost impossible to secure. 
Even DiFranco, who has a massive following and more than a dozen 
albums to her credit, has enjoyed only limited airplay on a single 
from her 1998 album, ``Little Plastic Castle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're going to sell hundreds of thousands of records  
you're going to have to embrace the structure somehow,'' admits 
Andy Allen, president of the New York-based Alternative 
Distribution Alliance, a Koch competitor. More than 75 percent of 
the music sold is produced by a major label, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, ``(Brooke's) alignment with Koch is something  
you'll see a lot of,'' Allen said. And to be successful out on 
one's own, the artist must ``have to have a real understanding of 
how to reach your fan base.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That may be Brooke's greatest strength. The connection with her  
audience at a recent performance at the Fillmore was palpable. 
</P>
<P>
	She packed the house, capturing the thirtysomething audience  
with an accessible, on-stage manner as she interspersed ballet 
stretches with snips of chatty dialogue. She's an understated, but 
incredibly creative acoustic guitarist, backed by a drummer, 
guitarist, bassist and the keyboard-playing, backup vocalist Ingrid 
Graudins, who seemed to have a loyal following all her own. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooke's father was a journalist, her mother a poet, and their  
daughter obviously inherited a writing gene. Her lyrics are 
introspective, but not whiny; sentimental, not schmaltzy. And 
Brooke strips down to the core of her emotions -- inviting, 
welcoming. 
</P>
<P>
	During a haunting rendition of the traditional Scottish ballad,  
``In the Gloaming,'' the audience held its collective breath, 
allowing Brooke and Graudins to cast their spell. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooke says her fans are ``exquisite music listeners'' who  
``want to be challenged by what they listen to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In retrospect, it was such a gift to be cut loose when I  
was,'' she says. ``I think I'm going exactly where I want to go. I 
just feel better and better about what I do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few months after Brooke was dropped, MCA pared down  
substantially after the merger and left a lot of artists stranded, 
wondering what to do, she said. Performers who had had deals with 
Geffen, MCA, Island, Mercury and others found themselves shopping 
for a new label. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboy Junkies, an alternative-folk band with more than a  
decade of experience, had just released its second album for Geffen 
as merger panic began to build in June. The band hired its own 
promoters and publicists and, like Brooke, launched an extensive 
tour. 
</P>
<P>
	Huffamoose, a jazz-influenced rock band, didn't quite have the  
grassroots support to fall back on, but its 1997 major label debut 
got decent sales and the band felt reasonably secure in its 
relationship with Interscope. But after a few months back in the 
studio, the ax fell. Huffamoose is now looking at other labels or 
self-promotion. 
</P>
<P>
	Advice? Brooke believes artists can achieve more success when  
they build their popularity ``organically,'' from a solid base of 
steady touring. She looks to Shawn Colvin -- who won Grammys for 
song of the year and record of the year in 1998 after more than 20 
years in the business -- as a role model. 
</P>
<P>
	``She just worked and worked and worked,'' Brooke said. ``I  
admire her stamina and conviction. She's a great example of how if 
you're not able to tour, then your career will be short. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really love performing. It's still a joy. The schlepping  
part is less because I'm not lugging my guitar through the 
airport.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The singer's warmth, maturity and experience come through in her  
steady gaze as she sits cross-legged on a sofa. She runs a hand 
through her super-short, reddish-blond hair and is thankful to be 
asked how she's doing after her tumultuous year. 
</P>
<P>
	She has accumulated a lifetime of lyrics, but is ``definitely on  
solid ground,'' she answers with a smile. 
</P>
<P>
	And that should make a great launching pad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
