<DOCNO> APW19990526.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 09:41:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox May Get Others' Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Boston Red Sox' plans to obtain 24 parcels of  
land in an effort to build a bigger, new version of Fenway Park has 
raised questions about the rules by which the city can take land 
away from one private property owner and give it to another. 
</P>
<P>
	Legally, attorneys who specialize in eminent domain, or  
governmental land taking, say the Red Sox and the city are likely 
to win in any court challenge from landowners. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Red Sox move ahead with their plan, the city would take  
24 properties, valued at an estimated $65 million, and offer 
landowners fair prices for the properties. The team would then 
reimburse the city. 
</P>
<P>
	If there are legal challenges, the government may have to prove  
that the area around the park is in need of a makeover. If a 
government classifies an area as being in bad shape, it often has a 
greater ability to confiscate one property owner's land in that 
area and sell it to another. 
</P>
<P>
	But that could be difficult in the Fenway area, which has a  
thriving commercial district and lots of university students. 
</P>
<P>
	``Blight is when there's no land value,'' Tom Piper, a scientist  
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Department of Urban 
Studies and Planning, told The Wall Street Journal's New England 
Section. 
</P>
<P>
	He said while the team's plans might improve the area, what  
exists there now hardly qualifies as a neighborhood in need. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fenway is a very urban, mixed-use development where people can  
live, work and play,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 01:11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Meningitis Vaccine Study Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Researchers have found that college students  
living on campus are about three times more likely to contract 
meningitis infections than classmates who live off campus. 
</P>
<P>
	The analysis released Tuesday in The Journal of the American  
Medical Association was performed by researchers at Johns Hopkins 
University School of Public Health. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings prompted the American College Health Association to  
renew its 1997 recommendation that all college students consider 
getting vaccinated against meningococcal disease, which can cause 
meningitis or an overwhelming and often fatal blood infection 
called meningococcemia. 
</P>
<P>
	Meningococcal disease afflicts 125 to 175 college students  
annually and kills 15 to 20 of them, according to public health 
estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	But the risk among college students generally is about one in  
100,000 yearly, and in college students living on campus about 3 in 
100,000 yearly, according to the new study, led by Dr. Lee H. 
Harrison, now of the University of Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	The low risk and the hope of an upcoming vaccine that will cover  
more strains of bacteria have led the American Academy of 
Pediatrics and the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices for 
the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention to refrain 
from recommending routine immunization. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some parents will ask for or insist upon the vaccine in the  
setting, and that's OK, but the risk is not high enough to 
recommend routinely,'' said Dr. Neal A. Halsey, chairman of the 
committee on infectious diseases for the pediatrics group. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. James Turner of the American College Health Association said  
the increasing number of outbreaks points to the wisdom of routine 
vaccination. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1980 to 1993, there were 21 U.S. outbreaks of meningococcal  
disease, three of which occurred in colleges, his group says. From 
1994 to 1996, there were 51 outbreaks, six of which occurred in 
colleges, it says. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are so many risks that we as parents worry about when  
kids go off to school,'' Turner said. ``This is one of those rare 
risks we can virtually eliminate with a vaccine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Melanie Benn headed off to college in 1995, she looked  
forward to living in northern California and to enjoying her 
independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Within months, she was back home in San Diego, a quadruple  
amputee, having barely survived meningococcal disease. 
</P>
<P>
	She almost certainly could have avoided it if she had been  
immunized, and she wants other people to know. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is something you can prevent,'' Benn said. ``I don't know  
how to get people to realize that. Usually it takes a tragedy to 
get people to realize that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Benn had spent a semester at Humboldt State University in  
Arcata, Calif., and had lived in a dormitory. Researchers say dorms 
probably contribute to spreading meningococcal bacteria the same 
way that crowding recruits into barracks does -- a fact the military 
discovered during World War II. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
