<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> La. Candidate's Grandson Is Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CASCADE LOCKS, Ore. (AP) -- The missing grandson of former  
Louisiana Gov. Dave Treen was found in good condition today by a 
news helicopter flying over the rugged Columbia Gorge area where he 
had been lost since Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Neville, 20, frantically waved metal pans to a KOIN-TV  
news helicopter. He appeared to have set up a camp with a blue tarp 
and tent and tended to a nearby fire. Neville was seen drinking 
from a canteen, wearing a white T-shirt and khaki pants. 
</P>
<P>
	At the base camp, Treen was hugging his daughter, Jennifer  
Neville, the missing hiker's mother. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's him!'' Mrs. Neville screamed through tears as she  
watched the live TV pictures. ``If it's not it's his twin, baggy 
pants and all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just so thankful to God,'' she said. ``It's the greatest  
day of my life.'' Through tears, Treen added, ``It's probably the 
most emotional moment of my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was spotted in an area where searchers had not been looking,  
on the southeast side of Wahtum Lake, about six miles from the 
Eagle Creek trailhead above the snowline. 
</P>
<P>
	About an hour after Neville was spotted, KOIN reported that its  
helicopter had landed and picked him up. But rescue officials said 
later that the effort was aborted because of the rugged conditions 
and plans were to bring in a National Guard helicopter to bring 
Neville out later this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Treen, 70, was elected Louisiana's governor in 1979 -- the  
state's first GOP governor since Reconstruction -- and was defeated 
in a bid for re-election in 1983 by Democrat Edwin W. Edwards. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Treen, who served in Congress from 1973 until he became  
governor, is trying to return to the House, running for the seat 
vacated by Rep. Bob Livingston. He faces a runoff Saturday against 
fellow Republican David Vitter. Treen had canceled all campaign 
appearances Tuesday and flew to Oregon with his daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	``The campaign is not on my mind at this point,'' Treen had said  
Tuesday. ``There's nothing I would not do or give up to find 
Jason.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Treen and Vitter were the top two vote-getters in a May 1  
primary in which former Ku Klux Klan leader David Duke finished 
third. 
</P>
<P>
	Neville, a student at Louisiana State University, had taken time  
off from college to work for AmeriCorps, the domestic equivalent of 
the Peace Corps, teaching poor children in Portland to read. 
</P>
<P>
	He set out alone Thursday evening on the Eagle Creek trail, one  
of Oregon's most popular hiking routes, near the river town of 
Cascade Locks, about 40 miles east of Portland. Officials said he 
wanted to be by himself in the wilderness when he turned 20 at 
midnight Friday. He was due back on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	KOIN-TV helicopter pilot Warren Petrie said he was attracted to  
the area by the light reflecting off the pans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just great news to be in right place at the right time,''  
Petrie said in his live report. ``You can see the smile on his 
face.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Louisiana, Treen campaign manager Jay Zainey said volunteers  
and staffers at headquarters cheered, hugged and wept with joy when 
they learned Neville was safe. 
</P>
<P>
	``God almighty, it was like we just won the campaign. More  
important than that,'' he said. ``We're still on the high.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
