<DOCNO> APW19990526.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 02:51:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> End to Gun Hunting Lessons Sought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) -- Rifles and shotguns are regularly brought to  
schools across Wisconsin for courses to train thousands of young 
hunters. 
</P>
<P>
	But at least one district has reconsidered the gun safety  
program after activists questioned the wisdom of bringing weapons 
on campus. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's find another place for it so we don't send mixed  
messages to our students about weapons,'' said Andrea Utrie, a 
teacher in Beaver Dam about 60 miles northwest of Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing reaction to the recent school shootings in Colorado and  
Georgia, Superintendent Richard Fitzpatrick decided to cancel the 
daytime hunter's education classes in Beaver Dam. 
</P>
<P>
	Utrie also wants the nighttime courses canceled -- classes that  
have been offered for 40 years -- and the school board is reviewing 
the request, Fitzpatrick said. 
</P>
<P>
	But gun enthusiasts say educators are going too far. Better to  
teach gun safety, they say, especially in a setting congenial to 
learning. 
</P>
<P>
	James E. Fendry, a lobbyist for Wisconsin Pro-Gun Movement,  
which has ties to the National Rifle Association, says talk of 
gun-free schools is an ``overreaction based upon total ignorance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Every state except Alaska mandates that hunters receive an  
education certificate before they can buy a hunting license, said 
Dave Knotts, executive director of the International Hunter 
Education Association headquartered in Wellington, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 700,000 people, mostly youths, graduate from the classes  
annually, and many are taught in schools, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Department of Natural Resources, said 839 hunter's  
safety classes were offered across Wisconsin last year and that 
265, or about one-third, were taught in schools for children ages 
12 to 16. 
</P>
<P>
	``You really don't need the guns to teach the course, but it is  
kind of like trying to teach driver's ed without walking out to the 
car,'' Knotts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
