<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philly May Get DisneyQuest Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Walt Disney Co.'s plans to open a  
high-tech entertainment center in Philadelphia drew a step closer 
to reality with the creation of a joint venture to develop the 
downtown site. 
</P>
<P>
	The Goldenberg Group Inc. said Tuesday it would team up with the  
Pennsylvania Real Estate Investment Trust (PREIT-Rubin) to develop 
the $150 million Pavilion at Market East. 
</P>
<P>
	The block-long project, scheduled to open in the summer of 2000,  
will include the five-story DisneyQuest amusement park, as well as 
a 20-screen movie theater, health club and about 400,000 square 
feet of additional retail space. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenneth Goldenberg, president of the Goldenberg Group of Blue  
Bell, said PREIT-Rubin offers an excellent supply of capital as 
well as experienced leasing staff who could attract retailers. The 
developer has said he hopes to bring in another high-end department 
store, an F.A.O. Schwarz toy store and a Benetton sports cafe. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Goldenberg/PREIT joint venture creates terrific synergies,  
and I am very excited about them joining with us on this project,'' 
Goldenberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Edward G. Rendell on Tuesday lauded the joint venture as a  
step forward in advancing the city's efforts to market itself as a 
vacation spot. 
</P>
<P>
	``PREIT-Rubin is not only one of the best developers in the  
Delaware Valley, it is one of the best developers anywhere in 
America,'' Rendell said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The combination of the Goldenberg Group's aggressive,  
ground-up development experience and PREIT-Rubin's long history of 
achievement and extensive leasing capabilities make this a terrific 
combination,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney announced plans in December to open DisneyQuest, which  
will allow visitors to play interactive fantasy-adventure games 
just a few blocks from the Liberty Bell and Independence Hall. 
Officials said they hope the center will attract about one million 
visitors a year by recreating the Disney experience with computer 
animation. 
</P>
<P>
	The city is expected to offer $25 million in tax breaks, improve  
sidewalks and lighting, and renovate the closest subway station. 
Disney will spend about $90 million on the attractions. 

</P>
</TEXT>
