<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Star Watch: Julia Roberts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- As a movie star, Julia Roberts is worth $20  
million a film at last count. 
</P>
<P>
	But that's very different from playing a star, Roberts explains  
over a double soy cappuccino, a delicacy that seems to be a 
necessary component of, well, being a star. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just because you share an occupation with someone doesn't mean  
you're the same person,'' says Roberts, as she tries to distance 
herself from Anna Scott, the actress who sets Hugh Grant's and the 
world's hearts aflutter in ``Notting Hill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Richard Curtis' screenplay for the romantic comedy is  
being viewed as a follow-up to his box-office hit ``Four Weddings 
and a Funeral,'' the earlier Grant movie offered nothing to compare 
with Roberts' star wattage, either on or off the screen. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``Notting Hill,'' Anna Scott's face enlivens posters and  
billboards, though it takes a chance encounter with the aw-shucks 
west London bookseller William (played by Grant) to bring the 
paparazzi swooping down upon her. 
</P>
<P>
	During one crucial dinner scene with William's friends, Anna  
ponders the time in her career when -- or so the script envisions it 
-- ``my looks will go. They'll find out I can't act, and I'll become 
a sad, middle-aged woman who looks a bit like someone who was 
famous for a while.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Exactly Roberts' own worries, right?  
</P>
<P>
	``No, I don't have those concerns at all,'' she says, chatting  
amiably in an interview at the Dorchester Hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	``Again, Anna and I are different people,'' Roberts continues,  
displaying little sign of the jet lag she says she is feeling. 
``Anna is still unsure of her own self-worth, whether it be as an 
actor or just as a person on the planet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to just reconcile the differences between us,'' she  
says. ``Anna is a lot more fragile than I am, and what is written 
(about her) concerns her a lot more than it concerns me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, much has been written about Roberts in the 13 years  
since the small-town girl from Smyrna, Ga., became an actress, 
hitting an early peak with ``Pretty Woman'' at age 22 and fast 
eclipsing her older brother, actor Eric Roberts (``Runaway Train,'' 
``It's My Party''), in the fame game. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the coverage has detailed her recalcitrance toward the  
media, which avidly chronicled Roberts' numerous celebrity 
boyfriends -- from Kiefer Sutherland and Jason Patric to 
singer-actor Lyle Lovett, to whom she was briefly married. 
</P>
<P>
	During the interview, Roberts admits to not having a date for  
the imminent London premiere of ``Notting Hill,'' since current 
boyfriend Benjamin Bratt is in Los Angeles making a film with 
Rupert Everett, Roberts' erstwhile co-star (``My Best Friend's 
Wedding'') and friend. 
</P>
<P>
	(That very premiere made English headlines for -- gasp! horror! --  
the actress' refusal to shave her armpits.) 
</P>
<P>
	Now 31, after weathering a rough patch in her career, Roberts  
speaks with the self-possession of a still-young veteran and the 
savvy of someone fully expecting to stay the course. 
</P>
<P>
	She shortly begins work on her next film, Steven Soderbergh's  
``Erin Brockovitch,'' for which she is reportedly is being paid $20 
million -- the sort of Hollywood paycheck traditionally reserved for 
the guys. 
</P>
<P>
	Dressed in leather pants, her hair darker and straighter than it  
has often appeared, Roberts makes a ready and agreeable 
conversationalist. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the risk of exhibiting hubris, I think I have evolved  
beyond the sense that one's worth is based on a stranger's 
evaluation,'' she says. ``I'm really sure of who I am and why I do 
the things that I do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it seems to be true that Roberts tends to do her best  
work when she smiles -- that radiant visage in the ``Notting Hill'' 
ads is no accident -- and stumbles when she frowns. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a skill. It's not a gift,'' Roberts says of that  
star-making grin. ``If you want to appreciate somebody for it, then 
appreciate my parents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If people support me ... they must support my desire to be a  
good actor, and in order to be a good actor, it is my obligation 
... to try different things,'' she says. ``If I did the same thing 
all the time, how quickly would people get bored? They'd be like, 
`She's smiling again. Oh God, that smile.''' 
</P>
<P>
	With 1996's ``Mary Reilly,'' for example, ``people were saying,  
`She's so dour,''' recalls Roberts. ``But what on Earth does Mary 
Reilly have to smile about, getting up at 4 a.m. and spit-shining 
shoes? Should I be singing a little song? It was as if people were 
criticizing me within the piece itself. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason I do a movie is the same as it was 10 years ago,''  
she continues. ``I like it or I don't, period. I respond on some 
level, which is all my own for reasons I could not begin to 
articulate, and that's why I do it, regardless of what seems to be 
a public demand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of the box-office pressure to smile, ``I do recognize it,''  
Roberts says with a, um, smile. ``Part of my obligation is to at 
least recognize it. That doesn't mean it has to dictate my moves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Notting Hill'' isn't Roberts' only movie this summer. She also  
has the title role opposite her ``Pretty Woman'' co-star, Richard 
Gere, in ``Runaway Bride,'' in which she plays a woman she 
cheerfully calls ``a psychotic. I just loved her. She's a freak.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts expresses amazement that all the ``Pretty Woman''  
principals -- director Garry Marshall included -- could ``finally 
find something, because Richard and I never agree on any script. We 
spent 10 years never agreeing on anything, and I knew Richard liked 
this and it just seemed too much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That intervening decade, of course, saw Roberts become a star.  
</P>
<P>
	As a result, more rests on her career choices now than in the  
days of ``Pretty Woman'' or the earlier ``Steel Magnolias,'' both 
of which brought her Academy Award nominations. (``Notting Hill'' 
goes one better, making Anna Scott an Oscar-winner.) 
</P>
<P>
	Does Roberts agree with some of the premises posed by ``Notting  
Hill,'' starting with the idea that fame is a trap? 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there is an essence of truth to it, but I don't feel  
trapped and I don't feel like anybody but me has the power,'' she 
says. ``I feel liberated and inspired and empowered by my life and 
the choices that I make.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moving on to more important matters, what about the film's  
proposition that a mere mortal has an amorous chance with a 
Hollywood superstar? 
</P>
<P>
	``I've talked to 75 people, and they're all saying this could  
never happen. Where's your sense of adventure? Your sense of 
self?'' she asks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not actor-Julia,'' she adds excitedly. ``I'm Julia. If  
you're with the right person and you have that amazing well of 
communication and support and love, then anything is 
understandable.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
