<DOCNO> APW19990526.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 14:31:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Automakers Expanding With Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- With cars and trucks driving off dealer lots at a  
fast clip, automakers have decided now is the time to build new 
factories and expand old ones. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with excess capacity at factories that make passenger cars,  
demand is so great for their highly profitable sport utility 
vehicles and pickup trucks that carmakers are willing to risk 
adding plants to cash in on the good times. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say they doubt the risks are too great. They say that  
even if the industry hits a slump, it will not be forced into plant 
shutdowns and layoffs like the wholesale cuts of the early 1980s 
that decimated the Big Three. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, most of the expansion is aimed at achieving production  
efficiencies as well as capitalizing on the booming market. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a fair amount of overcapacity in cars right now,''  
said Robert Duronio, manager of product analysis for AutoPacific 
Inc. ``Right now, everyone is looking for more capacity to make 
light trucks and SUVs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the automakers' plans:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Ford Motor Co. on Wednesday announced plans to convert a  
car-production line at a plant outside Kansas City, Mo., to make a 
new top-of-the line pickup truck, the Lincoln Blackwood. 
</P>
<P>
	-- DaimlerChrysler AG on Tuesday said it plans a $435 million  
modernization and expansion program at its plant in Fenton, Mo., 
where the popular Dodge Ram Quad Cab pickup is produced. 
</P>
<P>
	-- General Motors Corp. has said it is considering three new  
factories in Michigan and Ohio -- the first new GM plant 
construction in North America in a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Honda Motor Co. has said it will build a new $400 million  
plant in Lincoln, Ala. The plant will employ about 1,700 workers 
and produce 120,000 vehicles a year, either sport utility vehicles 
or minivans. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Toyota Motor Co. is ramping up production at its new $1.2  
billion Indiana pickup truck plant, where jobs are expected to grow 
to 2,300 in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	These plans come as total sales in the United States are up 9  
percent over 1998. Analysts said those sales, especially the 
booming demand for trucks, is driving the new construction. 
</P>
<P>
	``What you have is a situation where truck plants are operating  
with a lot of overtime, running six days a week with three shifts a 
day,'' said Greg Salchow, an analyst with Roney &AMP; Co. ``Contrast 
that with plants that produce passenger cars, and some of these are 
not even at normal capacity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the exception of GM's proposed plants, most other factory  
projects involve adding capacity to build trucks, minivans or sport 
utility vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Cliff Swenson, an analyst with Monthly Autocast said U.S. auto  
factories had far less unused capacity than others around the 
world. 
</P>
<P>
	Swenson said even if GM adds new factories, it has made  
production cuts elsewhere, so overcapacity would not be a problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Cost-cutting is another reason automakers have built or added  
onto factories. GM says it loses money on nearly all of the small 
cars it sells, and has high hopes for techniques to reduce labor 
costs in new factories. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at Ford have spoken against building new factories,  
choosing instead to convert assembly lines that produced 
slow-selling cars into truck assemblers. Toyota and Honda gain by 
having plants in the United States, free from the shifting tides of 
import economics. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Wall Street brokerage firms recently downgraded their  
ratings on GM and Ford, citing the Federal Reserve Board's policy 
shift that leans towards raising interest rates if the economy 
shows signs of overheating. Current low interest rates have made 
auto loans more affordable. 
</P>
<P>
	But Salchow, the analyst at Roney, said he's not worried that  
the heady pace of sales is about to run out of gas. 
</P>
<P>
	Worries about a sales slowdown are ``more a matter of hedging  
than any real evidence that the market is slowing,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Swenson at Monthly Autocast said the surprising demand for their  
most profitable products was forcing automakers to adjust their mix 
of cars and trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The question is how much do you have to realign your  
production to meet changing consumer demand,'' he said. ``That's 
one of the things they're struggling with.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
