<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Almost Perfect Game Is Recalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Call it imperfect perfection, a perfect game  
that wasn't, and it was ended by a home run that wasn't. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 26, 1959, or 40 years ago today, Harvey Haddix of the  
Pittsburgh Pirates pitched the best game in major league history -- 
and lost. 
</P>
<P>
	The game was so brilliant that no one has come close to matching  
it, yet Haddix wound up with only a loss. He didn't even get a 
raise. 
</P>
<P>
	To make matters worse, Haddix saw the game stripped from  
baseball's official list of no-hitters not long before he died in 
1994. 
</P>
<P>
	His former Pirates teammates who remember that overcast night in  
Milwaukee's County Stadium don't care. They knew what they watched. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the greatest game ever pitched,'' second baseman Bill  
Mazeroski said. ``It was a pleasure to play in that game. It was a 
masterpiece. We knew all along what was going on. Believe me, when 
you play in a game, you know if it's a no-hitter or not, and that 
was something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Twelve innings. Thirty-six Braves batters. No hits. No walks. No  
errors. Not even many great plays to preserve what still is the 
longest single-game stretch of perfection ever in the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	Remarkably, Haddix didn't realize he was perfect.  
</P>
<P>
	The left-hander knew he had a no-hitter, but because he was  
concentrating on the job at hand while sucking between innings on 
lozenges to combat a sore throat and cold, he thought he walked a 
batter. He hadn't. 
</P>
<P>
	The perfect game finally ended in the 13th inning when third  
baseman Don Hoak, the Pirates' emotional sparkplug, threw away 
light-hitting Felix Mantilla's ground ball for an error. 
</P>
<P>
	The perfect game was over. The no-hitter lived on. But not for  
long. 
</P>
<P>
	As storm clouds hovered over the stadium and lightning crackled  
in the distance of a late spring Wisconsin night, Eddie Mathews 
bunted Mantilla to second base. The Braves, still without a hit, 
were within 180 feet of winning a game in which the Pirates had 12 
hits, but never got a runner across home plate. 
</P>
<P>
	Hank Aaron was up next. To set up a possible double play,  
Pirates manager Danny Murtaugh ordered him intentionally walked so 
Haddix could face Joe Adcock. They weren't strangers. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1954, Haddix, then of the St. Louis Cardinals, was set to  
start the All-Star game for the National League. But in the final 
game before the break, Adcock, who died earlier this month, lined a 
ball off Haddix's knee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was never the same pitcher after that,'' Haddix said.  
</P>
<P>
	Haddix had thrown his slider away from Adcock successfully all  
night, but Adcock was looking for it. Just as the wind that had 
whipped across the stadium all night calmed momentarily, Adcock 
drove the ball over the chain link fence in center field for a 
three-run homer. Or at least what the crowd of 19,194 thought was a 
three-run homer. 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron, thinking Adcock's drive had bounced over the wall for a  
ground-rule double, cut across the diamond and Adcock passed him on 
the basepaths and was ruled out. Adcock's hit was officially listed 
as a double. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't until a day later that the National League office  
ruled the final score wasn't 3-0 or, as it was initially listed 
that night as 2-0, but 1-0. 
</P>
<P>
	The home run ball was never recovered. A fan jumped out of the  
stands, grabbed the ball and took off, never to be seen again. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, Haddix didn't know whether to laugh or cry. So,  
fittingly for a person of relatively small stature (5-foot-9, 155 
pounds) and calm demeanor, he did neither. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't know that nobody else had ever pitched a game like  
that,'' he said in 1989. ``I knew something was up, because there 
were a lot of reporters there and that was unusual, because teams 
weren't covered then like they are now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Haddix was behind in the count to only one batter until the  
fateful 13th inning, left fielder Bob Skinner recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a `perfect' perfect game,'' Skinner said. ``Harvey had  
unbelievable control. It was just phenomenal. It was as good as you 
could pitch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Haddix didn't benefit financially from the greatest game ever  
pitch. He wasn't given even a token raise -- this was an era when 
clubs and players routinely fought over $1,000 raises -- and he 
turned down the Ed Sullivan Show's offer of $500 for an appearance 
because the Pirates were traveling. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there is a happy ending to the story. A year later,  
Haddix won twice in the World Series as the Pirates beat the 
supposedly unbeatable New York Yankees, including the Game 7 
decided by Bill Mazeroski's home run. 
</P>
<P>
	Years later, Haddix recalled the World Series, not his imperfect  
game, as his greatest thrill in baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	Haddix, a three-time All-Star, was 136-113 with a 3.63 ERA from  
1952 to 1965 with the St. Louis Cardinals, Philadelphia Phillies, 
Cincinnati Reds, Pirates and Baltimore Orioles. After retiring, he 
was the pitching coach for the Mets and Pirates before dying of 
emphysema in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a damn shame he lost the game,'' winning pitcher Lew  
Burdette said. ``I called him up in the clubhouse and told him I 
scattered my 12 hits and he bunched his one, but he hung up on 
me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
