<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Presidential Candidates in Texas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- The presidential election may not be until next  
year, but Texas this week is a focal point for a campaign that 
already appears to be in full swing. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton was in the state Tuesday, accompanied to the  
Rio Grande Valley by the man he hopes will succeed him, Vice 
President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	When Clinton headed off to vacation in Florida, Gore remained  
for a planned education forum and fund-raising event today in 
Dallas and another one later in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's rival for the Democratic presidential nomination, former  
Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, was in El Paso and Houston, 
tapping backers Tuesday for money to help his so far low-key effort 
to overtake Gore's built-in White House incumbency advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``They might be spinning their wheels if the focus were on the  
general election, but with respect to winning their party's 
nomination, Texas is a key state,'' said Dave Rohde, a political 
science professor at Michigan State University. ``And although 
George W. Bush is the favorite to be the Republican nominee, at 
this point, that's far from certain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	University of Texas political scientist Bruce Buchanan, who  
specializes in presidential campaigns, said it's logical for Gore 
and Bradley to visit Texas because of Bush's notoriety as the 
Republican front-runner. 
</P>
<P>
	``The state is crawling with national reporters,'' he noted.  
``This is the political story of the day. To go where the lights 
are makes political sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican governor, making sure he was heard during the  
Democratic invasion, sounded more like a presidential candidate 
than ever as he used the release of a congressional report about 
the theft of nuclear secrets by China to rip into the Clinton 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``The next president and presidents after that are going to have  
to deal with that,'' said Bush, who officially has formed only an 
exploratory committee to pursue the presidency in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley acknowledged Tuesday knowing little about the Texas  
governor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't really know that much about George W. Bush, quite  
frankly,'' he said. ``I believe in playing one game at a time and 
this game is the primary election. When I have the nomination, then 
we'll focus on whoever is the Republican nominee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was quick to point out, however, what he believed were his  
contrasts with Gore, positioning himself as a government outsider, 
despite an 18-year career in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I've had a more varied life experience than the vice  
president,'' he said. ``I've gotten up a lot of mornings, in fact 
for many years of my life, and gone to work and never thought of 
the federal government. I was just like millions of other Americans 
going to work every day. I think he's had experiences primarily 
based in Washington.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also insisted that during his Senate years, he took risky  
stands on volatile issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the risk of leadership,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's been more cautious,'' Bradley said of Gore.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Gore were in Edinburg for an annual conference on  
empowerment zones -- economically depressed communities targeted 
with tax incentives, job training, low-interest loans and community 
grants for revitalization. The Rio Grande Valley empowerment zone, 
established in 1994, has been called one of the country's most 
successful, and Clinton urged people to push their congressmen to 
continue the program. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore continued that theme at other stops later in the day.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is certainly a labor of love to have the opportunity to  
work with you on community empowerment,'' he told about 400 people 
at an outdoor appearance at McAllen's South Texas Community 
College. 
</P>
</TEXT>
