<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Milosevic Indictment Is Expected  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- According to U.S. officials, the U.N. tribunal  
that prosecutes war crimes will announce as early as tomorrow the 
indictment of Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic for atrocities. 
The indictment has been handed down in The Hague, Netherlands, one 
official declared. Another said: ``The decision has been made.'' 
The U.N. court's chief prosecutor, Louise Arbour, promised ``an 
important announcement'' tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	UN Says Kosovo Is 'Calamitous'  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Wrapping up an 11-day mission to  
Yugoslavia, a U.N. fact-finding team called the situation in Kosovo 
``calamitous'' and said the humanitarian needs are ``immense.'' It 
was the first group of international observers allowed to visit 
Kosovo since the large-scale exodus of ethnic Albanians began two 
months ago. About 840,000 have fled or been driven out by Serb 
forces. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Makes Extensive Strikes  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Dozens of Yugoslav cities were  
struck today during a record 284 NATO attack flights. NATO zeroed 
in once more on President Slobodan Milosevic's villa and hit army 
barracks and command posts. Jets bombarded Kosovo's capital, 
Pristina, its surroundings and the northern city of Novi Sad, Serb 
media reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Works During Vacation  
</P>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla. (AP) -- President Clinton played a round of golf and  
went biking with the first lady today on a secluded plantation in 
northern Florida. Clinton also received his daily security briefing 
on the Yugoslavia campaign, called the Italian prime minister and 
named Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel a special envoy to Macedonia to 
check up on refugees from Kosovo. ``He will stay in touch, as 
you've already seen today,'' White House press secretary Joe 
Lockhart said. ``But it's important from time to time to take a 
chance to get away.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Rejects Base Closings  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ignoring Pentagon pleas, the Senate voted  
60-40 today to block a round of cost-saving military base closings 
proposed for 2001. The Clinton administration argued the closures 
were needed to free up funds to help modernize a military stretched 
even thinner by the conflict in the Balkans. Republicans said they 
mistrusted the process, renewing allegations that Clinton meddled 
in 1995 to save jobs at bases in vote-rich California and Texas. 
And Democratic support for another round was mixed, with Minority 
Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., among the opponents. 

</P>
<P>
	Suit Planned in School Attack  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- A lawyer for relatives of a student slain in the  
Columbine Hich School massacre said today he plans to file a $250 
million lawsuit against the parents of student gunmen Dylan Klebold 
and Eric Harris. Geoffrey Fieger, who is best known for 
representing Dr. Jack Kevorkian, said he will file the lawsuit 
tomorrow in Denver on behalf of Isaiah Shoels' parents. ``Justice 
demands a full accounting of everyone who significantly contributed 
to this massacre,'' Fieger said. 

</P>
<P>
	India Planes Fire on Kashmir  
</P>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- India's aircraft fired on separatist  
guerrillas in Kashmir province today and Pakistan threatened 
retaliation. It was the first use of air power in years in the 
long-running conflict over the Himalayan border region. India said 
it had blasted at Pakistani soldiers and guerrillas entrenched in 
rugged, snowcapped mountains in the Indian-held part of Kashmir. 
Pakistan, however, denied that its troops were involved and said 
India's aircraft had bombed Pakistani territory. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends 171.07 Higher  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rebounded strongly today as  
bargain-hunters returned to a turbulent market following the 
biggest losing streak since late March. The Dow Jones industrial 
average shot up 171.07 points to close at 10,702.16. On the NYSE, 
losers led gainers 1,498-1,477. The Nasdaq rose 46.28 points to 
2,427.18. 

</P>
<P>
	Manchester United Wins Title  
</P>
<P>
	BARCELONA, Spain (AP) -- Scoring two goals in injury time,  
Manchester United edged Bayern Munich 2-1 today to win the 
Champions Cup, the top club title in European soccer. Goals by 
Teddy Sheringham and Ole Gunnar Solksjaer gave Manchester its first 
Champions Cup since 1968. United became the first English team to 
win the triple crown of league championship, Football Association 
Cup and the Champions Cup. 

</P>
<P>
	Yankees Beat Red Sox  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tino Martinez hit a grand slam and Orlando  
Hernandez allowed three hits in seven shutout innings to help the 
New York Yankees beat the Boston Red Sox 8-3 today. Hernandez (5-4) 
walked two and struck out five to beat the Mark Portugal (3-3). 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  
</P>
