<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> San Diego Gets Super Bowl in 2003 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Super Bowl is on its way back to San Diego.  
</P>
<P>
	NFL team owners today picked San Diego to host the 2003 game.  
The only other contender was South Florida, where this year's Super 
Bowl was held. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego replaces San Francisco, which was awarded the game but  
will not have a new stadium ready by 2003. Atlanta hosts the game 
in 2000 followed by Tampa, 2001 and New Orleans, 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are once again on the Super Bowl circuit,'' said Mayor  
Susan Golding, who traveled to Atlanta with a delegation from San 
Diego to make a pitch to NFL team owners. ``The success of our last 
Super Bowl shows that San Diego is the ideal host.'' 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego hosted the game in 1988 and 1998.  
PricewaterhouseCoopers, a New York-based consulting firm, was hired 
by the NFL to study the game's economic impact on the host city 
after the 1998 Super Bowl. The firm estimated that up to $295 
million was pumped into San Diego's regional economy. The 2003 
Super Bowl is expected to yield similar returns. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our analysis shows people who attend the Super Bowl spend  
generously on food, beverages, lodging, transport, retail 
merchandise associated with the game and much more,'' said Robert 
Canton, a member of the firm's financial advisory services 
division. 
</P>
<P>
	James Wiesler, president and chief executive officer of the  
Greater San Diego Chamber of Commerce, said last year's World 
Series and the 1996 Republican National Convention shows San Diego 
is a growing destination for large national events. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision by the NFL team owners marks the second time the  
group has taken the Super Bowl away from San Francisco. The city 
was supposed to have hosted the 1999 championship, but approval was 
contingent upon an estimated $26 million in renovations to 3Com 
Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of pumping the money into upgrades, however, the 49ers  
pushed for a new stadium. In June 1997, voters approved a $525 
million measure for a new stadium and mall next to 3Com Park. 
</P>
<P>
	The stadium wasn't built in time for this year's game and NFL  
team owners didn't feel there were enough guarantees that it would 
be finished by 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
