<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 13:59:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Essence Awards Honor Kirk Franklin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Kirk Franklin, one of the honorees at this  
year's Essence Awards, wasn't expecting a big fuss. 
</P>
<P>
	``I honestly thought it was something that they were going to  
give me in a pre-show or something,'' the popular gospel 
entertainer said. ``I didn't think that I was going to be part of 
the big deal, because usually the gospel music stuff is always in 
the pre-shows or stuff. Like at the Grammys, the gospel awards are 
done way before the show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franklin, 28, along with Lauryn Hill, Chris Rock and others,  
were honored by Essence magazine at the 12th annual awards show on 
April 30. The show will air June 2 on Fox television. 
</P>
<P>
	The Essence Awards honor individuals who have made exceptional  
contributions to the community. Franklin, whose funk beats are 
infused with a religious message, was cited for raising funds to 
help rebuild churches and synagogues destroyed or damaged in bias 
incidents. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's a shining example of the opportunities that life  
offers us all to transform ourselves,'' said Susan Taylor, the 
magazine's editor-in-chief. ``We honored him for his message of 
hope and love that he brings to young people and people of all 
ages.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franklin's life began under troubled circumstances. He was born  
to a teen-age mother who left him to be raised by a religious aunt. 
But the young Franklin didn't always practice what he was taught. 
</P>
<P>
	``I honestly think it's because of all of the things we are told  
that we can't do,'' said Franklin, who is now married and the 
father of three children. ``When you are told all the things that 
you can't do, it's making you want to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After years of resisting the religious message, he came to  
embrace it. ``Church Boy,'' published last year, is the title of 
his autobiography. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though I strayed away as a teen-ager, that stuff is still  
in you, and the circumstances of life, they can have a way of 
waking you up, have a way of saying, 'OK, Lord, I hear you 
calling,''' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether it's a friend dying or whether there are some near  
death experiences of your own, you know, stuff like that will cause 
you to really want to relook at your whole life and your 
situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franklin's work performing for his local choir, The Family, led  
to a record contract. The group sold more than one million copies 
of its debut album. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lean on Me,'' his inspirational collaboration with U2's Bono,  
R. Kelly, Mary J. Blige and Crystal Lewis, was nominated for three 
Grammys, including song of the year. His album, ``The Nu Nation 
Project,'' won a Grammy for best contemporary soul gospel album. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Franklin has been criticized by those who think his music is  
too secular. Those criticisms intensified when his protege group 
God's Property was catapulted to crossover success with the 
dancelike hit ``Stomp'' in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people first said things, it was kind of frustrating, but  
man, you don't think about that kind of stuff anymore because you 
have so many people to reach, and you realize that there is always 
going to be some kind of persecution when you're doing stuff for 
the Lord,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealing with the business of gospel music has been frustrating  
for Franklin, who said some of his personal relationships have 
suffered under the strain of his success. 
</P>
<P>
	``The nature of this business is not built on the rules of  
friendships. This business destroys friendships,'' he said. ``If I 
could do the music without the business, I'd be a very happy man. 
But that's almost like wanting watermelon, but you don't want the 
seeds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franklin refuses to get caught up in the pursuit of money, a hit  
record or fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never want my motive to go into the studio and write a hit,  
but to be able to hear from the Lord, to be able to do a song that 
will reach people,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I mean, the word 'gospel' is to send good news. Gospel is the  
good news of Jesus Christ, and if it's not that, it's just good 
music.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
