<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Sentenced for Thrill Killings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASTORIA, Ore. (AP) -- A judge has sentenced a man to two  
consecutive life prison terms for his role in beachfront thrill 
killings that police say were inspired by repeated viewings of the 
film ``In Cold Blood.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley Price, 24, will be eligible for parole in 30 years for  
his part in the 1997 slayings of a couple watching the sunrise in 
Seaside. Gabriella Goza, 26, and Frank Nimz Jr., 36, were shot in 
the head. 
</P>
<P>
	Police say it was a random killing, inspired by the movie  
version of Truman Capote's book ``In Cold Blood,'' about the 1959 
slayings of four members of a Kansas farm family. 
</P>
<P>
	Price, who was sentenced Wednesday, had claimed that admitted  
triggerman Jesse McAllister was the one who had an intense desire 
to kill someone just to see what it felt like. 
</P>
<P>
	Price said he attempted to talk his friend out of it, but didn't  
really take the fantasy seriously until it got out of control. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors contended Price bought the gun used in the attack  
and knew full well of McAllister's intention as they walked on 
Seaside beach the morning of July 14, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Price, who fled with McAllister to Mexico and was arrested a  
year after the slayings, escaped the death penalty because of a 
deal with Mexican authorities for his return to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	McAllister, 21, who was stopped as he crossed into Texas from  
Mexico, confessed to being the triggerman and is serving two 
consecutive life terms in prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
