<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 14:52:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quayle: Bush Backers Making Mistake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dan Quayle accused establishment Republicans  
on Wednesday of putting polls over principles and making a 
``colossal mistake'' by stampeding to presidential contender George 
W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this thing is just a rush to judgment,'' said the  
former vice president who trails far behind front-runner Bush in 
his bid for the White House in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with The Associated Press, Quayle also proposed  
a missile defense system for U.S. allies in Asia to serve as a 
``clear warning'' against potential Chinese aggression. 
</P>
<P>
	And he accused the Clinton administration of ignoring evidence  
of Chinese espionage in the United States, though acknowledging 
that spying took place during his White House stay. Quayle, who 
served under Bush's father from 1989-93, said the administration 
didn't know about the espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Had we known, we would have done something about it,'' Quayle  
said. ``Our first response would not have been to sweep it under 
the rug.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Bush, a second-term governor of Texas, also has  
criticized Clinton by saying ``only one administration knew'' of 
the espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the FBI has been investigating espionage at nuclear  
labs since the early 1980s. The most prominent case dating from the 
Reagan administration, the one involving former Los Alamos 
scientist Wen Ho Lee did not come to light until 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle is hoping to emerge from early primary fights as the  
leading conservative candidate, but he is having trouble raising 
money. He also must overcome doubts about his ability to win a 
general election after being the butt of jokes during the Bush 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor announced Wednesday that more than half of  
the 222 Republican House members have endorsed him. Supporter Henry 
Bonilla, a GOP lawmaker from Texas, called the development a ``kick 
in the gut'' to Bush rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	But Quayle shrugged it off, saying party leaders are so eager to  
win that they're rallying behind a candidate they know relatively 
little about. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it shows that there is a genuine nervousness in the  
Republican Party and they're trying to go with polls rather than 
ideas -- and that is a colossal mistake. It may feel comfortable 
today, but down deep if you think you're going to win this on what 
public opinion polls say 18 months out, I beg to differ,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you show nervousness like that,'' he said, ``you are in  
trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker replied, ``People know a lot about  
Governor Bush. They know he has made education his top priority. 
They know he has cut taxes. They know he cut welfare. And they know 
he has been able to unite people and build a consensus on 
conservative principles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle said Bush's endorsements could backfire.  
</P>
<P>
	``If he's going to run a status-quo, establishment kind of  
campaign, I think he's going to be in for a rude awakening, because 
Republican voters are looking for action, looking for commitment, 
looking for bold ideas,'' Quayle said. 
</P>
<P>
	The comments may signal a new route of attack against Bush: link  
him to Congress, which is considered weak and wavering by many GOP 
primary voters. Other GOP campaigns could soon follow suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush will make his first campaign trip next month, a  
high-profile journey to Iowa and New Hampshire that rivals hope 
will expose political weaknesses. Lamar Alexander, who is competing 
against Bush for moderate voters, recently called Bush ``completely 
untested.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle accused congressional Republicans of forsaking  
conservative principles to avoid confrontations that might hurt 
them in the polls. ``Congress must focus on tax cuts, choice in 
education ... a missile defense system, not busting the spending 
caps,'' Quayle said. ``This is our agenda and it's barely being 
talked about on the Hill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, in an address to conservative leaders, Quayle received  
several rounds of applause when he railed against the 
establishment. ``If you want to win, wake up, folks!'' he said. 
``The establishment does not win elections when they campaign for 
the Republican Party. Conservatives win elections.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that Bush recently said global warming was a problem.  
``I'm not so sure it will be a popular position in the Republican 
Party to be on the side of (Vice President) Al Gore on 
environmental issues.'' Gore, the Democratic presidential 
front-runner, has warned that rising temperatures threaten the 
world's environment. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who in the past said he ``wasn't sure of the science'' on  
global warming, said in a statement released Wednesday that there 
is disagreement on the cause and impact of global warming but ``the 
issue should be taken seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On China, he said Congress should postpone debate on extending  
most-favored-nation status to Beijing until the United States sorts 
through the espionage fallout. And he said Beijing is not ready to 
enter the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
