<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 171.07 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rebounded strongly today as  
bargain-hunters returned to a turbulent market following the 
biggest losing streak since late March. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average shot up 171.07 points, a rise  
of 1.6 percent, to close at 10,702.16. At one point late in the 
session, the Dow was up 190. 
</P>
<P>
	Going into today's session, the Dow had fallen four straight  
sessions, including a combined 298-point drop in the past two days, 
and was off 5 percent from its May 13 record of 11,107.19. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market was oversold,'' said Tony Dwyer, chief equity  
strategist at Ladenburg Thalmann &AMP; Co. ``It's ready for a bounce.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mostly higher.  
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 20.23 to 1,304.63, and the  
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 45.36 to 2,426.26. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues barely outnumbered advancers on the New York  
Stock Exchange, with 1,498 down, 1,477 up and 557 unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 868.39 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.  
816.28 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 7.50 to 624.84, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 3.82 to 782.66. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.96 to 435.41.  
</P>
<P>
	Investors today returned to some conventional favorites that  
have faltered in recent sessions. IBM, which had tumbled along with 
the entire technology sector, was the strongest of the Dow 
components today. A 2-for-1 split of Big Blue's stock takes effect 
after the close of the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks have been hit particularly hard as concerns  
about potentially higher interest rates drew investors away from 
the high-priced shares that have fed the market's massive gains. 
Through Tuesday, the Nasdaq index had tumbled 10 percent from its 
all-time record of 2,652.05, set April 26. A decline of 10 percent 
or more is viewed as a ``correction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Today, several industry leaders continued to languish. Intel,  
which unveiled a new chip design today, slipped throughout the 
session. But some Internet-related shares rebounded from recent 
losses, including search engine Yahoo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those stocks were hurt by panic selling,'' Dwyer said. ``They  
were ready to come back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The recent slump of Internet stocks, coupled with the market's  
losing streak, created a tough climate for the initial public 
offering of DLJ Direct, the online brokerage unit of Donaldson, 
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc. Its shares rose, but failed to triple or 
quadruple in the manner of previous Internet IPOs. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, DLJ's debut mirrored the IPO Tuesday of  
barnesandnoble.com. The new issue disappointed some traders with a 
modest 27 percent gain in its first day of trading. Today, however, 
barnesandnoble.com made some solid gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's market gained a measure of support from a Commerce  
Department report that showed orders for big-ticket manufactured 
goods fell an unexpectedly sharp 2.3 percent last month. The figure 
offered new evidence that the economy is not overheated. 
</P>
<P>
	Several sectors rebounded today. Drug stocks were higher, led by  
Bristol Myers Squibb. 
</P>
<P>
	Banking and financial stocks also rose, led by Merrill Lynch,  
which led the sector amid fresh rumors it will be acquired by Chase 
Manhattan Bank. Both companies denied the reports. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market seemed to return to the stocks it liked earlier  
this year,'' said A. Marshall Acuff, equity strategist at Salomon 
Smith Barney. 
</P>
<P>
	Benefitting from a slight gain in oil prices Tuesday, shares of  
Dow component Exxon rose. Mobil and Chevron also gained as 
investment bank Schroder Wertheim, which increased its rating on 
the stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Some market weakness was still apparent today as declining  
stocks outnumbered advancers for much of the session. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the healthiest of rallies,'' Acuff said.  

</P>
</TEXT>
