<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Voting on Union Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WATSONVILLE, Calif. (AP) -- Berry pickers employed by the  
nation's biggest strawberry grower voted on whether to unionize 
Wednesday in a key test of a United Farm Workers effort to regain 
the clout it had when Cesar Chavez was its leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago, the UFW committed itself to winning a union vote  
at Coastal Berry Co., hoping a victory there would create momentum 
throughout California's farm fields. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry growers have historically been among the most  
resistant to union organizing. And despite a promise from Coastal 
Berry not to block unions, the campaign has been plagued by 
setbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The UFW organizers have struggled to win the trust of workers  
and faced competition from a rival union backed by Coastal Berry 
supervisors. 
</P>
<P>
	``The strawberry industry wants to stop UFW progress at all  
costs, and Coastal Berry could be a crucial turning point for the 
workers statewide,'' UFW spokesman Marc Grossman said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Coastal's 1,500 employees in the farming communities of Oxnard,  
Watsonville and Salinas were voting by secret ballot Tuesday and 
Wednesday. Their choices: representation by the UFW, its rival, the 
Coastal Berry of California Farm Worker Committee, or no union at 
all. 
</P>
<P>
	In Watsonville, pickers briefly left oceanside fields laden with  
fat red strawberries to place their ballots under the close watch 
of state labor officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The ballot count was delayed Wednesday night as officials  
checked to make sure all voters were currently employed by the 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Coastal Berry President Ernie Farley has said the company is  
neutral on whether its workers should be represented by the UFW or 
the Farm Worker Committee. The UFW has said its rival is a sham 
union that doesn't have the workers' interests at heart. 
</P>
<P>
	Coastal Berry's pickers are treated better than some in the  
berry fields. They earn an average wage of between $7.50 and $8.50 
an hour and have full medical and dental benefits for themselves 
and dependents. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're pretty much in the top of the industry. The dependents  
get health benefits even if they live in Mexico,'' Farley said. 
</P>
<P>
	The union fell into the doldrums even before the 1993 death of  
its legendary founder, Chavez, who inspired thousands of 
farmworkers to join up in the 1970s and '80s. Union membership had 
declined to 20,000 at the time of his death. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of a membership drive begun in 1995, membership is up to  
27,000 now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
