<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuadoreans React to Train Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Ecuadoreans see a countrywoman and her  
three children killed by a train in the United States as a symbol 
of the desperation that forces thousands of them to live -- and die 
-- abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	Julia Toledo, 46, who left for the United States a year and half  
ago looking for work, died under an Amtrak train in Fairfield, 
Conn. on Tuesday as she was trying to snatch her 10-year-old son, 
Jose, out of the way of the train. 
</P>
<P>
	Her three other children raced after her and were struck as  
well. Jose lost his left leg and is in critical condition with head 
injuries in Fairfield's Bridgeport Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``The death of this woman and her children is due to the  
desperation we Ecuadoreans feel to leave the country because of 
economic problems. There is no work here,'' Quito shopkeeper 
Bernardo Delgado said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose was so badly injured that even relatives were unable to  
identify him, and he was initially identified as his younger 
brother, Angel, who was 6. Also killed was Carlos, 12, and Pedro, 
3. 
</P>
<P>
	News of the family's death filled the front pages of Ecuador's  
newspapers Wednesday. Reporters were trying to locate Jose's 
father, Carlos Luis Urgiles, who is thought to be in Ecuador. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecuadoreans expressed sorrow at a desperate single mother dying  
with her family at night far from home. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation of the country gets worse by the day,'' said Dr.  
Nolberto Devia, a physician at a private clinic. ``Everyone wants 
to leave. If I were a young man, I would also try my luck abroad 
like this mother.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This poor Andean nation of 12 million inhabitants is mired in a  
deep economic recession that President Jamil Mahuad has called its 
worst in 70 years. Inflation may top 100 percent this year and the 
economy is expected to contract 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Unemployment stands at 15 percent of the work force but an  
additional 57 percent are underemployed, meaning they have only 
part-time work or their pay does not meet their basic needs. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators in Connecticut are trying to figure out why the  
family was walking on the trestle over a two-lane road at 2:20 a.m. 
Rescuers found backpacks, books, report cards and a Bible strewn 
among the body parts. 
</P>
<P>
	A local newspaper reported that Toledo had quit her job as a  
university janitor recently because raising her four children alone 
and holding a demanding job had become too much for her. 
</P>
<P>
	She had moved out of her apartment and into a YMCA family  
shelter last week, the Hartford Courant reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Toledo was not an American citizen but was living there legally,  
Julia's sister Maria Toledo said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, a group of Ecuadorean immigrants held a vigil for  
Jose outside Bridgeport Hospital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:42:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airline Relaxes Cell Phone Rule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Delta Air Lines is relaxing its rules requiring  
passengers to keep their cellular phones and laptop computers 
turned off before takeoff. 
</P>
<P>
	As of June 1, Delta passengers will be able to use cell phones  
on the ground as long as the plane is parked at the gate and its 
boarding door is open, the Atlanta-based airline said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Captains will also be allowed to OK use of laptops and cell  
phones during extended waits on the runway. 
</P>
<P>
	Airlines restrict onboard use of cell phones and laptops because  
they may interfere with the plane's electrical systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta agreed to the rule changes at the behest of passengers who  
have grown increasingly dependent on their techno toys, said Delta 
spokeswoman Kay Horner. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cell phones are more and more a part of our life,'' she said.  
``They wanted to use them more on board.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal regulations prohibit any use of cellular phones during  
flight and use of laptops below 10,000 feet. Airlines are allowed 
to set their own policies for use on the ground. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 16:21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Maple Leafs Square Buffalo Series </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- On the day after his Maple Leafs rebounded  
for yet another crucial win in the Stanley Cup playoffs, Toronto 
coach Pat Quinn had more to worry about than the groin of Buffalo 
Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to try to get better, and we need to get better,''  
Quinn said Wednesday on the eve of Game 3 of the Eastern Conference 
finals. ``We've got to be better. If we don't, we won't survive 
this series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Quinn's protestations, the Leafs did OK in Game 2,  
jumping to an early 2-0 lead and winning 6-3 to even the series 
heading into Thursday night's game at Marine Midland Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the most goals the Sabres have allowed in the playoffs,  
and the only ones Buffalo got against goalie Curtis Joseph came on 
the vaunted power play. The Sabres have scored at least one 
power-play goal in each of their 12 games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew they were going to come out hard, and they did,'' said  
Sabres center Curtis Brown, who leads the team with five playoff 
goals. ``But it's not about who wins the first game or the second 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's who's the first team to get to four. With Dom out, we  
can't focus on things that we can't control. Those are intangibles 
that you have to work through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But that is the biggest intangible by far. One only needs to  
look back to Buffalo's first-round series sweep of Ottawa, which 
had finished second in the conference and entered the postseason 
with high hopes. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek intimidated the Senators, helping to hold their leading  
scorer, Alexei Yashin, without a point. Buffalo won three one-goal 
games, and Hasek pitched a shutout in the other. 
</P>
<P>
	And no matter what the coaches say, the absence of Hasek has had  
an effect on this series, and not just because the media has said 
so. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always hard to play against Buffalo because of Hasek,''  
said Leafs defenseman Dimitri Yushkevich. ``We make like 50 shots 
and he always stops them all. It's hard to score on them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Hasek doesn't get better quickly, the Sabres will be  
hard-pressed to advance to the Stanley Cup finals for only the 
second time in team history. That they are unbeaten in five home 
games in the playoffs is irrelevant. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Wednesday, the Dominator had some good news for his  
teammates. After medical consultation, he skated for a half-hour 
and liked how he was progressing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt pretty good,'' he said. ``I didn't do everything. I  
didn't stop too many pucks, but my skating was almost without pain. 
I feel closer to playing the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know with this injury I won't be 100 percent. I know that.  
But I've already played with the injury and I wasn't 100 percent. I 
feel I am very close to being in that position, not 100 percent, 
but ready to play and play well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And that might be just what the Sabres need to revert to form.  
This series was expected to be a tight-checking affair, and it 
hasn't been. The teams have combined for 18 goals in what has 
turned into something of a shooting match. 
</P>
<P>
	Without Hasek to confront, the explosive Leafs, who led the NHL  
in scoring during the regular season, have 10 goals against 
seldom-used backup goalie Dwayne Roloson. With Hasek back in there, 
maybe the Sabres will display their customary defensive style of 
play, if only to protect him. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just looking to get back to our game,'' said Sabres  
defenseman Jay McKee, who is a solid plus-7 in the playoffs. 
``We're not happy with that last one. I don't know if Toronto has 
gotten us off our game or if it's just us, but it's too 
run-and-gun.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 22:51:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Memo: China Spying Found in 1984 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The military intelligence assessment was short  
and to the point: China was improving its nuclear warheads by 
stealing technology from the United States. The year: 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	In language similar to that used in the Cox report 15 years  
later, the Defense Intelligence Agency stated that China is ``now 
deriving'' benefits ``from both overt contact with U.S. scientists 
and technology and the covert acquisition of U.S. technology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Increased access to this technology and continued Chinese  
efforts will in the 1980s and early 1990s show up as qualitative 
warhead improvements,'' concludes the DIA document known as an 
``estimative brief.'' It is entitled ``Nuclear Weapons Systems In 
China.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the blame game escalated Wednesday between Democrats and  
Republicans over alleged Chinese espionage, the National Security 
Archive -- a private Washington group -- released the document it had 
obtained from the DIA through the Freedom of Information Act. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the document says people at DIA, and I presume others  
in the intelligence community, understood exactly how the Chinese 
were going to go about improving their arsenal,'' said Jeffrey 
Richelson, who is compiling a 15,000-page collection of 
declassified documents on U.S.-Chinese relations for the archive. 
</P>
<P>
	Richelson said he doubts the DIA memo, dated April 24, 1984, got  
to the National Security Council inside the Reagan White House. But 
``certainly key officials in the government would understand the 
essence of the observation about how the Chinese would go about 
improving their nuclear arsenal,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The assessment stated: ``There is evidence that the Chinese have  
been successful in assimilating into their nuclear weapons program 
United States technology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In some areas, the gap between United States and Chinese  
nuclear warhead technology may begin to narrow,'' the estimate 
concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	Eager to move the blame for China's theft of U.S. nuclear  
secrets away from a Democratic White House and onto the Reagan and 
Bush administrations, Democrats on Capitol Hill circulated a 
document entitled ``What President Bush Knew.'' The five-page 
summary reviews dire warnings about Chinese espionage and security 
lapses at U.S. nuclear laboratories going back to 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	The summary juxtaposed Texas Gov. George W. Bush's strong  
criticism Tuesday of President Clinton with a lengthy recitation of 
incidents from the 1980s and early 1990s about Chinese nuclear 
espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Cox report was released, Bush said, ``There is only  
one administration that has been given the news'' about Chinese 
espionage at weapons labs ``and that's the Clinton administration. 
The interesting question is when did they know?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Democrats' summary targeting the Texas governor's father  
pointed to: 
</P>
<P>
	--Newspaper reports that Chinese intelligence agents had stolen  
nuclear weapons secrets from the Lawrence Livermore National 
Laboratory. 
</P>
<P>
	--A lengthy series of reports by the General Accounting Office --  
Congress' investigative branch -- detailing security problems at the 
weapons labs that made them vulnerable to espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democrats' summary also highlighted a recently published  
comment by Bush administration national security adviser Brent 
Scowcroft that lab security was not an issue when he was in office. 
</P>
<P>
	``If allegations of Chinese spying had been widely known, they  
would have been a major issue in the Clinton-Gore campaign in 
1992,'' responded Karen Hughes, a spokeswoman for Gov. Bush. ``They 
were not'' an issue ``because it's not true'' that the allegations 
were widely known. 
</P>
<P>
	``America deserves leaders who are honest, not partisans who  
attempt to spin their way out of responsibility for a major 
embarrassment that happened on their watch,'' said Hughes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 21:17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Miss Botswana Wins Universe Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT-OF-SPAIN, Trinidad (AP) -- A Botswana woman late Wednesday  
became the last Miss Universe of the century, winning the crown in 
her country's first-ever entry in the beauty pageant. 
</P>
<P>
	Mpule Kwelagobe, 19, reacted with shock, surprise then joy at  
the crowning in this Caribbean country. 
</P>
<P>
	She was announced the winner after responding to a final  
question on whether Miss Universe should be allowed to continue her 
reign if she got pregnant. 
</P>
<P>
	``Personally, I think it should not in any way interrupt her  
duties. She should celebrate her femininity,'' Kwelagobe said to 
wild applause and yells of approval from the audience. 
</P>
<P>
	In second place was Miss Philippines, Miriam Quiambao, a  
23-year-old physical therapist. Miss Spain, 24-year-old Diana 
Nogueria, took third place. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Puerto Rico, 23-year-old Brenda Liz Lopez, was named most  
photogenic and the Miss Congeniality award went to Marisa Ferreira, 
a 21-year-old student from Portugal. 
</P>
<P>
	Kwelagobe's prize means she no longer will she have to describe  
herself as ``unemployed,'' as she did on the pageant entrance list, 
where she said she was awaiting further studies and hoped to become 
an electronic engineer. 
</P>
<P>
	Her prize includes a $40,000 salary for the year's reign, along  
with a mountain of cash, a plush apartment in New York City for the 
year and a bonanza of designer clothes, jewelry, luggage and 
makeup. 
</P>
<P>
	She was chosen from five finalists, including beauty queens from  
the Philippines, South Africa, Spain, and Venezuela. Ten 
semifinalists were chosen, out of 83 contestants, after parading in 
swimsuits and evening gowns by designer Diane von Furstenberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Their winner was announced by host Jack Wagner -- whose ``Melrose  
Place'' ended its long run on American television on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowning occurred in a converted U.S. Army helicopter  
hangar, a 3,900-seat auditorium that was sold out for the gala 
being broadcast live to 80 countries by CBS. The faded green 
corrugated iron building's interior has been converted into a 
lavish auditorium featuring artwork by Trinidadians. 
</P>
<P>
	Pier One, a private entertainment center, was the site of  
demonstrations by hundreds of people Tuesday demanding an 
explanation of how a worker with the Trinidad and Tobago Electrical 
Commission was electrocuted Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Moonilal Hardeen, 31, was killed by a surge of electricity that  
the electric company said appeared to come from a standby 
generator. 
</P>
<P>
	Among judges was world heavyweight boxing champion Evander  
Holyfield, Buffalo Bills linesman Bruce Smith and Sirio Maccioni, 
owner of New York's chic Le Cirque restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on hand was U.S. business mogul Donald Trump, who owns the  
pageant with CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	Most ordinary Trinidadians seem to relish the entire affair,  
which has also reinforced admiration for a hometown heroine, 
outgoing Miss Universe Wendy Fitzwilliam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 21:17:55 </DATE_TIME>
