<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 04:12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	India Launches Kashmir Airstrikes  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Indian air force jets and helicopters  
fired on intruders in the disputed Kashmir province today, marking 
the most serious escalation of fighting since both countries tested 
nuclear weapons last year. Indian officials charge that about 600 
infiltrators -- allegedly Afghan mercenaries supported by Pakistani 
forces -- moved into the Indian-controlled Himalayan region earlier 
this month, posing a threat to Indian supply lines in the Himalayan 
state.	   Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz immediately issued a 
stiff warning to India. ``We are retaliating and we will 
retaliate,'' he warned. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Demands End To NATO Strikes  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Warning that the growing number of alliance  
attacks could destroy any chance of a political settlement, Russia 
demanded an immediate halt to NATO airstrikes against Yugoslavia 
today. Viktor Chernomyrdin, Russia's special envoy on Kosovo, said 
he would press for at least a temporary and immediate halt to the 
airstrikes during talks today with Deputy Secretary of State Strobe 
Talbott and Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari. ``The result of the 
upcoming negotiations on Wednesday should be a stop to missile and 
bomb strikes on Yugoslavia,'' he told reporters. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO To Increase Kosovo Force  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- After approving a plan to nearly  
double the size of a proposed peacekeeping force to roughly 50,000 
troops, NATO launched fierce air attacks against Yugoslavia today. 
The original NATO plan called for 28,000 troops. Diplomatic efforts 
including an American and a Russian envoy were also set to resume 
in Moscow today after the night of heavy attacks that Serbian media 
said included hits on Kosovo's capital, Pristina, and the northern 
city of Novi Sad. Sustained NATO pounding also was reported in 
central and southern regions of Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	JonBenet's Brother Said Questioned  
</P>
<P>
	BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- JonBenet Ramsey's 12-year-old brother was  
reportedly questioned by the grand jury investigating the little 
girl's death. Burke Ramsey appeared before the panel last week, 
according to today's Denver Rocky Mountain News, which cited a 
family friend, and KUSA-TV. Boulder authorities would not comment 
on whether the boy appeared. However, authorities have said 
previously that Burke is considered a witness in the case. Burke 
was 9 when his sister was found beaten and strangled in the 
basement of the family's Boulder home in 1996, the day after 
Christmas. 

</P>
<P>
	China Reacts To Spying Allegations  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- For many Chinese, the U.S. congressional report  
alleging that China stole American weapons secrets was another 
unfriendly salvo from a nation that seems intent on turning China 
into the new enemy. From China's Foreign Ministry to people on the 
street, reaction was the same: the allegations were designed to 
divert attention from NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in 
Yugoslavia on May 7. Some couldn't see what the fuss was about, 
saying all nations spy. Others doubted that the United States would 
be so lax as to let another country steal its most prized nuclear 
weapons secrets. 

</P>
<P>
	Meningitis Vaccine Study Released  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- An analysis in The Journal of the American  
Medical Association shows that college students living on campus 
are about three times more likely to contract meningitis infections 
than those who don't. The findings prompted the association to 
renew its 1997 recommendation that all college students consider 
getting vaccinated against meningococcal disease, which can cause 
meningitis or an overwhelming and often fatal blood infection 
called meningococcemia. Meningococcal disease afflicts 125 to 175 
college students annually and kills 15 to 20 of them, according to 
public health estimates. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Finish Mixed  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks finished mixed today as investors  
turned cautious amid a sharp overnight fall on Wall Street and a 
stronger Japanese currency. The Nikkei gained 16.29 points, closing 
the day's trading at 16,230.52 points. 

</P>
<P>
	Braves 5, Brewers 2  
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Pinch-hitters Keith Lockhart and Javy Lopez  
homered to start the ninth and Walt Weiss homered later in the 
inning last night, giving the Atlanta Braves a 5-2 victory over the 
Milwaukee Brewers. Atlanta connected for back-to-back pinch-hit 
homers for the first time in team history. Greg Maddux, who has not 
won since April 29, allowed five hits in seven innings and left 
leading 2-0. He wound up with a no-decision and avoided his first 
four-game losing streak in three seasons. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
