<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Nixes Charge Involving Fetus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- A state appeals court Wednesday threw out  
the case against a woman accused of trying to drink her fetus to 
death, ruling that she could not be charged with attempted murder 
because a fetus is not a human being. 
</P>
<P>
	In a case closely watched by civil libertarians and people on  
both sides of the abortion debate, the 2nd District Court of 
Appeals ruled in favor of Deborah Zimmerman, whose daughter was 
born in 1996 with a blood-alcohol level of 0.199 percent, twice the 
level considered intoxicated under Wisconsin law. 
</P>
<P>
	``The term `human being' was not intended to refer to an unborn  
child and Deborah's prenatal conduct does not constitute attempted 
first-degree intentional homicide and first-degree reckless 
injury,'' the court ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Zimmerman spent the day her daughter was born drinking at a  
bar, building a blood-alcohol level exceeding 0.30 percent at the 
time of birth. 
</P>
<P>
	At the hospital, Ms. Zimmerman allegedly told a nurse: ``I'm  
just going to go home and keep drinking and drink myself to death 
and I'm going to kill this thing because I don't want it anyways.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Zimmerman's baby was born limp and pallid. Ms. Zimmerman's  
lawyer, Sally Hoelzel, said the girl -- now 3 years old and living 
in foster care -- is healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Zimmerman has yet to stand trial. She took her case to the  
appeals court after a trial-level judge refused to dismiss the 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Zimmerman contended that her alcohol abuse during pregnancy  
was directed toward her own body and the fetus she carried -- not 
another human being. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities argued that Ms. Zimmerman should be prosecuted for  
attempted murder based on the state's ``born alive'' rule. The law 
says a person can be charged with murder if he or she harms a 
pregnant woman and her fetus is born alive and then dies. 
Prosecutors argued that the law should be extended to attempted 
murder if a fetus is born with injuries but survives. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court ruled Wednesday that that was not the  
Legislature's intent. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Zimmerman has been in prison for violating her bail  
conditions in the case and is due for release in September. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Zimmerman's attorneys and civil libertarians had argued that  
if the state succeeded, women would risk criminal charges if they 
did anything -- such as smoking or drinking -- that could harm a 
fetus. 
</P>
<P>
	Simon Heller, litigation director for the Center for  
Reproductive Law and Policy, which handled Ms. Zimmerman's defense, 
said there have been many rulings that a fetus is not a human 
being, including the U.S. Supreme Court's Roe vs. Wade decision 
legalizing abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	The South Carolina Supreme Court, however, ruled that a viable  
fetus is a person under a statute punishing child abuse, he said. 
The court did not apply it to murder laws in that case. 
</P>
<P>
	Barbara Lyons, executive director of Wisconsin Right to Life,  
said the Wisconsin appeals court is ``behind the times'' because 
Wisconsin has passed laws to protect fetuses. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court had earlier passed the case along to the  
Wisconsin Supreme Court without ruling. But the case was sent back 
to the appeals court after the high court tied 3-3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 22:31:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quayle Casts Himself As Outsider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dan Quayle once ranked near the top of the  
Republican establishment. Now he is campaigning against it, 
complaining about its poll-driven ``rush to judgment'' in favor of 
George W. Bush for president in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	In Quayle's campaign script, the Texas governor is the  
establishment candidate, in the early lead because nervous 
Republicans are behaving like Bill Clinton and shaping their 
choices to the public opinion polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle casts himself as the outsider even though he got his  
national start as a ranking insider, in four years as vice 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	The questions from conservative activists still are addressed to  
``Mr. Vice President,'' an echo of his term as No. 2 to President 
George Bush, father of the current GOP leader. Not front-runner, 
Quayle contends. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can talk all you want to about polls and all this happy  
nonsense, who the front-runner is, but you're not going to know who 
the true front-runner is until they vote in Iowa, on February 7,'' 
he said Wednesday in an interview with The Associated Press in the 
conference room of his own pollster's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle's dispute with candidate-rating polls is understandable;  
they rank Bush far ahead of him, and Elizabeth Dole second on the 
list of 11 prospects for the 2000 nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``This presidential campaign, like most presidential campaigns,  
is going to come down to a choice between the establishment and a 
conservative,'' Quayle said. He said he and Bush will be the GOP 
finalists. 
</P>
<P>
	With Bush harvesting endorsements -- most of the GOP governors  
and more than half the Republicans in Congress -- and far ahead in 
campaign fund raising, Quayle and the rest of the entries have to 
slow the train if they are to catch it. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle insists that he will, that he can prove himself a winner  
in the opening 2000 primaries. Win, he said, and the past setbacks 
and stumbles will not count any more. Not even the Quayle jokes, 
which he insists do not bother him and will not hurt him. ``Jokes 
don't determine. Election issues do, ideas do,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the laughing matter of late-night television certainly has  
not helped his image. His counter is that it proves he can take 
hits, get up and keep fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Republicans today, they have become captivated by polls,''  
Quayle said. ``I think it shows that there is a genuine nervousness 
in the Republican Party and they're trying to go with the polls 
rather than ideas and that is a colossal mistake. ... I think that 
this thing is just a rush to judgment and shows that Republicans 
are nervous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What they are nervous about is winning the White House in 2000,  
after two Democratic terms. And about defending their narrow 
control of the House. 
</P>
<P>
	So when Bush soared in the polls, even before his landslide  
re-election as governor, he began reaping endorsements and rolling 
up campaign money. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle prefaced his own campaign with a 30-state, 70-candidate  
drive for Republican congressional candidates in 1996, the kind of 
effort that can gain allies for a presidential candidate. But in 
the endorsements game, Bush is the faraway leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``People don't even really know where he stands, because he  
hasn't said where he stands on these national issues, he hasn't 
even campaigned yet,'' Quayle said. ``He hasn't defined himself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush describes himself as a compassionate conservative. He has  
not been silent, answering questions, if cautiously. He has a 
record in five years as governor. Quayle discounted that, saying he 
wants to hear Bush on national issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what kind of a campaign he's going to run,''  
Quayle said. ``I'm not even sure he knows what kind of a campaign 
he's going to run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush is, indeed, untested as a national candidate. That changes  
next month. Early favorites have fallen before. For Quayle to gain 
headway, that would have to happen again, and there is no guarantee 
that if it did, he would climb past the field. He has competition 
on the GOP right, and his initial campaign finance report showed 
that he spent $1 million in raising $2.1 million, compared with 
Bush's $7.6 million. ``We'll be adequately financed to get our 
message out,'' Quayle said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can win,'' he told about 80 conservatives at the Washington  
headquarters of Americans for Tax Reform. ``If you're going to let 
the establishment take over, it might get you through the next 
poll, but it's not going to win. 
</P>
<P>
	``And I'm tired of losing.''  
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and special  
correspondent for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington 
and national politics for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 12:21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Leader Urges Fight Vs. Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan urged  
the world's major powers today to fulfill years of promises to 
reduce global poverty and boost economic growth so the world's 3 
billion poor people can have the chance of a better life. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the fears of a global recession recede, there is a danger  
that the continuing economic crisis afflicting many countries may 
be overlooked,'' Annan said in a letter to German Chancellor 
Gerhard Schroeder, host of a June 18-20 summit of Russia and the 
seven leading industrialized nations in Cologne. 
</P>
<P>
	The secretary-general made clear that he wants the so-called  
Group of Eight to take concrete action to ensure that the bulk of 
the world's population is not left ``on the margin of today's 
liberalized global economy, living in abject poverty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He called for more balanced and higher economic growth to open  
export markets that developing countries need for their economic 
recovery. He urged governments to reverse a nearly 40-year decline 
in development assistance, and also called on the G-8 to take 
further measures to strengthen the international financial system 
to prevent another global financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Marta Mauras, director of the secretary-general's office, said  
Annan is concerned that the economic crisis is ``deeper and more 
pervasive in its magnitude than we had anticipated'' -- with growing 
inequalities between rich and poor and a slowdown in global 
economic growth from 3.6 percent in 1996 to 1.9 percent projected 
in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the international community's repeated commitments to  
reduce global poverty, Annan noted in the letter that 3 billion 
people still live on the margins of subsistence with little hope of 
a better life for their children. 
</P>
<P>
	The financial crisis which swept Asia, Russia and Brazil caused  
a recession in Latin America, left some Asian countries with 
dramatically lower living standards and Africa barely able to 
sustain its already low income level, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The present ``sluggish'' economic growth rate is not only making  
it impossible to eradicate poverty but ``is also aggravating the 
imbalance in trade among the leading industrial powers, and thereby 
threatening the stability of the international financial system'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	To help spur economic recovery, Annan urged the major powers to  
boost output and open markets, to continue the momentum to reform 
the global financial system, to reduce instability in capital 
markets, and to include representatives of developing nations in 
deliberations on a new global financial architecture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
