<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House GOP Try To Protect Surpluses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans, trying to protect their  
party's flanks on a volatile social issue, were poised Wednesday to 
push through legislation to put new obstacles in the way of 
spending government surpluses that come from Social Security taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Workers should have the confidence that the money they pay  
into Social Security and Medicare is used only for Social Security 
and Medicare, not bigger government or new spending,'' said House 
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Most House Democrats planned to vote for the GOP proposal,  
saying they believe it won't do much to help the nation's 
retirement system, but also couldn't hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although this bill will probably not make things any worse, it  
won't make them any better,'' said Rep. Joseph Moakley, D-Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	A stricter version of the legislation has been stalled in the  
Senate by Democrats' objections and faces a veto threat from the 
Clinton administration, however. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's budget surplus, expected to be $80 billion to $110  
billion, will come entirely from Social Security taxes. Under 
current projections, income tax surpluses aren't anticipated until 
after 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The House GOP legislation would forbid Congress or the president  
from including Social Security surpluses in their budgeting for 
other programs of for tax cuts. Instead, it would have to be used 
to pay down the government's debt to private bondholders -- 
something economists say could help promote economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Separate votes on the House floor would be required for most  
exceptions. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers could tap the money to help prepare Social Security or  
Medicare, the health insurance program for the elderly, for a cash 
shortfall expected after baby boomers, now in middle age, retire. 
</P>
<P>
	Skepticism has been growing, however, that Congress can pass a  
full-scale overhaul of the retirement programs in the politically 
charged year and a half before the 2000 presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP drive to formally wall off Social Security surpluses is,  
in part, a fallback plan to counter Democrats' accusations that 
Republicans want to spend money that could help shore up the 
nation's retirement system on tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Public opinion polls, including polling by the Republican  
National Committee, indicate that Americans, by a double-digit 
margin, consider Democrats more likely than Republicans to make the 
right decisions about Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, RNC polling found that legislation to  
safeguard Social Security surplus dollars offered some cover, 
commanding strong support, with 87 percent of Americans in favor. 
</P>
<P>
	But it is unclear whether the GOP strategy can succeed.  
</P>
<P>
	A Senate version of the legislation is opposed by Democrats  
there and by the Clinton administration. It would lower the 
government's statutory debt limit, something administration 
officials say could hinder borrowing flexibility the Treasury 
Department needs in times of economic trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	And already, the conflict in Yugoslavia, with its $9  
billion-and-growing price tag, suggests that lawmakers are sure to 
face necessary -- or at least tempting -- exceptions to any new 
spending restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Democrats are challenging Republicans to set aside  
even more money, from expected income tax surpluses, for Medicare. 
The Clinton administration wants about $700 billion over 15 years 
for Medicare -- close to the same amount Republicans have budgeted 
for tax cuts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
