<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Goldman Investing in S. Korean Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Goldman Sachs and Co. signed an  
agreement Thursday to invest $500 million in South Korea's Kookmin 
Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. investment firm agreed to buy $200 million in  
convertible bonds and $300 million in newly issued shares of 
Kookmin in June. 
</P>
<P>
	That will make Goldman Sachs the largest shareholder of Kookmin  
with a 16.6 percent stake. The South Korean government will be the 
second largest shareholder with a 6.9 percent stake. The remaining 
shares are owned by individual investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldman Sachs said it will not take management control, but will  
appoint one board member and transfer advanced management know-how 
to Kookmin. 
</P>
<P>
	``We share the vision of Kookmin's management team. We are  
looking forward to working together with Kookmin in its drive to 
become a world-class bank,'' said Henry Cornell, a managing 
director of Goldman Sachs. 
</P>
<P>
	Specialized in retail banking, Kookmin is South Korea's second  
largest bank with 580 branch offices and 11,800 employees. It has 
assets of about $94 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	It marks the second major foreign investment in South Korean  
banks. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, British banking giant HSBC Holdings PLC signed a  
memorandum of understanding with the Korean government to acquire a 
70-percent stake in Seoulbank for $700 million. 
</P>
<P>
	A consortium led by U.S. investment fund Newbridge Capital Ltd.  
is holding talks with the Korean government to take over a 
51-percent stake in Korea First Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korea was forced to accept a $58 billion bailout from the  
International Monetary Fund in late 1997 to save its faltering 
economy. Bank and corporate reforms were a key condition of the 
loan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
