<HEADLINE> Two Cos. Sign To Sell Olympic Items </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Two more companies have signed on to sell  
2002 Winter Games merchandise, bringing to six the number of new 
licensees this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Concord Industries will market key tags, writing instruments,  
collectible ornaments and leather goods, and Bula Inc. will be the 
official licensee of head wear. 
</P>
<P>
	The Salt Lake Organizing Committee, trying to dig out of a $300  
million sponsorship hole lft by the Olympic bribery scandal, now 
has 20 companies as official licensees to sell merchandise ranging 
from clothing to refrigerator magnets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Definitely, it's a vote of confidence in us and the games that  
companies will make the financial commitments and devote the 
manufacturing resources to produce our products,'' said Mark Lewis, 
SLOC vice president of marketing and licensing. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that the new companies sell a broader range of  
products, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC gets a royalty ranging from 15 percent to 30 percent of the  
wholesale cost of the goods sold. The terms of the two deals were 
not released. 
</P>
