<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Palmer Group Wants Pebble Beach  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Pebble Beach golf course is close to being  
sold to a group that includes Arnold Palmer, Clint Eastwood and 
former baseball commissioner Peter Ueberroth, according to 
Golfweek.com web site. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer confirmed Wednesday that the group is ``in serious  
negotiations'' to buy the prized Pebble Beach, Calif., properties 
from Lone Cypress Co., a Japanese partnership. Sources told the 
magazine that the deal is close to completion for a price of about 
$1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a Golfweek source who requested anonymity, Palmer  
met with some of his partners Tuesday evening and Wednesday morning 
at Bay Hill Club. Palmer's group also includes Richard J. Ferris, 
former chief executive officer of United Airlines and chairman of 
the PGA Tour Policy Board. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked if his group is bidding on Pebble Beach, Palmer  
replied, ``Yes.'' He also confirmed Eastwood, Ueberroth and Ferris 
are part of the group. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Palmer said the sale hasn't been finalized.  
</P>
<P>
	Lone Cypress Co., a partnership between Taiheiyo Club Inc. and  
Sumitomo Credit Services Ltd., bought the Pebble Beach Co. for $500 
million in 1992 from Japanese tycoon Minoru Isutani. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese banks have reportedly been pressuring Taiheiyo and  
Sumitomo to liquidate their assets to pay off rising debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Leach, managing director of Lone Cypress Co., could not be  
reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pebble Beach Golf Links, the centerpiece of the Monterey  
Peninsula properties owned by Lone Cypress, will host the U.S. 
Amateur Championship this year and the 100th U.S. Open next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
