<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Entertainment highlights during the week of May 30-June 5:  
</P>
<P>
	60 years ago: Deanna Durbin signed a five-year contract with  
Universal at an annual salary of $195,000. 
</P>
<P>
	40 years ago: ``Juke Box Jury'' started its long run on BBC  
television. 
</P>
<P>
	35 years ago: The Rolling Stones made their U.S. television  
debut on ``The Les Crane Show.'' The show was followed by a 
nine-date tour that opened in San Bernadino, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	30 years ago: The Plastic Ono Band recorded ``Give Peace a  
Chance'' at a hotel in Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	25 years ago: Patti Smith recorded her version of ``Hey Joe,''  
her first recorded work. 
</P>
<P>
	15 years ago: Sergio Leone's film, ``Once Upon a Time in  
America,'' starred Robert DeNiro, James Woods, Elizabeth McGovern, 
Treat Williams and Tuesday Weld. 
</P>
<P>
	10 years ago: The first International Rock Awards paid tribute  
to Elvis Presley and honored Keith Richards of The Rolling Stones 
with a Living Legend Award. 
</P>
<P>
	And Robin Williams starred in ``Dead Poets Society.''  
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: TV Guide's annual ``best and worst'' issue cited  
LaToya Jackson for making ``her first smart career move'' by not 
attending ``The Jackson Family Honors'' in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	One year ago: Singer Geri Halliwell, better known as Ginger  
Spice, quit the Spice Girls. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken 10 years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``The legend bit's easy, the living's hard.'' -- Keith Richards  
of The Rolling Stones, who received a Living Legend Award at the 
first International Rock Awards. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken five years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``I dreamed about bread and cheese when I was fasting and had  
fantasies of pouring wine on my head while I rolled naked in the 
dirt.'' -- Keanu Reeves, on location in Nepal for the filming of 
``The Little Buddha.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
