<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL To Give Loans for New Stadiums </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Acting on a new policy aimed at keeping teams  
from moving, the NFL today committed more than $200 million as 
collateral for stadiums in Philadelphia, Denver and Foxboro, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision comes in response to the departure of two teams  
from Los Angeles and one each from Cleveland and Houston in 
1995-96. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a crucial policy for the league to have strong footing in  
the largest media markets,'' said Philadelphia owner Jeffery Lurie, 
one of the beneficiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The money is the first to be committed under a bylaw enacted in  
March. The policy allows backing of up to 50 percent of private 
financing used for stadiums in the top six markets and 34 percent 
in those below that level. 
</P>
<P>
	New England and Philadelphia are in the first group and Denver  
in the second. 
</P>
<P>
	Broncos owner Patrick Bowlen said he expects a commitment of $43  
million to $44 million, and the Eagles expect close to $50 million 
to $55 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots, recommitted to Massachusetts after a withdrawing a  
plan to move to Hartford, Conn., could get more than $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
	All three already have various commitments for public financing.  
</P>
<P>
	In other action on the final day of the league's spring meeting:  
</P>
<P>
	--The owners rejected a proposal to move kickoffs from the 30- to  
the 25-yard line to encourage returns. That first came up in March 
and was tabled but proponents were still unable to get a consensus. 
</P>
<P>
	--The owners awarded the 2003 Super Bowl to San Diego, replacing  
San Francisco, which will not have a new stadium ready. South 
Florida was the only other contender. 
</P>
<P>
	--The league unveiled the technology for its new replay system,  
to be reinstated this fall after seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	--The owners extended NFL Europe for at least another season.  
</P>
<P>
	But the biggest impact may be the commitments toward stadiums.  
</P>
<P>
	For while the money is more collateral than loan, it will allow  
the teams involved to get a commitment for funds to build stadiums 
and to get them at lower interest rates than they might have. 
</P>
<P>
	It's also not likely to cost the teams involved. Money will be  
paid back from the 40 percent of club seat revenues that go to 
visiting teams. 
</P>
<P>
	In part, it's a continuation of a league policy. But never  
before has the NFL backed as much as half the building cost. 
Thirty-four percent was the most committed in the past, and most of 
that was for renovations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an evolutionary thing not a new thing,'' commissioner  
Paul Tagliabue said. 
</P>
<P>
	That didn't sit well with everyone.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tax on all the teams that won't benefit,'' Al Davis of  
the Raiders said. ``Never before in the history of the league have 
the poor given to the rich.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Patriots owner Robert Kraft, who recently withdrew from a  
$380 million stadium deal in Connecticut, suggested it was simply a 
case of partners helping each other. Massachusetts Gov. Paul 
Cellucci signed legislation Monday that will provide $70 million to 
help the Patriots build a new stadium in Foxboro. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole stadium issue is an area that's highly complex,''  
Kraft said. ``Helping each other is one way to get things done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On replay, the owners were shown the technology in which coaches  
will get two challenges a game, plus an unlimited number in the 
last two minutes of each half. The calls will be made by a replay 
official from a stadium booth. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a system designed to correct a mistake that the whole  
world knows is a mistake,'' said Dennis Lewin, the league's top 
television official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 20:44:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Investigation Bangkok Bank Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Police have completed their  
investigations into the looting of Bangkok Bank of Commerce and 
have forwarded evidence to support prosecuting 40 former 
executives, the Bangkok Post reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The attorney general will decide which cases to take to court,  
but with reports on the cases averaging 10,000 pages each, there is 
no telling when a decision will be made, the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-six of the cases were described by police at the Economic  
Crimes Division as major. 
</P>
<P>
	The scandal at the Bangkok Bank of Commerce emerged in 1996. In  
what police have described as collusion, bank executives allegedly 
lent vast sums of money to a clique of politicians who put up 
collateral described as worthless and used the money for attempted 
hostile takeovers of companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly $3 billion was borrowed and never repaid to the bank,  
which plunged into insolvency. It was taken over the by the 
government and eventually shut down. 
</P>
<P>
	Reports did not detail if any politicians would be prosecuted  
along with the former bank executives. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the executives have fled the country, including Rakesh  
Saxena, an ethnic Indian former BBC official who was described as 
Thailand's takeover king. Saxena is in Canada fighting extradition 
to Thailand. He has said he believes he will be made the scapegoat 
for the scandal because of his Indian origins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
