<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Launches Extensive Airstrikes  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO officials say warplanes were  
involved today in the fiercest attacks yet in the three-month 
conflict against Yugoslavia. Serbia's state-run news agency said 
two children were killed and another seriously hurt when a NATO 
missile hit a village outside the Kosovo capital of Pristina. The 
Serbs say two other people were also wounded when missiles hit a 
family home in another Kosovo village. NATO said its jets 
participated in a record number of attack flights, bombarding 
artillery, tanks and mortar targets in Kosovo. A wide range of army 
barracks, ammunition storage sites, command posts and petroleum 
storage sites also were hit. 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan Charges India With Bombing  
</P>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- Military leaders from India and Pakistan are  
planning to meet later today to try to defuse tensions after 
Pakistan accused India of dropping bombs on its territory in the 
disputed Kashmir region. India said there was ``no truth'' to the 
Pakistani claims and that the attacks occurred solely on its own 
territory and were aimed at what it called Afghan mercenaries 
supported by Pakistani forces. A Pakistani spokesman said the 
alleged attacks were ``very grave escalation'' of tensions between 
the wary neighbors, and that Pakistan would possibly retaliate. 

</P>
<P>
	Wounded Ga. Student Leaves Hospital  
</P>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- The most seriously injured victim of last  
week's shootings at Heritage High School was released from the 
hospital today and said she bears no ill will toward the boy who 
shot six of his schoolmates. ``I forgive him,'' Stephanie Laster 
said. T.J. Solomon, 15, was charged in Thursday's shooting. 
Stephanie was shot in the abdomen. 

</P>
<P>
	End to Gun Hunting Lessons Sought  
</P>
<P>
	WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) -- Educators are questioning the wisdom of  
allowing children to bring guns to school, even for a hunting 
class. Officials in Wisconsin, citing reaction to the recent school 
shootings in Colorado and Georgia, decided to cancel the daytime 
hunter's education classes in Beaver Dam. They also want the 
nighttime courses canceled -- classes that have been offered for 40 
years -- and the school board is reviewing the request. Of the more 
than 800 such classes offered in Wisconsin last year, about a third 
were taught in schools for kids ages 12 to 16. But gun enthusiasts 
say better to teach gun safety, especially in a setting congenial 
to learning. 

</P>
<P>
	Commander: Pol Pot Was Executed  
</P>
<P>
	PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- The former military commander of the  
Khmer Rouge claims that Pol Pot was executed, contradicting earlier 
reports that the former guerrilla leader died of natural causes or 
killed himself. A lawyer for Ta Mok said his client claims Pol Pot 
was ordered killed, and that Ta Mok knows who ordered the killing. 
Ta Mok took power from Pol Pot in bloody struggle in 1997. He was 
arrested earlier this year. An estimated 1.7 million people died 
during Pol Pot's bloody reign. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 53  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 1 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 53.39 to 10,584.48. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,594-1,158. The Nasdaq was up 7.93 to 
2,388.83. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 1 Kafelnikov Out at French Open  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Top-seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov, struggling since  
winning the Australian Open, was eliminated today from the French 
Open tennis tournament in a straight-sets, second-round defeat to 
unranked Dominik Hrbaty of Slovakia. Kafelninkov won in Australia 
in January, then lost six straight matches. He gained the No. 1 
spot despite the defeats. Kafelnikov will lose his top ranking if 
either Pete Sampras or Patrick Rafter reach the quarterfinals here. 
Fifth-seeded Richard Krajicek was routed 6-1, 6-2, 6-2 by Vince 
Spadea. 

</P>
<P>
	San Diego Gets Super Bowl in 2003  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- San Diego, which played host to Super Bowls in  
1988 and 1998, was voted the 2003 Super Bowl today by NFL owners. 
The only other contender was South Florida, where this year's Super 
Bowl was held. San Diego replaces San Francisco, which was awarded 
the game but will not have a new stadium ready for the game. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
