<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Opel Car Plant To Cut 4,000 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RUESSELSHEIM, Germany (AP) -- The German unit of General Motors  
Corp., Adam Opel AG, plans to cut 4,000 of some 10,000 jobs at its 
main plant here as part of a four-year modernization plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The personnel cuts will include early retirement of older  
workers, with reduced working hours for some, but no outright 
layoffs, the company said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	According to board chairman Robert Hendry, Opel plans to replace  
its old facilities on the site with new buildings at a cost of 
$445.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will build one of the most modern automobile plants in the  
world,'' Hendry said. The new plant is to start production in 2002 
with an annual output of 270,000 vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Opel works council chief Rudi Mueller said a  
step-by-step reduction of personnel would take place, cutting the 
number of employees to 6,000 from a current 10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is the bitter side of the development,'' Mueller said.  
But he added that revamping Opel's facilities southwest of 
Frankfurt was necessary to remain competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the costs of construction, costs for razing old  
facilities and the possibility of adding a new model to its 
production line would push the outlay for the overall project to 
some $540 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Opel currently produces its Omega and Vectra model at the  
Ruesselsheim plant, which will continue during the interim phase. 
The new plant will be 40 percent smaller after the modernization is 
completed, with emphasis on productivity, quality and safety, said 
production manager Michael Wolf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
