<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Jews Adopt Traditional Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The spiritual leaders of the largest group of  
American Jews today approved a return to traditional values such as 
the wearing of yarmulkes, keeping kosher and praying in Hebrew. 
</P>
<P>
	The Central Conference of American Rabbis, the governing body of  
Reform Judaism, voted 324-68 in favor of the new platform after 
heated debate Tuesday and this morning. Nine rabbis did not vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm overjoyed. The overwhelming majority of my colleagues feel  
the same, and although this is not perfect, it is a framework for 
the future,'' said Rabbi Lawrence Goldmark, president of the Board 
of Rabbis of Southern California. ``This puts Reform Judaism in a 
positive light. This is what we stand for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The group had worked until late Tuesday on the new set of  
principles, then postponed their vote to allow for more debate 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have an organization where there are no smoky back rooms,''  
Rabbi Paul J. Menitoff, executive vice president of the 
1,700-member rabbis' group, said in explanation of the delay 
Tuesday. ``We respect our members. ... We never expected it to go 
smoothly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rabbi Eric Wisnia of New York City argued this morning that the  
group should not feel an obligation to pass the principles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't broken. Why are we fixing it?'' Wisnia said as  
debate resumed. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the document was so flawed that if passed, the rabbis  
would eventually have to repeat the same tortuous process of 
rewriting it. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a perfect document, but it is an important one,''  
countered Rabbi Laura Geller of Beverly Hills, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Prompting much of the debate was a section on intermarriage.  
Some participants were concerned that the section could be 
interpreted as condoning intermarriage, when their intent was 
instead to welcome non-Jews who were willing to convert. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new platform, ancient rituals sometimes scoffed at or  
ignored in Reform communities and usually associated with 
Conservative or Orthodox Jewry will again be embraced, such as the 
wearing of yarmulkes and prayer shawls, the observance of Jewish 
dietary laws and the use of Hebrew during prayer services. 
</P>
<P>
	Reform leaders said many of the 1.5 million Reform Jews in the  
United States already have been returning to traditional practices, 
and the new principles would only reinforce that. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting Tuesday and today was only the fourth time since  
Reform Judaism was established in North America in the mid-19th 
century that the rabbis' group met to issue comprehensive 
principles. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1885, 15 Reform rabbis issued the Pittsburgh Platform, which  
rejected traditional Jewish practices as ``entirely foreign'' for 
modern American times. 
</P>
<P>
	A platform adopted in 1937 encouraged rabbis to incorporate  
science into their views of sacred literature. And a conference in 
1976 produced a call for diversity, individuality and change. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest platform was not reached without controversy and  
several rewordings. 
</P>
<P>
	An earlier draft was dubbed ``Conservative lite'' by Rabbi  
Robert M. Seltzer, professor of Jewish history at the City 
University of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Reform leaders said the final draft maintains the traditional  
Reform ethos that sets their branch apart from Conservative Judaism 
-- the idea that Jews should choose traditions that help them and 
bypass those that do not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 13:52:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRL and CART Hold Unification talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The big names may be coming back to the  
Indianapolis 500. 
</P>
<P>
	After four years of bitter rivalry that threatened the future of  
open-wheel racing in the United States, CART and the IRL have begun 
face-to-face talks about bringing the two racing circuits together. 
</P>
<P>
	Word of the negotiations came as teams prepared for this  
weekend's race at the Indy 500, which has lost its luster during 
the feud as the best-known drivers stayed away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can confirm that there have been some very informal talks  
with Tony George,'' said Andrew Craig, president and CEO of 
Championship Auto Racing Teams. ``However, I am not prepared to 
comment on any of the details.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is no comment -- but also no denial of the talks -- from  
George, the Indianapolis Motor Speedway president who started the 
war when he formed the Indy Racing League late in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The answering salvo from CART was to quit the Indianapolis 500,  
leaving George to stage the world's most famous auto race with 
virtually no stars. 
</P>
<P>
	The differences between the two circuits once seemed  
insurmountable, with totally different chassis and engine rules in 
place. But the last few weeks have brought hope that a settlement 
could be achieved as early as 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his differences with George, who started the IRL as a  
low-cost, ovals-only alternative to CART, Craig says a merger would 
be in the best interests of both sides. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's CART's position that open-wheel racing would benefit  
greatly from having one series instead of two,'' Craig said. ``I 
think everyone in the industry would like to see it happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sources close to the two circuits who spoke on condition of  
anonymity say NASCAR president Bill France Jr., the most powerful 
man in American racing, is brokering the peace. 
</P>
<P>
	France did not return phone calls, but his interest is not  
surprising. International Speedway Corp., which owns and operates 
NASCAR, recently bought Penske Motorsports, giving ISC 10 
racetracks, with at least three more planned in the near future. 
</P>
<P>
	ISC will need more than just its stock car and truck divisions  
to keep those tracks busy and prosperous. 
</P>
<P>
	The war between CART and the IRL was destructive, and the timing  
couldn't have been worse, with NASCAR's emergence as the hottest 
American sport of the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	CART has been solid almost since its debut in 1979, but it  
attracts far fewer fans at tracks where NASCAR also races. Although 
the Indy 500 will race Sunday before another sellout crowd 
approaching 400,000, for the most part the IRL has not drawn well 
elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	When CART was the one major open-wheel entity in America, its TV  
ratings were adequate and building slowly. Since the split, neither 
side has drawn more than a bare audience, except for Indy. 
</P>
<P>
	And even the once mighty Memorial Day weekend classic has  
slipped from a high rating of 8.4 in 1995 to 5.5 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	But -- perhaps in hopes of a peace treaty -- ABC and ESPN haven't  
given up on either series. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN already had a deal with CART through 2001 before ABC  
re-upped for Indy last week, extending its contract through 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement also means ABC and ESPN will show the rest of the  
IRL schedule each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard Katz, the new president of ABC Sports and the catalyst in  
extending the current contract with George, says the biggest 
problem facing the open-wheel folks is building stars. 
</P>
<P>
	CART is perceived to have the big names, with Michael Andretti  
and Al Unser Jr. still its marquee drivers. But neither has won a 
championship in five years, and former Indy winners Mario Andretti, 
Bobby Rahal, Emerson Fittipaldi, Rick Mears, Al Unser Sr. and Danny 
Sullivan -- have retired in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the biggest stars stayed with CART, the IRL had a shaky  
foundation. Its one big-name driver, two-time Indy 500 winner Arie 
Luyendyk, will race Sunday for the final time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you've got to build stars,'' Katz said. ``You've got  
to have a reason to root for or even against people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sponsorships, which supply most of the money for race teams,  
also are a problem for open-wheel racing. 
</P>
<P>
	CART still has more than $400 million in sponsorship backing,  
but many of the long-term contracts will end in either 2000 or 
2001, with no guarantees they will be renewed. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL, which started from nothing in 1995, has built perhaps  
$50 million in sponsorship, but with minuscule TV ratings and 
little identity it continues to be a hard sell to corporate 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR, massively promoted and armed with high TV ratings,  
already has about $500 million annually in sponsorship money and 
continues to grow at a fast rate, drawing sponsors away from the 
open-wheel divisions. 
</P>
<P>
	PPG Industries, the longtime series sponsor for CART, is one of  
the few backers involved in both open-wheel series. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've managed to keep a foot in both camps, feeling that there  
was value on each side of the fence,'' said Mike Sack, PPG's 
director of motorsports. ``That's a difficult position to be in, 
not only from the standpoint of money, but also politically 
speaking. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know one sponsor that doesn't think peace between the  
series is a good idea.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 07:21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Truck Safety Measures Unveiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Critics say the Clinton administration's plan  
to cut the number of truck-related deaths in half over the next 
decade is well-intentioned but unlikely to produce quick results. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the things the secretary talked about are long-term,''  
said Jacqueline Gillan, vice president of Advocates for Highway and 
Auto Safety, a group with insurance industry support. ``The safety 
community wants action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater announced the  
goal and unveiled a series of steps to achieve it. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his department would ask for $56 million more from  
Congress this year to increase the number of inspectors for 
commercial vehicles, which includes trucks and motor coaches, and 
to boost state and federal safety programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Slater also said the federal Office of Motor Carriers, which  
regulates commercial vehicles, would increase the fines for 
violations, move more swiftly to shut down unfit motor carriers, 
limit negotiated settlements in enforcement cases and aggressively 
pursue criminal or civil penalties when someone is killed in a 
commercial vehicle crash. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the secretary said he would push to reduce driving  
time for operators and seek to monitor compliance with rules 
through the expanded use of technology similar to airline 
flight-data recorders. 
</P>
<P>
	All told, Slater said he hoped to reduce the number of  
truck-related deaths from about 5,000 annually to about 2,500 
annually. In 1997, 5,355 people were killed; preliminary figures 
show the number fell to about 5,200 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	On average, six people are killed each year in bus accidents,  
although the figure has spiked in the past six months after a 
Christmas Eve crash that killed eight in New Jersey and a charter 
bus accident earlier this month in New Orleans that killed 22. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today we face up to a time for action, and the plan that I  
have outlined deals with action,'' Slater declared at a news 
conference. He was accompanied by Federal Highway Administrator 
Kenneth Wykle, who oversees the Office of Motor Carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals triggered swift and critical reaction from safety  
advocates and truckers. 
</P>
<P>
	Joan Claybrook, president of the advocacy group Public Citizen,  
said: ``While we welcome DOT's statement on improved enforcement, 
they're still talking about useless safety education programs and 
'collaborative' government-industry research, for which they have 
been harshly criticized by the inspector general of the DOT.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, truckers said they wished Slater had already reformed  
hour-of-service rules, which regulate the amount of time truckers 
are on the road, and created a separate agency to oversee motor 
carrier safety, much like the Federal Aviation Administration does 
with airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Only in this format, with a Senate-confirmed presidential  
appointee reporting to the secretary of transportation, will truck 
safety get its proper respect,'' said Walter McCormick Jr., 
president of the American Trucking Associations. 
</P>
<P>
	In his announcement, Slater ducked one demand of safety  
advocates: moving the Office of Motor Carriers out of the Federal 
Highway Administration and into the National Highway Traffic Safety 
Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Both are parts of the Transportation Department, but the highway  
administration largely oversees the interstate system, while the 
safety administration deals with issues such as drunken driving, 
air bags and seat belt use. 
</P>
<P>
	Slater didn't rule out the change, but said he would prefer to  
be accountable for results and ``not just rearranging boxes on an 
organizational chart.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:52:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Power Deregulation Plan Under Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration's plan for  
generating competition among electric utilities was roundly 
criticized Wednesday by rural lawmakers who fear it could raise 
rates and hurt service in remote areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel very much like we're being offered a pig in a poke,''  
said Rep. Sanford Bishop, D-Ga. ``Nobody really know what this is 
going to do, if it happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A deregulation bill introduced by the administration last month  
would allow all consumers to choose their electric utility by 2003 
unless their states decided after public hearings that they do not 
want the competition. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a dozen states already have moved toward deregulating  
rates on their own. But administration officials told a House 
Agriculture subcommittee that federal legislation is needed to 
speed the process, overhaul tax laws and ensure that service 
remains dependable as competition increases. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department estimates consumers nationwide save $20  
billion a year by 2010, although rates could rise in some areas. 
The legislation provides for a tax that could be used to protect 
rural customers from rate increases and also guarantees that rural 
electric cooperatives would continue to buy federal hydropower at 
cost. 
</P>
<P>
	``No restructuring plan currently before the Congress is as  
complete or as sensitive to rural concerns as is the president's 
bill. ... One way or another, restructuring is coming,'' said Wally 
Beyer, administrator of the Agriculture Department's Rural 
Utilities Service. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said rural electric cooperatives could lose some of their  
biggest, most profitable customers to competing utilities. 
``There's going to be cherry-picking, no doubt about it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Thune, R-S.D., said it should be left to states decide  
to decide how or whether they deregulate electric rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. David Minge, D-Minn., expressed fears that rural electric  
co-ops could suffer the same fate as some rural telephone 
exchanges, which have been put up for sale or abandoned. 
</P>
<P>
	``The competitive forces do not favor the more remote parts of  
our country but would instead place them at risk,'' Minge said. 
</P>
<P>
	A USDA study that has not been released officially warned that  
deregulation could lead to rate increases in 19 states. USDA's 
chief economist, Keith Collins, told the House Agriculture 
subcommittee on general farm commodities, resource conservation and 
credit that the study was based on a worst-case scenario. 
</P>
<P>
	A more optimistic report by the Energy Department says that  
average rates would fall in 45 of the 48 contiguous states. Some 
consumers in Montana, Washington and Oregon would see increases, 
the study found. 
</P>
<P>
	``With appropriate strategies to implement competition, the  
administration believes that even these three states. ... can 
assure benefits from competition to all customer classes, said Mark 
Mazur, the Energy Department's acting policy director. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
