<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Hit by Train Faced Troubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- No one can say for certain why a mother  
and four of her sons would court a ghastly death by walking along 
railroad tracks in the middle of the night. 
</P>
<P>
	But the pressures on Julia Toledo were mounting every day: Her  
husband had returned to their native Ecuador. She had filed for 
divorce. Day care was hard to find. She quit her job to care for 
the children. She stopped taking English lessons. She moved out of 
an apartment and into a shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	And she had recently begun to worry that her kids would be taken  
away by the state, a friend said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, Toledo, 46, may have been running from the hard  
times when she and three of her boys were killed by an Amtrak train 
early Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials have ruled the deaths an accident; they do not believe  
it was a suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was obviously fleeing, but we don't know why. We wished we  
had known she was in trouble, because we could have helped her,'' 
said Sister Brenda Lynch of Caroline House, an educational center 
for immigrant women where Toledo took English lessons and other 
classes. 
</P>
<P>
	The dead boys were identified as Pedro Urgiles Toledo, 3; Angel  
Gabriel Urgiles Toledo, 6; and Carlos Urgiles Toledo, 12. The sole 
survivor was 10-year-old Jose Francisco Urgiles, who lay comatose 
Wedneday in critical condition. He lost most of his left leg and 
suffered a severe head injury and broken bones. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose was initially identified as Angel; he was so badly injured  
that even relatives were unable to identify him. 
</P>
<P>
	Toledo's friends have a number of theories to explain why the  
family was walking along the tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynch said following train tracks is a common practice in Latin  
America. Toledo may also have believed it was safer to follow the 
tracks than to walk through a poor neighborhood at night, Lynch 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a direct way, the tracks. What she did would make sense  
to her,'' Lynch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many people who knew Toledo said she usually seemed happy and  
stable. Milagros Vizcarrondo, principal of Luis Munoz Marin 
Elementary School, attended by three of the boys, said Toledo 
sometimes sought help to buy clothes or food. 
</P>
<P>
	Toledo had told school officials about her recent move to a  
shelter, worried that the children might have to switch schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was comfortable coming in here,'' Vizcarrondo said. ``She  
was comfortable asking for help. She had very happy children. She 
gave no indication that her situation had reached such heights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sister Brenda TeVogt said Toledo stopped attending English  
classes at Caroline House in early April, after being a steady 
student for nearly two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``She said, `Things are tough. I'm needing to get my life going,  
but I'll be back,''' TeVogt said. 
</P>
<P>
	TeVogt said Toledo had been having difficulty finding child care  
because of her unusual schedule. Until recently, she had worked 
nights cleaning offices at Fairfield University. 
</P>
<P>
	A neighbor, 69-year-old retired construction worker Gabriel  
Sanchez, said Toledo had quit her job and was worried about being 
able to support her family. 
</P>
<P>
	And in recent weeks, Toledo told TeVogt of another fear. She  
said a relative had scolded her for being ``a bad mother.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``My sense is she was afraid of losing her children,'' TeVogt  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	John Wiltse, a spokesman for the state Department of Children  
and Families, said the agency had no record of involvement with the 
family and had not investigated any reports of abuse or neglect. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency took temporary custody of the surviving child  
Wednesday in order to make legal and medical decisions about his 
care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
