<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:59:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grant: No Hard Feelings Toward Jazz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Brian Grant pondered the gash over his  
right eye -- opened up by one of Karl Malone's notorious elbows -- 
and decided he isn't angry about it. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the six-stitch cut represents what Grant wants to learn  
from Malone and the Utah Jazz: how to play with the intensity 
needed to win the biggest of games. 
</P>
<P>
	Grant and the rest of the Portland Trail Blazers face such a  
game tomorrow night in Game 6 of the Western Conference finals at 
the Rose Garden. The Jazz won Game 5 on Tuesday night, pulling 
within 3-2 and avoiding elimination for the third time in the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Malone cut Grant while going for a rebound in the first quarter.  
Grant lay on the floor in pain, and came back after being stitched 
up. He was ineffective, however, scoring eight points on 1-of-7 
shooting in the Blazers' 88-71 loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure he wasn't planning on elbowing me in the eye,'' Grant  
said before practice Wednesday. ``Even if it was intentional, 
that's part of the game. Those things are going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the fourth quarter, with the outcome decided, Grant was  
frustrated after Malone made a swipe at the ball Grant had 
rebounded. Grant faked a throw at the back of Malone's head, 
drawing a technical foul. That sent Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy 
into an uncharacteristic rage. 
</P>
<P>
	He stomped onto the court toward an official and, after being  
ejected, had to be restrained by assistant coaches and players. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Grant was in Malone's face, exchanging heated words  
with the future Hall of Famer. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're going to have to guess what I said to him, because it's  
between me and Karl,'' Grant said. ``This isn't about Brian Grant 
playing Karl Malone. It's about the Trail Blazers trying to win a 
championship this year. I know we're not going to be able to do it 
with me bickering with one player. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have any ill feelings toward any of the Jazz. If  
anything, I can take a page from their book someday as far as how 
to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Game 5, Blazers teammate Isaiah Rider hinted that the team  
might bring a role player off the bench to take out Malone, a 
suggestion quickly shot down by Dunleavy and Grant. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not my approach,'' Grant said. ``I'm a ballplayer, not  
a wrestler. I'm not a fighter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Malone was fined $10,000 by the NBA for elbowing Grant in the  
mouth in Game 1. As in Tuesday night's game, Malone was not 
whistled for a foul in that incident. 
</P>
<P>
	``He does have a problem with his elbows,'' Dunleavy said. ``I  
don't want to make excuses. But if a guy continually hits people 
with elbows and they get cut, what does that tell you?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rough play in Game 5 overshadowed an otherwise impressive  
performance by the Jazz, who say the pressure is now on the Blazers 
to win on their homecourt to avoid going back to Salt Lake City for 
Game 7. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they say they're not feeling a little pressure, I would say  
they're lying a little bit,'' Malone said. ``Because they're 
supposed to close us out because we're getting old, we can't do 
this, and we're predictable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jazz are trying to become the seventh team in NBA history to  
come back from a 3-1 deficit. The last to do it was the Miami Heat 
in 1997, against the New York Knicks in the Eastern Conference 
semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jazz have trailed 3-1 five times in the Malone-John Stockton  
era, and have yet to win the series. 
</P>
<P>
	But Utah is 6-1 the last two seasons when it had to win or go  
home. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to come again with a whole lot of energy, and  
we've just got to come out with the same energy that we had in 
Games 1 through 4,'' said Blazers guard Damon Stoudamire. ``Playing 
hard makes up for mistakes, and all the little things that were 
happening to us last night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Game 5, Utah showed intensity for the first time since Game  
2, when they came back from a 78-74 deficit to win 93-83. Utah also 
outrebounded the Blazers 45-31, and used their familiar screens to 
get open shots. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot easier now,'' said Utah guard Jeff Hornacek.  
``Sacramento proved it that when you're not playing under any 
pressure, it's a lot easier. The pressure is on them to try to 
finish us up.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
