<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 00:01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Said To OK Diabetes Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- SmithKline Beecham will make commercially  
available in the next few days a treatment for Type 2 diabetes that 
promises to have fewer risks than a current competing drug that has 
been linked to liver failure. 
</P>
<P>
	The pharmaceutical company said Tuesday it has received approval  
from the Food and Drug Administration to market Avandia to treat 
diabetes in the same manner as Rezulin. But, unlike Rezulin, in 
studies of more than 4,000 patients Avandia showed no sign of liver 
damage. 
</P>
<P>
	FDA spokesman Brad Stone said he could not confirm the agency  
action and another FDA official did not return calls seeking 
comment. The company said the approval came late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Advisers to the FDA last month recommended approval of the drug  
but warned that no one can say for certain that Avandia will never 
damage diabetics' livers. They said Avandia patients should have 
intensive liver testing similar to that now required for patients 
who take Rezulin. 
</P>
<P>
	In clinical trials, common side effects of using Avandia  
included upper respiratory tract infections and headaches. Some 
patients also reported weight gain. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue is Type 2, or adult-onset diabetes, which afflicts  
millions of Americans whose bodies lose the ability to properly use 
insulin, the hormone that processes blood sugar. 
</P>
<P>
	Rezulin, known chemically as troglitazone, was cheered widely  
when it hit the market in 1997 because it is the only drug sold 
that resensitizes the body to insulin. Many doctors contend it is 
invaluable for patients who have failed other diabetes therapies. 
Some 750,000 Americans now use the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after Rezulin hit the market, however, it began causing  
liver failure. FDA officials list 43 Rezulin patients who suffered 
acute liver failure. Of those, 28 died and seven needed liver 
transplants to survive. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA warned that those cases may represent only 10 percent of  
all Rezulin-related liver damage. Last month, the agency's advisers 
called for imposing new restrictions be put on Rezulin's sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA is also considering Takeda Pharmaceuticals' Actos,  
another drug that could offer Rezulin's benefit with fewer liver 
risks. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 08:12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dominik Hasek Might Skate Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- With Dominik Hasek out, the Toronto Maple Leafs  
are back in the Eastern Conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek, the star goalie for the Buffalo Sabres, sat out his  
second straight game Tuesday night with a sore groin. 
</P>
<P>
	Result: a 6-3 victory by the Maple Leafs that evened the  
best-of-7 series at a game apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's face it,'' said Leafs winger Steve Thomas, whose  
third-period goal gave Toronto a 5-3 cushion after the Sabres 
pulled within a goal, ``Dominik Hasek is the best goaltender in the 
world. When he's not in there, they're definitely aware of that. 
But we've been successful against them before, and some of the 
goals we scored would have gone in even if Hasek had been in 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe. Maybe not. Dwayne Roloson, who made 28 saves in Buffalo's  
5-4 win in Sunday's opener, his first-ever playoff start, played 
well again, but had less help from his teammates this time. It 
almost seemed as though they thought Hasek, the two-time league 
MVP, was back in there. 
</P>
<P>
	``Five goals, and three of them were within five feet,'' Sabres  
defenseman Jason Woolley said. ``I don't know how much more he can 
do. It's real tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fortunately for the Sabres, Hasek said his injury probably  
wouldn't keep him out the entire series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel much better than I did two days ago,'' Hasek said  
before Tuesday's game. ``I feel pretty optimistic. I feel much more 
strength in my leg and that's good. I hope I'll be back in the 
series. It's day-to-day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek has been taking anti-inflammatory drugs to ease the pain.  
Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff said the team was considering using 
cortisone injections. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to try anything,'' Ruff said. ``We'll explore  
every avenue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek first injured the groin in a 3-2 overtime loss to Toronto  
in Buffalo on Feb. 17. The Czech goalie, who led the NHL in save 
percentage (.937) for the sixth straight year, missed a dozen games 
and did not return until March 19. He flew to Germany on March 24 
for treatment after twisting his back in a game against the New 
Jersey Devils. 
</P>
<P>
	The groin injury flared up again in a Game 4 victory over Boston  
in the second round of the Stanley Cup playoffs and continued to 
hamper the acrobatic goalie in a 5-3 loss to the Bruins in Game 5. 
Hasek started and won Game 6 against Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has got to get to a level where he feels comfortable and  
can perform his acrobatics,'' Ruff said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek, whose butterfly style relies on mobility and quickness  
and a capacity to rebound from a prone position, said he didn't 
know when he would return. The teams play Thursday and Saturday in 
Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course I'm thinking about Thursday,'' said Hasek, who said  
he would try to skate today. ``Who knows? I cannot answer because I 
don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek said he would be cheating his teammates if he were to try  
to come back too soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I cannot go up and down, and if I cannot go up and down, I  
cannot do my job,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	An MRI in Buffalo on Monday confirmed that Hasek has a strained  
groin, but a bone scan revealed no other damage, the team said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruff said the Sabres were still a good team without Hasek.  
</P>
<P>
	``We can beat anybody, and we don't need every star player in  
the lineup,'' said Ruff, also missing leading scorer Miroslav Satan 
since the first round because of an ankle bruise. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres have recalled Martin Biron from Rochester, the team's  
AHL affiliate, to back up Roloson. Biron, named the AHL's 
outstanding goalie this season, made three starts and was 1-2-1 
with the Sabres. 
</P>
</TEXT>
