<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 4,000 Baby Bouncers Recalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- About 4,000 baby bouncers were recalled  
Tuesday after several reports of babies falling and bumping their 
heads. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bungee Baby Bouncer allows a baby to bounce while supported  
in a ``belly band,'' suspended from a doorway. Knots tied in the 
rope that supports the bouncer can unravel, causing the baby to 
fall, said the Consumer Product Safety Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission and the bouncer's manufacturer, E &AMP; I Inc. of  
Bancroft, Idaho, have received six reports of knots failing, with 
babies being injured in four of those cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers should immediately stop using the bouncers and return  
the bungee assembly to the manufacturer for repair. 
</P>
<P>
	Chelsea and Scott's One Step Ahead catalogs, and baby specialty  
retailers in Utah and Idaho sold the bouncers from September 1998 
through March 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:52:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Voting on Union Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WATSONVILLE, Calif. (AP) -- Berry pickers employed by the  
nation's biggest strawberry grower voted today on whether to 
unionize, a key test of the United Farm Workers' long-running 
effort to restore its once-formidable clout in agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
	The UFW committed itself to winning such a vote at Coastal Berry  
Co. five years ago, hoping a victory there would create momentum 
for similar successes throughout California's farm fields. 
Strawberry growers have historically been among the most truculent 
opponents to union organizing. 
</P>
<P>
	But despite unusual advantages at Coastal Berry, the foremost of  
which was a promise by its owners not to block unions, the campaign 
has been plagued by setbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The UFW organizers struggled to win the trust of workers and  
faced competition from a rival union backed by company supervisors 
who had ties to other anti-union growers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The strawberry industry wants to stop UFW progress at all  
costs, and Coastal Berry could be a crucial turning point for the 
workers statewide,'' UFW spokesman Marc Grossman said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Coastal's 1,500 employees in the farming communities of Oxnard,  
Watsonville and Salinas voted by secret ballot Tuesday and 
Wednesday. Their choices: representation by the UFW, its rival, the 
Coastal Berry of California Farm Worker Committee, or no union at 
all. Results were expected Wednesday evening. 
</P>
<P>
	In Watsonville, pickers briefly left oceanside fields laden with  
fat red strawberries to place their ballots under the close watch 
of state labor officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Coastal Berry Co. President Ernie Farley said Wednesday the  
company is neutral on whether its workers are represented by the 
UFW or the Farm Worker Committee. The UFW says its rival is a sham 
union that doesn't have the workers' interests at heart. 
</P>
<P>
	Coastal Berry's pickers are treated better than some in the  
berry fields. They earn an average wage of between $7.50 and $8.50 
an hour and have full medical and dental benefits for themselves 
and dependents. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're pretty much in the top of the industry. The dependents  
get health benefits even if they live in Mexico,'' Farley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the UFW wants better wages, benefits and job security,  
not only at Coastal Berry, but at other growers as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The results of the vote will be pivotal in the UFW's effort to  
overcome the doldrums it fell into even before the 1993 death of 
its legendary founder, Cesar Chavez, who inspired 80,000 
farmworkers to join up by 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	That activism later faded, and union membership declined to  
20,000 at the time of his death. 
</P>
<P>
	In the fields, migrant farmworkers and undocumented immigrants  
were unwilling to risk their livelihoods by alienating their 
bosses. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, the UFW's revived organizing effort was begun in the  
most difficult place -- strawberry fields, where picking the crops 
is entry-level farmwork, the most backbreaking, low-skilled labor 
available. 
</P>
<P>
	The state's $600 million strawberry industry employs about  
20,000 workers. Until this week, the only strawberry grower to sign 
a UFW contract is a small organic farm with 50 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the UFW has won 18 union elections and signed 22  
first-time contracts with growers of other crops, increasing 
overall union membership to 27,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coastal Berry campaign got a boost when the company's former  
parent Monsanto Corp., under pressure from Congress and Vice 
President Gore to resolve the berry company's labor problems, sold 
it to two liberal Washington, D.C., investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the company's efforts to achieve labor peace, some of  
its own supervisors actively opposed the UFW, and formed the Farm 
Worker Committee as an alternative union. 
</P>
<P>
	The Farm Worker Committee won a union election at Coastal Berry  
last July after the UFW refused to participate, claiming the 
workers had been intimidated by members of the committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Agricultural Labor Relations Board invalidated the  
election because some workers weren't given the opportunity to 
vote. The company later fired several of the Farm Worker 
Committee's leaders, who had been accused of threatening workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 14:11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Churchill Will Be Site of 2000 Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Churchill Downs will be the site of the  
2000 Breeders' Cup, marking a record fifth time the event is to be 
held at the same track. 
</P>
<P>
	In making the announcement Wednesday, Breeders' Cup Ltd.  
president D.G. Van Clief Jr. cited the success of last year's 
championship, which also was held at Churchill, for the quick 
return to the track, home of the Kentucky Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	A Breeders' Cup record crowd of 80,452 attended in 1998,  
breaking the previous record of 71,671 which was set when Churchill 
hosted the races in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The reception the championship got from the community was  
another factor, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Churchill's management and staff have done a first-rate job in  
presenting the Championship on four previous occasions,'' Van Clief 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The championship, on Nov. 4, 2000, is thoroughbred racing's  
richest day, featuring eight races with purses and awards totaling 
$13 million. A new race, the Filly and Mare Turf, will be added to 
the card this year. 
</P>
<P>
	No track has held the event more than three times.  
</P>
<P>
	Churchill Downs has recently enjoyed growing crowds. Attendance  
at the 1999 Kentucky Derby was the second largest in the track's 
history. Four of the top five crowds in Breeders' Cup history were 
when the races were held at the track. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Van Clief said it was unlikely the Breeders' Cup will  
be awarded exclusively to Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's healthy for the championship to be moved from city to  
city,'' he said. ``It gives it an aesthetic value it might not have 
if it was sedentary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the championship's revenue, Van Clief said, comes from  
the breeding industry in the form of nomination fees. Moving the 
championship to other states that are important to the breeding 
industry, such as Florida and California, is an acknowledgment of 
their contributions, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related development, Van Clief also announced Wednesday  
that the Breeders' Cup will seek an agreement with The New York 
Racing Association to conduct the 2001 Breeders' Cup at Belmont 
Park. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's Breeders Cup Championship will be held at Gulfstream  
Park in Hallandale, Fla., on Nov. 6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0241 </DOCNO>
