<DOCNO> APW19990526.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 14:52:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AMA Restores Journal Independence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The American Medical Association said Wednesday  
it will guarantee the editorial independence of its weekly journal 
by creating a board to serve as a buffer between the editor in 
chief and the organization's management. 
</P>
<P>
	The move follows criticism that erupted in January, when Dr.  
George Lundberg was fired as editor of The Journal of the American 
Medical Association for publishing a survey of college students' 
sexual attitudes that coincided with President Clinton's 
impeachment. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. E. Ratcliffe Anderson, the AMA executive vice president,  
said at the time that Lundberg had inappropriately interjected the 
organization into a political debate. 
</P>
<P>
	AMA officials did their best not to mention the episode  
Wednesday, dodging questions about Lundberg's firing by saying they 
preferred to look to the future than dwell on the past. 
</P>
<P>
	They instead announced new guidelines to assure JAMA's  
independence and praised the spirit of solidarity among board 
members, Anderson and the search committee that drew up the 
guidelines and is looking for a new editor. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Roger Rosenberg, chairman of the search committee, called  
the safeguards ``the issue we felt was most important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Editorial independence is essential,'' Rosenberg said.  
</P>
<P>
	Anderson will not have solo firing authority under the new  
guidelines. A firing would have to be approved by the newly created 
oversight board and two-thirds of the AMA's board of trustees. 
</P>
<P>
	The oversight board will be composed of six members from outside  
the AMA, and one member of the association's senior management. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Jerome Kassirer, editor of the New England Journal of  
Medicine, had criticized Lundberg's firing as irrational and inept. 
He said the oversight board is a good idea, if it truly serves as a 
buffer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The key question will be: Are they going to be advocates for  
the editor in chief or advocates for the AMA policies?'' Kassirer 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lundberg, who had been JAMA editor for 17 years, is now editor  
in chief for an online medical information site, medscape.com. He 
did not immediately return a phone call seeking comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 17:05:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Give $175B to Charity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Americans opened their pocketbooks wider in  
1998, donating nearly $17 billion more to charities than the 
previous year, according to a new report on charitable giving. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong economy, low inflation, a growth in personal wealth and  
more sophisticated fund raising helped fuel the 10.7 percent 
increase and raise overall charitable giving to $174.52 billion, 
said Ann E. Kaplan, research director for the American Association 
of Fund-Raising Counsel's Trust for Philanthropy. 
</P>
<P>
	When adjusted for inflation, the increase was 9 percent, she  
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Individuals donated the bulk of the money, giving $134.84  
billion in 1998, an increase of 9.7 percent. Foundations gave the 
next highest amount with $17.09 billion, up 22.9 percent; bequests 
accounted for $13.62 billion, a 7.8 percent increase, and 
corporations gave $8.97 billion, up 9.3 percent, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the third year in a row charitable giving increased  
dramatically -- it rose 11.8 percent in 1996 and 13.7 percent in 
1997 -- with religious organizations and denominations continuing to 
get the biggest piece of the pie. They took in $76.06 billion, a 
4.6 percent increase over 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the increase may seem small at a time when more people  
say they are attending religious services, Kaplan noted that those 
who give to religious charities are also giving more to other 
charities. ``They are not abandoning religious contributions,'' she 
said. ``If anything, they appear to be broadening their charitable 
horizons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Statistics for the ``Giving USA 1998'' report come from  
deductions listed on tax returns as well as reports submitted by 
more than 3,000 charities. Figures will be adjusted when late 
filing taxes are due later in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Contributions in four nonprofit areas rose more than 20 percent.  
Civil rights and public affairs groups had the biggest increase, 
jumping 29.5 percent to $10.86 billion. Wildlife and environmental 
organizations took in $5.25 billion, up 28.3 percent; human service 
organizations got $16.08 billion, up 27 percent; and health 
organizations, including hospitals and major disease-related 
organizations, received $16.89 billion, up 20.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Giving to education, mostly to university capital campaigns, was  
up 10.8 percent to $24.56 billion and contributions to 
international affairs rose 9.3 percent to $2.14 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Gifts to foundations rose from $14.56 billion in 1997 to $16.94  
billion in 1998 and Kaplan said they may rise even further when 
other tax data is analyzed. 
</P>
<P>
	The only decline was in the arts and cultures category, which  
dropped slightly by 0.8 percent. Kaplan said small, community-based 
arts programs and large institutions reported getting increases of 
6 percent from 1997 to 1998 but mid-sized organizations have had 
trouble fund raising. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of these groups have been around less than 10 years and  
don't have well organized fund-raising efforts,'' Kaplan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 23:51:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Manhunt Caps Weird Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Political professionals in Louisiana say the  
race to replace Bob Livingston in Congress is unlike anything 
they've ever seen. 
</P>
<P>
	Few campaigns, after all, start after an admission of adultery,  
move through a primary with a former Ku Klux Klan grand wizard and 
peak with a manhunt that takes one candidate to remote forests on 
the other side of the continent. 
</P>
<P>
	For former Gov. Dave Treen, finding his grandson in an Oregon  
wilderness on Wednesday eclipsed his runoff contest with state Rep. 
David Vitter. It was, he said, ``better than getting elected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	How this latest twist might affect the outcome in Saturday's  
special election is unknown, chiefly because there isn't much 
precedent for a candidate ditching his campaign just days before 
the final vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Livingston thing was weird, and the situation with Treen's  
grandson just stopped the campaign with five days to go. That 
doesn't happen too often,'' said Joe Walker, a New Orleans 
political consultant. 
</P>
<P>
	``It might make a few people feel that they should vote for  
Treen because the guy was willing to give up his campaign to save 
his grandson.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Treen and Vitter, both conservative white Republicans, were  
running neck-and-neck before Treen pitched in to help in the search 
for Jason Neville, who was found in good shape by a news helicopter 
that spotted him flashing metal camping pans as it passed over the 
rugged Columbia Gorge. 
</P>
<P>
	Neville had set out alone last Thursday to celebrate his 20th  
birthday and got lost in the steep ridges and cliffs along the 
Columbia River about 40 miles east of Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	Treen planned to return today to resume a campaign that never  
really shut down after he left on Tuesday. His telephone, mail and 
television appeals continued to run during a manhunt that was 
exhaustively covered by the local media. 
</P>
<P>
	Apart from a possible sympathy dividend for Treen, some voters  
said the unusual episode in Oregon may have little impact in a race 
where the divide between the issues is about as thick as a tissue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone has already made their decision,'' said Joel Hill, a  
voter who lives in the New Orleans suburb of Metairie. ``You're not 
looking at a major disparity in political philosophy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, about the only major distinction between the two  
conservatives is their age. Treen, at 70, boasts he can hit 
Congress running, having served seven years in the U.S. House in 
the 1970s -- seven years that Speaker Dennis Hastert has said would 
count in seniority ranking. 
</P>
<P>
	Vitter, at 38, argues he is young enough to build the kind of  
seniority that Livingston amassed to ensure the 1st Congressional 
District gets its full share of Congressional largesse. 
</P>
<P>
	``The traditional things you get fireworks over can't exist in a  
situation like this,'' said Ed Renwick, head of the Loyola 
University Institute of Politics. ``It's not like there's a liberal 
and a conservative, black and white, man or woman. You've got none 
of the differences that make a very lively campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The issues haven't been very lively, but the circumstances of  
the race in the suburban New Orleans district haven't been dull. 
</P>
<P>
	Livingston, a 21-year House veteran and protege of Treen, was  
poised to inherit the speakership from Newt Gingrich when he 
abruptly resigned and declared himself an adulterer to keep Larry 
Flynt from doing so in Hustler magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	In the primary election, white supremacist and former KKK leader  
David Duke placed third among nine candidates after bombarding 
voters with phone messages against the Kwanzaa holiday and the 
creation of a stamp honoring Malcolm X. He broadcast TV spots 
criticizing federal laws that ban segregation. 
</P>
<P>
	The special elections also were oddly scheduled, with the  
primary during the New Orleans Jazz and Heritage Festival and the 
runoff on the Saturday that opens the long Memorial Day weekend. 
Turnout is expected to be low. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill predicted the vote in this predominantly white,  
middle-class district will be split by age and money. 
</P>
<P>
	``The older, landed people are going to vote for Treen and the  
younger ones are going to vote for Vitter,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 01:21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Avs Look for Missing Sakic, Fleury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Where have you gone, Joe Sakic? And you, Theo  
Fleury? 
</P>
<P>
	While the Colorado Avalanche were forging a five-game playoff  
winning streak, no one seemed to notice the performanc of two of 
their most prolific scorers. 
</P>
<P>
	But when the Avalanche bowed to the Dallas Stars 4-2 Monday  
night to square the Western Conference final series at one game 
apiece, the finger-pointing began. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleury's assist Monday night was his first point in the last  
five playoff games, dating back to Game 3 of the Detroit series on 
May 11. Sakic has just one goal and one assist in the last eight 
playoff games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had some great chances as a line,'' Fleury said Tuesday.  
``The puck is just not going in, for some reason. We're too good of 
players not to get on the scoreboard. We're doing all the right 
things. It's just a matter of time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fleury said linemate Milan Hejduk, a rookie who scored his sixth  
goal of the playoffs Monday night, ``is playing great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the series shifts to Denver for Game 3 tonight, the Avalanche  
were eager for Sakic and Fleury to regain their scoring touch, as 
well as for the defense to cut down on the number of shots faced by 
their goalie, Patrick Roy. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas enjoyed a 45-19 advantage in shots on goal in Monday's  
game, including a 15-1 edge in the third period. 
</P>
<P>
	Playing with desperation and a street-fighter mentality, the  
Stars delivered a message: This will be a long, tough playoff 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were a desperate team and they had to be,'' Fleury said,  
referring to the Stars' situation after losing Game 1 at home. 
``They threw everything at us in the third period.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is, this is the semifinals,'' Dallas center  
Guy Carbonneau said. ``You play each shift as if it were your 
last.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Nieuwendyk and Mike Modano scored goals in the Stars'  
dominating third period. 
</P>
<P>
	``We finally found some seams and cracks through the defense to  
get to the net,'' Modano said. ``The second and third shots were 
finally there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said his team's more aggressive  
approach on Monday night was by design. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think for us to play well, we have to press the pace,'' he  
said. ``It doesn't matter who we're playing. We've played two 
pretty good hockey games. Unfortunately, we lost the first one. I 
thought the difference was we played with desperation, knowing our 
status. We took some chances and we didn't get hurt by it. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're playing a team as good and as skilled as Colorado,  
you can take one of two attitudes -- either stand back and wait and 
hope that's going to work out, or press the issue. Obviously, by 
the way we played, we've made the decision to press the issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of a suffocating defensive game, Modano felt as if he  
was turned loose on Monday night. That observation drew a chuckle 
from Hitchcock. 
</P>
<P>
	``He might think he's been turned loose, but he's not,'' the  
coach said. ``This is just a different series. There just is no 
play in the neutral zone. It's in one end or the other. The games 
are very similar to the way we play against Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the series against St. Louis, there was a tremendous amount  
of counter-attacking and neutral-zone play. In this series, there 
is none. So the feeling is that there's a lot of room because 
you're coming through that area between the two blue lines with a 
lot of speed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked to explain Colorado's somewhat lackluster play in Game 2,  
Hitchcock said, ``They got what they wanted. They got the split in 
our building. Now, we have to come in here and do that, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Avs forward Peter Forsberg said his team must play ``much  
smarter, much harder. We have to be the ones that play desperate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas lost forward Benoit Hogue for the remainder of the  
playoffs after he suffered torn knee ligaments in the first period. 
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche, meanwhile, were hopeful of getting back center  
Stephane Yelle, their best penalty-killer. Yelle has been sidelined 
since May 3 with a sprained left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's probably going to be a game-time decision,'' Colorado  
coach Bob Hartley said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
