<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Backs Center for Missing Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federally funded clearinghouse that helps  
locate missing or mistreated children would receive $10 million a 
year over the next four years under a bill the House passed 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The House voted 414-1 for the measure, and differences between  
that proposal and similar legislation the Senate passed last month 
must be worked out before Congress sends a bill to the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	The bills would free the National Center for Missing and  
Exploited Children, created by Congress in 1984, from having to 
apply yearly for federal grants it relies on to help run a national 
resource center and a 24-hour telephone hot line from its 
headquarters in nearby Arlington, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	The organization received $8.1 million in federal aid this year.  
</P>
<P>
	Since its creation, the center has worked with the FBI, the  
Justice Department and other law enforcement agencies to help find 
more than 40,100 missing children, according to the proposed 
legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Michael Castle, R-Del., the House sponsor, said guaranteed  
annual appropriations for fiscal year 2000, which starts Oct. 1, 
through fiscal 2004 will ensure the center can focus on helping 
families of missing children without interruption. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas, voted against the bill.  
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., recognized Missing  
Children's Day by asking his House colleagues and other computer 
users to create links from their World Wide Web pages to the 
``CyberTipline.'' The site, run by the missing children's center, 
accepts reports about the sexual exploitation of children. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress needs to do its part to find missing children and  
protect America's kids from exploitation,'' Watts said. ``It's 
critical that we recognize and promote the positive uses of 
America's fastest-growing medium.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Watts said the site received ``thousands of tips that have led  
to numerous arrests and reunited hundreds of missing children with 
their families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bills are H.R. 905 and S. 249. CyberTipline can be found at  
http://www.missingkids.org/cybertip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
