<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Museum Guns Didn't Belong to James </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KEARNEY, Mo. (AP) -- Jesse James aficionados never give up.  
</P>
<P>
	Four years ago, a team of scientists exhumed remains from James'  
grave in Kearney and used DNA testing to conclude that the outlaw 
was indeed the man buried there. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, extensive research by the director of the Jesse James Farm  
and Museum has shown that two guns James supposedly used in a train 
robbery actually were made after he died. 
</P>
<P>
	The error was discovered after a tourist asked an innocuous  
question about one of the guns, a Winchester rifle, prompting 
museum director Elizabeth Gilliam Beckett to review records. It 
turned out that the rifle and a Colt .45 revolver didn't have 
authenticity documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Using serial numbers, Ms. Beckett discovered the revolver was  
made in 1883 and the rifle was made in 1890. James was shot to 
death in 1882. 
</P>
<P>
	``The public needed to know these weren't Jesse's guns,'' she  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
