<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Celtics GM Testifies in Lewis Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A former Boston Celtics general manager testified  
today that Dr. Gilbert Mudge assured him Reggie Lewis would be able 
to return to basketball after fainting in April 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he said was that Reggie did not have ... an abnormal  
heart. He did not have a cardiac problem,'' Jan Volk said during a 
malpractice trial stemming from Lewis' subsequent death of a 
cardiac arrhythmia. 
</P>
<P>
	``He stated that he was very confident that Reggie would be able  
to return to competitive NBA play without limitation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Volk, called as a witness by attorneys for Lewis' widow in the  
fourth week of testimony, said Mudge told him tests had shown 
Lewis' problems were neurological and could have been caused by 
dehydration. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked his reaction to the news, Volk replied, ``I hoped he  
was right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis died months later, on July 27, 1993, in the Celtics  
practice gym at Brandeis University. He was 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Donna Harris-Lewis sued Mudge and two consultants, Drs. Mark  
Creager and Peter Friedman, claiming they misdiagnosed and 
mistreated her husband. A third consultant settled the case for an 
undisclosed amount. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge announced the same optimistic prognosis at a news  
conference when Lewis was released from the hospital. But Volk's 
testimony called into question Mudge's assertions that in private 
he never had ruled out the possibility that Lewis had a heart 
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	After Lewis' collapse during a playoff game in April 1993, a  
team of doctors from New England Baptist Hospital assembled by the 
Celtics diagnosed him with a potentially life-threatening, 
career-ending arrhythmia, or irregular heartbeat. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge, a doctor at Brigham and Women's Hospital, initially  
agreed with the group, but after further tests he told the All-Star 
he had a less-serious neurological condition that causes fainting 
spells. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Volk said Mudge had suggested the doctors from New  
England Baptist incorrectly diagnosed Lewis because their tests 
were faulty. 
</P>
<P>
	Volk testified that Mudge told the Lewises the earlier tests  
``had been calibrated for somebody much shorter, and that when it 
was recalibrated for somebody Reggie's height, the abnormality was 
not shown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under cross-examination by Mudge's lawyer, William Dailey Jr.,  
Volk acknowledged that Mudge told him when Lewis was discharged 
from the hospital that the Celtics would have to continue 
monitoring Lewis' health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
