<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Space Station Program for Museums </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- When Al Richmond began crossing the country to  
promote the planned international space station, his audiences' 
reaction was often a puzzled ``huh?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There are just so many other things in the news that have  
taken precedence, they don't realize the wonderful things that are 
happening around them,'' says Richmond, a former NASA employee who 
marketed the space station for Boeing, the project's prime 
contractor. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, the United States and 15 other countries are  
contributing resources and hardware to the multi-billion-dollar 
project that Richmond calls ``a bridge to the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When completed in 2004, the orbiting research facility will be  
larger than a football field and will be visible to the unaided eye 
in the heavens. 
</P>
<P>
	But back on Earth, few were getting excited.  
</P>
<P>
	While Richmond pondered the problem, officials at the Bishop  
Museum in Honolulu approached Boeing about designing a program to 
educate museum visitors about the space station. 
</P>
<P>
	The result is Star Station One, a series of discussions and  
multimedia presentations that grew to encompass more than 60 
museums, science centers and planetariums in all 50 states. 
</P>
<P>
	The program uses educational materials, exhibits and hands-on  
demonstrations to track the station's progress as astronauts 
assemble it in orbit -- piece by painstaking piece -- during a series 
of 45 space launches. 
</P>
<P>
	Materials are distributed to participating museums to coincide  
with each station mission. The next begins Thursday when space 
shuttle Discovery and its crew of seven are scheduled to blast off 
to deliver 1 1/2 tons of gear to the station. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important for people to know about the station not only  
from an educational standpoint but from an advocacy standpoint,'' 
says Mike Levad, aerospace educator at the Bishop Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	Star Station One debuted in November, prior to the launch of the  
first segment of the space station, the Russian-built Zarya module. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing paid $2.2 million to fund the program the first three  
years. In January, Richmond left the company to head up the Star 
Station One Institute, a nonprofit organization dedicated to 
expanding the project. 
</P>
<P>
	The only stipulation for participating museums is they are  
required to hold at least one workshop annually to instruct 
teachers about how to incorporate information about the space 
station into their lesson plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the future for all of the kids in school right now.  
They're the next designers of the next space station,'' says Susan 
Tortorici, the Star Station One project manager at Space Center 
Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Levad estimates the program already has reached about 180,000  
people nationwide, and several other countries have expressed 
interest in participating. 
</P>
<P>
	But for Richmond, the true test of the program's success will  
come the next time he addresses a group. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before they know it they'll be able to look up and see this  
thing streaking across the horizon,'' he says. ``We'd prefer they 
know about it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
