<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 21:11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High-Tech Braces China Backlash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Tighter export controls on the sale of  
computers and other high-tech products to China could cripple U.S. 
companies seeking to tap markets in the world's most populous 
country without improving national security, industry officials 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturers and free-trade advocates fear that the House  
report detailing 20 years of Chinese espionage against the United 
States could create a backlash that would limit their ability to 
compete with foreign companies already selling computers, chips and 
machine tools in China. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're certainly committed to protecting U.S. national security  
interests and we're investing millions of dollars to comply with 
U.S. export laws, but the fact is denying sales of computers that 
are widely available from other sources does little to protect 
national security,'' Bill Calder, a spokesman for Intel Corp., said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue for manufacturers is access to one of the world's  
fastest growing markets for high-tech products such as computers, 
cellular telephones and advanced manufacturing equipment. China is 
expected to spend $5.9 billion on personal computers during 1999 
and $15.2 billion in 2002, according to the research firm Dataquest 
Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The report released Tuesday recommends continued sale to China  
of technology for peaceful purposes and U.S. Rep. Christopher Cox, 
who chaired the investigation panel, said he doesn't want to hinder 
American companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also urges the Clinton administration to negotiate  
agreements with other countries to impose the same level of 
restrictions on China trade as the United States and to create a 
system to verify that technology isn't used for military purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	Calder and others worry that an anxious Congress might decide  
the United States can act alone and impose restrictions 
unilaterally. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington's ability to negotiate multilateral export pacts,  
even with close allies, has diminished since 1994, when Cold 
War-era agreements designed to block technology transfers to the 
Soviet Union were abandoned, said Ivan Eland, a defense analyst 
with the Cato Institute in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``We always tighten up our export controls in general and try to  
lead. Well, nobody ever follows us. Unilateral controls do 
absolutely nothing,'' said Eland. 
</P>
<P>
	Verification programs outlined in the report rarely work, he  
said. During the 1980s, the United States sold mainframe computers 
to South Africa with the understanding they would be for civilian 
use. South Africa foiled inspectors by allowing military users to 
log on by modem and use the mainframes even though they were 
installed at civilian institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales to China of computers commonly used in the United States  
and exported freely to most countries have been under tight 
restriction for several years. 
</P>
<P>
	Exporters already need a special permit to sell China computers  
equipped with Intel's newest 550 megahertz Pentium III chip. The 
Merced chip, due out in 2000, will push consumer-level technology 
even further past the government's ceiling, said Calder. 
</P>
<P>
	Desktop PCs have become a target of export restrictions in part  
because they have become far more powerful than in the past. More 
worrisome from a national security standpoint is the practice of 
parallel processing -- linking several desktops together to combine 
their computing power. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, chip manufacturers had hoped to see the ceiling lifted  
this year to allow easier export of the newer chips coming on line. 
</P>
<P>
	``The irony of it is we produce microprocessors in the millions  
each month and ship them through literally thousands of dealers all 
over the world,'' said Calder. ``Those other distributors can sell 
without restriction to any other country in the world. So the 
export controls in reality don't work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	American machine tool manufacturers already lose about $250  
million a year in China sales to European competitors because of 
existing export controls, said Paul Freedenberg, government 
relations director for the Association of Manufacturing Technology. 
The total overseas market for the industry is about $2.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The association supports controls on equipment that clearly can  
be used to improve China's military capabilities, but greater 
restrictions would only hurt U.S. companies, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. has a very tight system on most products. What  
happens is the U.S. companies that operate under that system lose 
business to the Europeans. The Europeans basically see it as a 
market opportunity.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
