<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Party Head Confirms Clinton's Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton intends to form a  
U.S. Senate exploratory committee and wants to spend part of the 
summer visiting families in upstate New York, the state's 
Democratic Party chief said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``She seems very exuberant and very excited,'' Judith Hope said.  
``Her commitment seems to be increasing toward this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hope said Mrs. Clinton called her Wednesday morning from  
Florida, where she is vacationing with the president, to ask for 
help in setting up this summer's visits. 
</P>
<P>
	``She said she doesn't want to do big events,'' Hope said. ``She  
wants to sit in people's living rooms and hear what kind of 
problems they're dealing with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is eyeing the Senate seat being vacated next year  
by Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan. New York City Mayor Rudolph 
Giuliani, among others, is looking at the race on the Republican 
side. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides to Mrs. Clinton have said that if she did set up an  
exploratory committee, it would mean she was almost certain to take 
the next step of entering the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Hope said Mrs. Clinton told her she planned to ``do a lot of  
first lady things'' after her current Florida vacation, ``and that 
if she is still leaning in the direction that she seems to be, 
which is toward making the race, she would expect to be creating an 
exploratory committee in late June or early July.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sources close to Mrs. Clinton had previously laid out similar  
timetables, but Hope's comments mark the first time one of the 
first lady's advisers has been willing to talk publicly about it. 
</P>
<P>
	Hope's comments came from one day after Robert Gigante, Staten  
Island's party chairman, said Mrs. Clinton had told him at a New 
York City fund-raiser the night before that she would run. 
</P>
<P>
	Gigante first made the remarks in an interview with the Staten  
Island Advance, then told other news organizations the same thing. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Mrs. Clinton's top adviser, Harold Ickes, said the  
first lady didn't tell Gigante any such thing. Gigante said he and 
his wife were making small talk with Mrs. Clinton when he brought 
up the subject. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ended by saying, `Do you have any good news for Staten  
Island?' and she said, `Yes,''' Gigante reported. ```Does that mean 
that you're running?' And she said, `Yes.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about the exchange, Ickes said that according to Mrs.  
Clinton, the first lady told Gigante that she is thinking it over 
and hasn't decided yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Told about Hope's comments Wednesday, Ickes said again that the  
first lady had not made a decision about the race. ``This week is a 
big week for her,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not dispute the first lady's likely timetable as laid out  
by Hope. 
</P>
<P>
	While the first lady ponders a Senate bid, she has all but ruled  
out any presidential aspirations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not even in the universe of my thinking,'' Mrs. Clinton  
said during a CBS ``60 Minutes II'' interview airing Wednesday 
night. She acknowledged that people have broached her about the 
idea of her running for president one day, but said she doesn't 
take such suggestions seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not possible, I don't believe,'' she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
