<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marge Schott Speaks Out Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Cincinnati Reds owner Marge Schott has decided  
to speak out again, telling a television station that she never 
imagined anyone would call her racist. 
</P>
<P>
	Schott allowed WCPO-TV into her suburban home for an interview  
that aired in part on Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, National League spokeswoman Katy Feeney said today  
she was unaware of Schott's comments. Feeney said she would inquire 
into whether baseball had granted permission for the interview to 
take place. 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of her current punishment from baseball, Schott is  
barred from giving interviews without baseball's permission. She 
was fined $10,000 by the National League for giving interviews in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Schott has twice been disciplined by major league baseball for  
inflammatory remarks. She was suspended by baseball's executive 
council for the 1993 season because of ``racially and ethnically 
offensive'' remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked by WCPO if she ever could have conceived of anyone calling  
her racist, Schott said, ``I wouldn't think so because I know how I 
was raised, I know the way we were brought up and I love people. I 
just like good people and don't like bad people and everybody's 
special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schott agreed to turn day-to-day running of the club over to  
managing executive John Allen in 1996 rather than accept another 
suspension for more inflammatory remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, she agreed to let Allen continue running the club  
while she tries to sell it rather than risk another suspension for 
allegedly using the names of Reds' employees on falsified sales 
records for her auto dealership. 
</P>
<P>
	Schott agreed to sell all but one of her shares to three of the  
team's current limited partners on April 20. Major league baseball 
hasn't yet approved the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why she decided to sell, Schott said, ``I usually don't  
like to give up on anything, but there comes a time when you have 
to do something.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
