<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 14:11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Parcells: At Least One More Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- Despite the impending sale of the New  
York Jets, coach Bill Parcells isn't going anywhere for at least 
one more season. 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells said Wednesday that John Hess, son of the late owner,  
had assured him there will be no changes in the front office 
through the 1999-2000 campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``He told me there'd be nothing that disturbs this season,''  
Parcells said Wednesday at the start of a three-day veterans 
minicamp. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I'm worried about is that. He said for me to run the  
operation as I've been running it, and if I need any help from the 
estate in doing that, to let him know. I was comforted a great deal 
about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells, entering the third year of a six-year contract that  
pays him approximately $2.4 million annually, reportedly has a 
clause in the deal that protects him financially if the 
relationship is severed early for any reason. 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells, 57, won't confirm whether he plans to retire following  
the coming season. 
</P>
<P>
	``My contract is explicit,'' he said, declining to elaborate.  
``So, I don't have any concern about that. I told the players that, 
my coaches know that and we're just looking forward to the season. 
I don't foresee any problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of his own future, the coach added, ``Write whatever you want. I  
haven't had anything to say about it. I coach every year, and at 
the end of the year I decide what's going on. There's obviously 
going to be some changes here and we'll just have to see what the 
new ownership wants to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Parcells leaves, his successor is expected to be current  
assistant head coach Bill Belichick. When Belichick, the former 
coach of the Cleveland Browns, was hired by Leon Hess in early 
1996, his contract stipulated that he would become head coach when 
Parcells left. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale of the Jets is being supervised by the investment firm  
of Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., with assistance from team president Steve 
Gutman. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation about potential bidders, who likely would invest at  
least $500 million for the franchise, has included Cablevision 
chairman Charles Dolan and his brother, Larry, a Cleveland 
attorney, New York Yankees principal owner George Steinbrenner, New 
York Mets co-owner Nelson Doubleday and New Jersey Devils owner 
John McMullen, among others. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the 79 players who gathered at the Jets complex  
Wednesday said that the pending sale of the team would have little 
effect on their preparation for the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Personally, I don't think it will make an impact on me at all,  
or I won't let it, anyway,'' Pro Bowl quarterback Vinny Testaverde 
said. ``I don't worry about who's going to be the next owner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever the outcome, Parcells feels that the Hess estate won't  
be in any hurry to get something done. 
</P>
<P>
	``I get the sense that they're going to be very thorough about  
this,'' Parcells said. ``I don't see anything happening for a 
while. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope they find someone who's as good as the guy we had --  
which would probably be tough to do.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 23:51:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Administration Defends Power Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is defending its  
plan for deregulating electric rates against concerns by rural 
lawmakers it would mean higher bills and poorer service in remote 
areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``No restructuring plan currently before the Congress is as  
complete or as sensitive to rural concerns as is the president's 
bill. ... One way or another, restructuring is coming,'' said Wally 
Beyer, administrator of the Agriculture Department's Rural 
Utilities Service. 
</P>
<P>
	A bill the administration introduced last month would require  
electric utilities to start competing for customers. All consumers 
would be allowed to choose their utility by 2003 unless their 
states decided after public hearings that they want to continue 
regulating rates. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a dozen states already have moved toward deregulating  
rates on their own. But administration officials told a House 
