<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 07:21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets rose Wednesday, with  
Seoul's key index soaring on a weaker Japanese yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained  
16.29 points, or 0.10 percent, to close at 16,230.52. On Tuesday, 
the average shed 176.26 points, or 1.08 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic institutional investors were buying some blue chips,  
including Sony Corp. and Fujitsu Ltd., but the market generally 
lacked direction, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the U.S. dollar fell against the Japanese  
yen for a second consecutive day on selling by overseas investors, 
retreating from last week's seven-month high. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.10 yen in the late afternoon, down 0.62  
yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York 
level of 122.70 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The stronger yen and easing domestic interest rates fueled a  
strong rally in South Korean stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	In Seoul, the key Kospi index soared 3.1 percent, or 21.36  
points, to 720.05. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen is believed to be positive for the price  
competitiveness of South Korean companies, which directly compete 
with Japanese companies in roughly half of their exports. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, stock prices ended a volatile session higher, with  
strong futures-related buying pulling the blue-chip index up near 
the market's close. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index rose 0.5 percent, or 62.25 points,  
to 12,409.16. It had fallen 0.7 percent Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the higher close, caution over a possible U.S. interest  
rate hike deterred aggressive buying. Hong Kong interest rate 
movements usually follow those of the United States because the 
Hong Kong dollar is pegged to the U.S. currency. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 123.58  
points, or 1.2 percent, to close at 10,531.09 on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Shares rebounded as local and foreign investors picked  
up selected blue chips, which had plunged Tuesday. The SET index 
rose 7.16 points, or 1.6 percent, to 458.21. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Shares fell as a recent rally lost steam. The JSX  
Composite Index fell 14.090 points, or 2.3 percent, at 605.787. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares fell as investors cashed in on some  
index-linked stocks. The Kuala Lumpur Composite Index fell 4.28 
points, or 0.56 percent, at 753.82 points. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares rose ahead of Friday's scheduled release of first  
quarter economic data, which many predict will be favorable. The 
PSE Index rose 19.98 points, 0.8 percent, at 2,390.35. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares prices closed nearly flat, as late  
bargain-hunting lent support to the market. The Straits Times Index 
closed 2.48 points, or 0.1 percent, lower at 1,893.73. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares rose following sharp gains in the banking and  
media sectors, which helped counter widespread losses in some 
mining and energy companies. The All Ordinaries Index rose 7.0 
points, or 0.2 percent, at 2,918.5. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Shares rose as investors bought back selected technology  
shares amid more optimistic market sentiment. The Weighted Price 
Index rose 9.60 points, or 0.12 percent, to 7,426.63. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares rose on gains in local forestry stocks such  
as Fletcher Challenge Ltd. and Carter Holt Harvey Ltd. The NZSE-40 
Capital Index rose 6.10 points, or 0.29 percent, at 2,100.60. 

</P>
</TEXT>
