<DOCNO> APW19990526.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 06:30:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRS Chief Testifies on Collections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tax collections by the IRS won't be  
jeopardized by broad new taxpayer rights, but they will be hurt if 
Congress fails to provide the agency with enough money to do its 
job, IRS Commissioner Charles Rossotti says. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of Internal Revenue Service employees has dropped  
13.7 percent since 1993, making it harder to keep up enforcement 
actions while implementing a 1998 reform law emphasizing taxpayer 
service first, Rossotti told a congressional panel Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Rossotti noted that the number of returns with over  
$100,000 in income has risen 56 percent over the past five years, 
while the number of those returns subjected to audits is down 21 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The path that the IRS has taken cannot continue,'' he said.  
``Doing business the same way while the economy grows and resources 
decline will eventually undermine the whole tax system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he added that only about 2 percent of the $1.7 trillion in  
taxes collected this year come from enforcement actions, making it 
imperative to stress improvement in service for the 98 percent of 
taxpayers who comply willingly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe we have a choice to make between effective tax  
collection and fair treatment of taxpayers,'' Rossotti said. ``We 
do have to effectively target our enforcement where it's really 
needed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rossotti's comment came at a joint House-Senate panel composed  
of members of seven committees with jurisdiction over the IRS and 
tax law. The 1998 law requires such a session each year to get an 
overall look at the agency's performance and needs. 
</P>
<P>
	After 18 months on the job, Rossotti has broad support among  
Republicans and Democrats on Capitol Hill as he tries to convert an 
entrenched bureaucracy into one more responsive to taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I recognize that the task of modernizing the IRS is not an  
easy one and may take some time,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, 
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, several lawmakers questioned the drop in enforcement  
actions in the first half of 1999. Garnishments of wages and levies 
on bank accounts, for example, are down to 458,000, from 1.8 
million during the same time period two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Rossotti said the causes were threefold: gradual budget  
reductions that have shrunk the IRS staff, requirements that 
collections agents perform other duties such as answering taxpayer 
calls and worker fears of mandatory firing under new laws -- known 
by workers as the ``10 deadly sins'' -- covering willful misconduct 
and mistreatment of taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are issues that have certainly caused confusion and  
anxiety in our work force,'' Rossotti said. 
</P>
<P>
	Intensive training continues to ease those fears and it will  
take time for employees to become accustomed to the new 
service-oriented IRS, he added. But Congress must support spending 
on technology, new business practices and management. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS is putting much of its stock in electronic tax filing  
programs, but on Tuesday acknowledged a glitch in one of them. The 
company contracted to handle credit card payments made errors in 
13,700 transactions on April 15, mistakenly applying the payment to 
1999 taxes instead of the 1998 return. 
</P>
<P>
	Rossotti said anyone who received an IRS notice for tax due  
after paying with a credit card that day should do nothing. The 
company, U.S. Audiotex, will contact taxpayers about the correction 
being made and no penalties will be assessed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
