<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Address ILO Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla. (AP) -- Trying to change the debate around trade  
policy, President Clinton will address the International Labor 
Organization in Geneva next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's June 16 speech will be the first by a U.S. president  
to the international body of government ministers and the leaders 
of unions and business associations around the globe. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know that he said in his State of the Union address that  
he wanted to put a human face on the global economy,'' said Labor 
Secretary Alexis Herman. ``This visit clearly will be a reflection 
of the fact that we're going to bring that face into focus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wants to increase trade as a hedge against the financial  
turmoil that recently rocked Asia and Latin America. He insists 
that fast-track negotiating power is essential to carry out his 
plans to organize a new round of global trade talks and to bring 
Chile into the North American Free Trade Agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	But organized labor has led a coalition that successfully  
defeated efforts to re-authorize fast-track negotiating authority, 
saying that workers' rights must be spelled out in the heart of 
trade agreements. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past year, with speeches to the World Trade  
Organization, the Council on Foreign Relations and other groups, 
Clinton has sought to steer a new course through the debate, 
acknowledging labor's concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	As he speaks out against child labor, sweatshops and unsafe  
working conditions, he also is highlighting how trade can help 
create jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials said the ILO speech will offer a deeper  
explanation of Clinton's views on trade and policy proposals to 
protect workers. Too often, Herman said, trade is viewed only from 
the point of view of markets and profits. ``It is also about 
working families and working conditions,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ILO, founded 1919, operates on the basis of consensus and  
often is seen as a weak enforcer of international labor standards. 
But the Clinton administration has been encouraged by the 
leadership of new ILO chief Juan Somovia of Chile. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the president secured $30 million for the ILO to  
fight child labor around the globe and this year the 
administration's $35 million proposal for a fiscal 2000 Labor 
Standards Initiative embraced the ILO's efforts to hold members 
accountable for labor rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
