<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies Co-Owner Facing Bankruptcy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Attorneys agreed at a federal bankruptcy hearing  
Wednesday to allow a trucking company owned by Colorado Rockies 
co-owner Jerry McMorris to continue operating through Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver-based NationsWay Transport filed for Chapter 11  
bankruptcy protection on May 20, citing deregulation and 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys representing the company, creditors and union truckers  
signed off on the plan during a hearing before U.S. Bankrupcty 
Court Judge Sarah Sharer Curley. 
</P>
<P>
	McMorris has a controlling interest in the Rockies, but has said  
that NationsWay is separate from the baseball club. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's not separate in the minds of NationsWay employees who  
attended the hearing. The bankruptcy left more than 1,000 employees 
out of work in Denver and 3,500 unemployed nationally. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Teamsters members who attended the hearing called the  
trucking company's bankruptcy a ``deliberate plan'' by McMorris. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was all pre-planned. He used this to fund the ballclub,''  
said Tom Woodhouse, a truck driver for 33 years and a member of 
Teamsters Local 104 in Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's court action allows NationsWay to pay operating  
expenses for work done since the bankruptcy filing through Friday. 
A similar agreement had expired Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Another hearing was set for June 1.  
</P>
<P>
	Under Chapter 11, a company is free from the threat of  
creditors' lawsuits while it reorganizes its finances. The debtor's 
reorganization plan must be approved by a majority of its 
creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	NationsWay attorney Donald Gaffney said the company filed for  
bankruptcy in Phoenix because its largest terminal is here. Other 
trucking terminals are in Denver, Dallas and Harrisburg, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	Teamsters officials filed claims to recover unpaid wages and  
other monetary compensation due its members who work for 
NationsWay. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Gary Keltner, representing the Central States Health  
and Welfare Pension fund, said NationsWay faces a $2 million claim 
on behalf of employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman Chip Roth of the union's international office said  
NationsWay truck drivers were last paid on May 18 and missed their 
first paycheck this week. 
</P>
<P>
	McMorris, who built the trucking company from three rigs in 1959  
to more than 2,000, is involved in several business ventures, 
including two other trucking companies. Critics have suggested that 
McMorris spent too much time focusing on his baseball team and not 
enough time trying to save NationsWay. 
</P>
<P>
	Union officials say members are angered that McMorris pays his  
baseball players millions but is unable to pay truckers' pensions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 16:02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASCAR Explores Safety Options </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Stock car racing's sanctioning body is  
exploring ways to prevent the wheels and hoods of vehicles from 
flying off in crashes and possibly landing in the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	Safety tethers on wheels have become a hot topic lately in  
racing because of two fatal accidents in the past year, both of 
which involved wheels that snapped off cars and flew into 
grandstands, killing spectators. 
</P>
<P>
	All three of the world's major open-wheel circuits have enacted  
rules requiring the use of wheel tethers. 
</P>
<P>
	But unlike the open-wheel tethers, which are made of relatively  
expensive fibers and can require intricate installations, the 
device being considered by NASCAR is easy to install and doesn't 
cost much. 
</P>
<P>
	The tether is merely a section of braided steel cable about a  
foot long and fastened into a loop at each end. NASCAR officials 
paid $7 for each unit, and because the sanctioning body feels that 
only the front wheels need to be secured, the cost would be $14 per 
car. 
</P>
<P>
	The devices are relatively simple and inexpensive because the  
suspension systems on Winston Cup cars are radically different from 
those on open-wheel cars. While Indy-car wheels and suspension 
systems are designed to break free in crashes, the opposite is true 
with Winston Cup cars. 
</P>
<P>
	No spectators have ever been injured by a wheel or suspension  
parts that flew off a Winston Cup car. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoods are a different matter, however. They have been known to  
fly into stands at races, especially those on the circuit's larger 
tracks where the speeds are highest. 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR is trying to develop a frame structure that would  
strengthen the hood and make it less likely to fly off in 
high-speed crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	The wheel cables were tested on a few cars during last week's  
all-star race activities at Lowe's Motor Speedway at Charlotte. 
NASCAR plans to test them again this weekend during the Coca-Cola 
600 Winston Cup race and the CarQuest 300 Busch Grand National 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very possible we can make them mandatory by Dover next  
week,'' NASCAR senior vice president Mike Helton said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR officials are considering experimenting with a new hood  
frame design this week at Charlotte, but only during a test 
session. No cars are to use the new design during any races this 
weekend, and Helton said no timetable has been set to implement any 
changes. 
</P>
<P>
	Helton said NASCAR had been looking at improving wheel cables  
and hood designs for several months, but the sanctioning body 
``turned up the wick'' after a fatal Indy-car race at Charlotte 
earlier this month. Three spectators were killed and eight injured 
when a wheel and suspension parts from a three-car wreck flew into 
the stands during an Indy Racing League event. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it happens one time,'' Helton said, ``it's too much.''  
</P>
<P>
	One of the Winston Cup cars testing the wheel cables last week  
was the Pontiac driven by Ward Burton and owned by Bill Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had no problems at all with them, but it's kind of a  
non-issue,'' Davis said. ``Tearing off suspension parts and them 
getting into the stands has really never been an issue. But at the 
same time, fan safety has to be our top concern, so if NASCAR 
decides to go with them, I don't think there's going to be any 
opposition down here.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 14:41:35 </DATE_TIME>
