</P>
<P>
	Factory Orders Fall 2.3 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A decline in demand for autos and other  
transportation equipment led a 2.3 percent decline in orders to 
U.S. factories for big-ticket manufactured goods in April, the 
second drop in the past three months. But Treasury Secretary Robert 
Rubin warned against reading too much into any one report and the 
president of the National Association of Manufacturers, economist 
Jerry Jasinowski, interpreted the numbers as indicating that the 
economy is moving to a ``more sustainable'' pace after two quarters 
of unusually strong growth. The April decline followed a 2.7 
percent increase in March. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM Has a Good Day  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- IBM rose 15 1/16 to 236 1/4 on the New York Stock  
Exchange today after its shares had dropped in recent sessions. 
Investors are returning to buy the widely held stock at a more 
affordable price. And it will become ``cheaper'' yet. After the 
close of trading, a 2-for-1 stock split was to take effect. 

</P>
<P>
	SEC Points Finger at Ex-IBM Worker  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An IBM secretary who knew of the company's plans  
to take over Lotus Development Corp. tipped off her husband, 
leading 25 people to pocket more than $1.3 million from insider 
trading, the Securities and Exchange Commission charged today. In 
papers filed in Federal Court in Manhattan, the SEC says that after 
the secretary, Lorraine K. Cassano, who has since been fired, told 
her husband of the plan, he told two friends, who agreed to 
purchase stock for him, and the word spread from there. The Lotus 
acquisition occurred in 1995. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Questions Gov't. Expert  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A computer expert who will be one of the final  
witnesses in the Microsoft trial revealed today how he has improved 
his method of disabling the Internet browser in Windows, touching 
on a central claim in the government's antitrust case. Edward 
Felten, a computer science professor at Princeton University, said 
some changes to his controversial technique were prompted by 
comments from Microsoft witnesses. Felten previously testified as 
one of the Justice Department's dozen witnesses. Microsoft 
questioned him again under oath today in a deposition at the 
federal courthouse here. The government wants Felten to take the 
stand again next month -- during the trial's rebuttal phase -- to 
rebut earlier testimony from Microsoft executive James Allchin. The 
trial resumes Monday after a 13-week break. 

</P>
<P>
	Small Businesses Offer Web Tips  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Small businesses looking for success on the  
Internet should have functional, well-designed Web sites and 
advertising good enough to lure customers, a New England seafood 
retailer told a House committee today. Hanson Bros. Fresh Seafood 
of Portland, Maine, launched its Web site in February and already 
Internet sales account for 25 percent to 30 percent of the 
company's fresh fish and seafood business, said Brian Hanson, the 
owner. He was not sure what to expect from going online, but said 
he was lucky to get help from an Internet service provider that 
helped put him on the Web. 

</P>
<P>
	Maxwell Auditors Settle Lawsuit  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Coopers &AMP; Lybrand today agreed to pay more than  
$108 million over its role in the affairs of the late media baron 
Robert Maxwell. Coopers &AMP; Lybrand, which merged with Price 
Waterhouse in 1998 to form PricewaterhouseCoopers, was the auditor 
for Maxwell Communication Corp. Maxwell disappeared in mysterious 
circumstances at sea off his yacht in 1991. Earlier that year, his 
empire had collapsed. The company administrators sued Coopers &AMP; 
Lybrand for $160 million for failing to spot any problems at the 
Maxwell corporation. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Delays Payments in Boeing Case  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- A federal court judge today delayed the  
distribution of money in the settlement of a discrimination lawsuit 
against Boeing Co. so that a group objecting to the deal can state 
its case. U.S. District Judge John Coughenour scheduled another 
hearing in the matter Sept. 23 after attorneys take depositions. 
The $15 million settlement of the class-action lawsuit was 
announced on Jan. 22 and covers about 12,900 past and present black 
Boeing workers. Attorney Alan B. Epstein of Philadelphia, who 
represents dozens of Boeing workers, filed the challenge to the 
settlement. He has said the settlement doesn't provide enough money 
or enforcement to prevent future discrimination. Boeing lawyers 
have called Epstein's challenge ``sour grapes'' from a lawyer who 
was less effective in the case ``and therefore is not getting as 
much money in attorney fees.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Sallie Mae Buys New England Firm  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sallie Mae, the nation's largest financer of  
student loans, has made its first big strategic move since becoming 
private, agreeing to buy a New England student loan maker for $320 
million. The acquisition was announced today by Sallie Mae, once a 
government-sponsored company that went private two years ago. 
Nellie Mae, with offices in Braintree, Mass., and Rumford, R.I., is 
the seventh-largest holder of federal student loans with a 
portfolio valued at $2.6 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Charter To Buy Falcon Cable  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen took a major  
step toward becoming a cable TV baron with a deal announced today 
to acquire Los Angeles-based cable company Falcon Communications. 
The deal, the latest in the rapidly consolidating cable TV 
industry, will make Allen's Charter Communications Inc. of St. 
Louis the nation's fourth-largest cable company with 5.5 million 
subscribers. Charter officials put the price of the deal at $3.6 
billion in cash and stock but did not provide a breakdown or 
comment on how much assumed debt was included in the transaction. 

</P>
<P>
	AirTran Faults Delta on Pricing  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Discount carrier AirTran claims Delta Air Lines  
is cutting fares on key routes to drive out competition and 
ultimately raise fares. AirTran sent a brief to the Justice and 
Transportation Departments outlining the accusations on the heels 
of a government lawsuit against American Airlines for predatory 
pricing against smaller rivals. ``Delta's competitive response to 
AirTran over the years, and increasingly in recent days, has only 
one objective -- drive a small-but-growing, successful low-fare 
carrier out of its markets,'' the brief said. Delta spokesman Bill 
Berry called the charges ``insulting and untrue.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Durable goods: down 2.3 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Gross domestic product  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Jobless claims  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Personal income  


