<DOCNO> APW19990526.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 11:41:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airports Lack Security at Bag Claim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Checking in at an airport, it's hard to miss  
the preoccupation with baggage security. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did you pack your own bags?'' the ticket agent asks. ``Did  
anyone ask you to carry anything on board?'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's a different story when passengers arrive at their  
destinations. 
</P>
<P>
	At some airports, such as Los Angeles International, most  
airlines will not let passengers leave baggage claim areas without 
showing a claim stub for their luggage. But at others, including 
Reagan National and Dulles International near Washington, no one 
checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Anyone can grab anything or, perhaps more worrisome for  
security, can leave a bag or package behind. The only safeguards 
are signs or public address warnings noting that many bags look 
alike so passengers should check their luggage tags. 
</P>
<P>
	In April 1998, police arrested a man who took advantage of such  
lax security at Dallas-Fort Worth Airport. They said that James 
Clarence Ringley of Arlington, Texas, stole about 500 bags from 
airline baggage belts and used the contents -- worth an estimated $1 
million -- to stock a booth at a flea market. 
</P>
<P>
	Airport police said it was the largest recovery of luggage at  
any major U.S. airport. Ringley recently received four years in 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've wondered about it a few times as I've walked out with all  
kinds of bags and nobody's checked me,'' said J.T. Maiorano of New 
York, a lighting technician who travels over 150,000 miles 
annually. 
</P>
<P>
	Standing outside the USAirways claim area at Reagan National,  
where he just picked up a garment bag unchallenged, Maiorano said, 
``I wouldn't mind at all being checked. ... I'd rather do it than 
get ripped off of my luggage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government requires the baggage questions at  
check-in and the constant reminders about unattended luggage. 
</P>
<P>
	But security at the end of a trip -- in the baggage claim areas --  
is the responsibility of individual airlines. They typically lease 
and operate baggage belts from an airport authority. Airlines, in 
turn, say they provide checkpoints where they are needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we don't have a high incidence of problems, we don't do  
it,'' said United Airlines spokesman Joe Hopkins. ``It helps keep 
down the cost of air travel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some airports like Hartsfield in Atlanta or Miami International  
provide baggage area security in many terminals as a basic service 
to their airline tenants. Atlanta, which handles 200,000 passengers 
a day, spends about $1.5 million annually on it. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, said Hartsfield spokeswoman Lanii Thomas, the  
airport does not have a high rate of baggage theft. 
</P>
<P>
	Airports generally don't keep track of stolen bags, deferring to  
the airlines. The carriers themselves are loath to report a bag as 
stolen, preferring to say that it is ``missing.'' Often a bag that 
has been reported stolen ends up back at its intended destination 
after a journey on the wrong flight. 
</P>
<P>
	The Transportation Department tracks mishandled bags -- those  
that are lost, damaged, delayed or ``pilfered.'' In March, the 
major U.S. airlines had about five reports of mishandled bags for 
every 1,000 they handled, about the same as the year before. 
</P>
<P>
	Tightening security at baggage claim areas is not always  
foolproof. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Los Angeles police arrested a man who allegedly raided  
the airline baggage belts at Los Angeles International and walked 
away with 11 sets of golf clubs, professional camera equipment, a 
snowboard and other items worth an estimated $20,000. 
</P>
<P>
	While the airport had and continues to use a bag-matching  
program, the suspect found a way around it: He wore a Delta Air 
Lines pilot uniform and a fake ID and strode confidently past the 
checkout gates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 21:19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Japanese Worried About Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- With its economy stuck in a deep slump, three out  
of four Japanese are worried about job security, according to a 
newspaper survey released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey by the Yomiuri newspaper showed that 76 percent of  
those polled said they are worried about current and future 
employment for themselves and other family members. 
</P>
<P>
	The figure was up by 8 percentage points from a similar Yomiuri  
survey in February 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest survey, conducted May 15-16, asked the opinion of  
2,035 eligible voters picked randomly across Japan. As with many 
Japanese opinion polls, no margin of error was given. 
</P>
<P>
	In particular, concerns over possibly losing jobs anytime soon  
were most severely felt by the middle-aged -- 83 percent of those in 
their 40s and 84 percent in their 50s, the survey said. 
</P>
<P>
	In late April, the government reported Japan's unemployment rate  
in March climbed to yet another record high of 4.8 percent, as 
corporate restructuring efforts force more people out of work. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say Japan's jobless rates will rise in coming months as  
the nation is undergoing profound structural changes in the economy 
and the breakdown of traditional business practices. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey showed that 64 percent of Japanese say that a  
performance-based wage system is more desirable than the 
traditional pay scale based on seniority, which was supported by 33 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a proof that people are beginning to accept changes in  
employment practice,'' Atsushi Seike, a professor on labor economy 
at Tokyo's Keio University, told the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 14:12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alaska Hesitant To Tap Oil Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) -- Faced with a huge budget shortfall, the  
Alaska Legislature raised a knife to the state's most sacred cow -- 
the $26 billion oil-royalty fund -- then passed the blade to the 
voters. 
</P>
<P>
	In a nonbinding election Sept. 14, Alaskans will make a choice  
people in other states might envy: 
</P>
<P>
	Should the annual dividend check every man, woman and child  
receives in Alaska continue climbing from last year's $1,540, or 
should its growth be reined in to help keep the state free of an 
income tax or a state sales tax? 
</P>
<P>
	If voters say yes, lawmakers plan to cut the dividend to about  
$1,340 in 2001 and dedicate some of the fund's earnings to 
balancing the budget. The fund is expected to pay Alaskans 
dividends of more than $1,700 this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The question is such political poison that lawmakers deadlocked  
for more than a week over whether to even ask it. Only a carefully 
negotiated compromise won over enough reluctant state senators to 
pass the bill Tuesday evening. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important thing that we did today is agree to ask  
Alaskans a question,'' Senate President Drue Pearce said. ``It is 
responsible, it is realistic, it is definitely workable, and we 
hope that Alaskans will take the time to understand it and to tell 
us what they think in September.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oil royalties and taxes have paid for most of state government  
since the late 1970s. The wealth was so abundant that the public 
voted in 1976 to sock some of it away in what is called the Alaska 
Permanent Fund. Six years later, the fund began paying dividends to 
Alaska residents. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, dwindling oil production and slumping prices have widened a  
gap between state spending and income to more than $1 billion, a 
shortfall that could drain the state's budget-balancing reserve 
within three years. 
</P>
<P>
	For more than four months, lawmakers have grappled with  
fundamental questions surrounding the fund and its dividend. 
</P>
<P>
	Is the fund a rainy-day account to pay for state government or a  
vault to safeguard some of Alaska's wealth from politicians who 
would fritter it away on pork? 
</P>
<P>
	Is the dividend a giveaway that has outlived its time, or an  
inviolate entitlement that keeps thousands of families out of 
poverty? 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no way to avoid the use of Permanent Fund  
earnings,'' said House Speaker Brian Porter, a Republican. ``No 
amount of reasonable statewide taxes could come close to filling 
the gap that we're faced with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now the focus shifts to two questions: How to persuade voters to  
take hundreds of dollars out of their pockets for government, and 
what to do if they say no. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we go back to the drawing board at that point,'' said  
Sen. Sean Parnell, a Republican. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:06:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  IRL and CART Hold Unification talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The big names may be coming back to the  
Indianapolis 500. 
</P>
<P>
	After four years of bitter rivalry that threatened the future of  
open-wheel racing in the United States, CART and the IRL have begun 
face-to-face talks about bringing the two racing circuits together. 
</P>
<P>
	Word of the negotiations came as teams prepared for this  
weekend's race at the Indy 500, which has lost its luster during 
the feud as the best-known drivers stayed away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can confirm that there have been some very informal talks  
with Tony George,'' said Andrew Craig, president and CEO of 
Championship Auto Racing Teams. ``However, I am not prepared to 
comment on any of the details.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is no comment -- but also no denial of the talks -- from  
George, the Indianapolis Motor Speedway president who started the 
war when he formed the Indy Racing League late in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The answering salvo from CART was to quit the Indianapolis 500,  
leaving George to stage the world's most famous auto race with 
virtually no stars. 
</P>
<P>
	The differences between the two circuits once seemed  
insurmountable, with totally different chassis and engine rules in 
place. But the last few weeks have brought hope that a settlement 
could be achieved as early as 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his differences with George, who started the IRL as a  
low-cost, ovals-only alternative to CART, Craig says a merger would 
be in the best interests of both sides. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's CART's position that open-wheel racing would benefit  
greatly from having one series instead of two,'' Craig said. ``I 
think everyone in the industry would like to see it happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sources close to the two circuits who spoke on condition of  
anonymity say NASCAR president Bill France Jr., the most powerful 
man in American racing, is brokering the peace. 
</P>
<P>
	France did not return phone calls, but his interest is not  
surprising. International Speedway Corp., which owns and operates 
NASCAR, recently bought Penske Motorsports, giving ISC 10 
racetracks, with at least three more planned in the near future. 
</P>
<P>
	ISC will need more than just its stock car and truck divisions  
to keep those tracks busy and prosperous. 
</P>
<P>
	The war between CART and the IRL was destructive, and the timing  
couldn't have been worse, with NASCAR's emergence as the hottest 
American sport of the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	CART has been solid almost since its debut in 1979, but it  
attracts far fewer fans at tracks where NASCAR also races. Although 
the Indy 500 will race Sunday before another sellout crowd 
approaching 400,000, for the most part the IRL has not drawn well 
elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	When CART was the one major open-wheel entity in America, its TV  
ratings were adequate and building slowly. Since the split, neither 
side has drawn more than a bare audience, except for Indy. 
</P>
<P>
	And even the once mighty Memorial Day weekend classic has  
slipped from a high rating of 8.4 in 1995 to 5.5 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	But -- perhaps in hopes of a peace treaty -- ABC and ESPN haven't  
given up on either series. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN already had a deal with CART through 2001 before ABC  
re-upped for Indy last week, extending its contract through 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement also means ABC and ESPN will show the rest of the  
IRL schedule each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard Katz, the new president of ABC Sports and the catalyst in  
extending the current contract with George, says the biggest 
problem facing the open-wheel folks is building stars. 
</P>
<P>
	CART is perceived to have the big names, with Michael Andretti  
and Al Unser Jr. still its marquee drivers. But neither has won a 
championship in five years, and former Indy winners Mario Andretti, 
Bobby Rahal, Emerson Fittipaldi, Rick Mears, Al Unser Sr. and Danny 
Sullivan -- have retired in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the biggest stars stayed with CART, the IRL had a shaky  
foundation. Its one big-name driver, two-time Indy 500 winner Arie 
Luyendyk, will race Sunday for the final time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you've got to build stars,'' Katz said. ``You've got  
to have a reason to root for or even against people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sponsorships, which supply most of the money for race teams,  
also are a problem for open-wheel racing. 
</P>
<P>
	CART still has more than $400 million in sponsorship backing,  
but many of the long-term contracts will end in either 2000 or 
2001, with no guarantees they will be renewed. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL, which started from nothing in 1995, has built perhaps  
$50 million in sponsorship, but with minuscule TV ratings and 
little identity it continues to be a hard sell to corporate 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR, massively promoted and armed with high TV ratings,  
already has about $500 million annually in sponsorship money and 
continues to grow at a fast rate, drawing sponsors away from the 
open-wheel divisions. 
</P>
<P>
	PPG Industries, the longtime series sponsor for CART, is one of  
the few backers involved in both open-wheel series. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've managed to keep a foot in both camps, feeling that there  
was value on each side of the fence,'' said Mike Sack, PPG's 
director of motorsports. ``That's a difficult position to be in, 
not only from the standpoint of money, but also politically 
speaking. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know one sponsor that doesn't think peace between the  
series is a good idea.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:06:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
