<HEADLINE> Mobile OKs Spending for Bowl Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOBILE, Ala. (AP) -- The City Council agreed to provide $950,000  
for the inaugural Mobile Alabama Bowl, scheduled for Dec. 22. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowl organizer Mike Gottfried said he met with several city  
officials last week and cleared up most of the questions that led 
to Tuesday's council approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Mike Dow also issued a four-page memo to council members  
Monday with information on revenues, expenses, potential economic 
impact and other events surrounding the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were a lot of questions, but when we talked, all of them  
were answered,'' Gottfried said. 
</P>
<P>
	The game will be played at Ladd-Peebles Stadium, matching the  
bowl committee's second choice selections from Conference USA and 
the Western Athletic Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the WAC agreed to the bowl tie-in for one year only,  
Conference USA has committed to send a team for the next five 
years. Gottfried described Conference USA as ``bowl hungry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Council members said the bowl may need a few years to become  
successful. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can sit here and go through this contract and I could  
probably find a hundred reasons why I shouldn't do this,'' said 
Councilman Charles Waller. ``But at the same time, I can find a 
hundred reasons why I should.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Estimates of ticket sales, hotel nights and numbers of visitors  
are ``very conservative,'' according to the mayor's memo. The total 
direct economic impact to the city is estimated at about $5 
million, with a total economic impact of about $16.7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Each team must purchase 7,000 seats at a minimum of $45 per  
ticket, said WAC Commissioner Karl Benson. Payouts to the two teams 
are guaranteed at $750,000 each but could run as high as $850,000, 
depending on total revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	The city will receive eight 30-second commercials during the  
game, which will be shown on ESPN2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
