<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Milosevic May Face War Charges  
</P>
<P>
	THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- With speculation mounting that  
Slobodan Milosevic may soon be indicted, the tribunal charged with 
prosecuting war crimes in Yugoslavia said today it already is armed 
with evidence of atrocities ``on a massive scale.'' The U.N. 
court's chief prosecutor, Louise Arbour, said she would make ``an 
important announcement'' tomorrow. She would not comment on a CNN 
report citing European diplomatic sources as indicating an 
indictment against the Yugoslav leader was imminent. 

</P>
<P>
	UN Says Kosovo Is Calamitous  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A U.N. fact-finding team wrapped up  
an 11-day mission to Yugoslavia, calling the situation in Kosovo 
``calamitous'' and the humanitarian needs ``immense.'' The team was 
the first group of international observers allowed to visit Kosovo 
since the large-scale exodus of ethnic Albanians from the province 
began two months ago. About 840,000 have fled or been driven out by 
Serb forces. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Launches Extensive Strikes  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Blasts reverberated throughout  
dozens of Yugoslav cities today during a record number of NATO 
attack flights, which zeroed in once more on President Slobodan 
Milosevic's villa and hit army barracks and command posts. Jets 
bombarded Kosovo's capital, Pristina, its surroundings and the 
northern city of Novi Sad, Serb media reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Works During Vacation  
</P>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla. (AP) -- President Clinton played a round of golf and  
went biking with the first lady today on a secluded plantation in 
northern Florida. Clinton also received his daily security briefing 
on the Yugoslavia campaign, called the Italian prime minister and 
named Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel a special envoy to Macedonia to 
check up on refugees from Kosovo. ``He will stay in touch, as 
you've already seen today,'' White House press secretary Joe 
Lockhart said. ``But it's important from time to time to take a 
chance to get away.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Rejects Base-Closing Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate today rejected the Clinton  
administration's request to close more military bases as a 
cost-saving measure. The 60-40 Senate vote rejected a move by Sens. 
John McCain, R-Ariz., and Carl Levin, D-Mich., to authorize a new 
round of base closings in 2001 as part of an $288.8 billion defense 
spending bill for the fiscal year that begins Oct 1. ``The timing 
could not be worse'' for additional base closings, said Senate 
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. He said that, with the military 
already stetched thin by the conflict in Kosovo, it was no time to 
be closing down any military installations. 

</P>
<P>
	NTSB Recommends MD-11 Modifications  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government's transportation safety panel  
is recommending that the autopilot system in the Boeing MD-11 
jetliner be modified to prevent severe reactions when pilots try to 
make flight course changes. The National Transportation Safety 
Board said overreactions caused severe pitching during two 
incidents in 1996 and 1997, seriously injuring four passengers and 
a flight attendant. Boeing had warned of the potential problem in 
flight crew operating manuals. 

</P>
<P>
	Small Businesses Offer Web Tips  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Small businesses looking for success on the  
Internet should have functional, well-designed Web sites and 
advertising good enough to lure customers, a New England seafood 
retailer told a House committee today. Hanson Bros. Fresh Seafood 
of Portland, Maine, launched its Web site in February and already 
Internet sales account for 25 percent to 30 percent of the 
company's fresh fish and seafood business, said Brian Hanson, the 
owner. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends 171.07 Higher  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rebounded strongly today as  
bargain-hunters returned to a turbulent market following the 
biggest losing streak since late March. The Dow Jones industrial 
average shot up 171.07 points to close at 10,702.16. On the NYSE, 
losers led gainers 1,498-1,477. The Nasdaq rose 45.36 to 2,426.26. 

</P>
