<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Factory Orders Fall 2.3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Orders for big-ticket manufactured goods fell  
an unexpectedly sharp 2.3 percent last month, the Commerce 
Department reported today. Private economists did not regard the 
drop as a major setback to U.S. factories' recovery from a global 
financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline, the second in three months, was driven by falling  
orders for transportation and defense goods. Without big declines 
in these two areas, orders for durable goods would have risen a 
strong 2.9 percent, the government said. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall decline in durable goods, which are items expected  
to last three or more years, followed a solid 2.7 percent rise in 
orders in March. Many analysts expected a gain of around 0.4 
percent for April orders. 
</P>
<P>
	For business groups, the new economic report indicated the  
economy is not overheated. 
</P>
<P>
	``The economy is coasting to a more sustainable pace following  
two quarters of unusually strong growth,'' said economist Jerry 
Jasinowski, president of the National Association of Manufacturers. 
``The fundamental message of these numbers is that the economy is 
undergoing a mild slowdown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street, after four straight losing sessions attributed to  
concerns about inflation, reacted positively. The Dow Jones average 
of industrial stocks jumped 171 points to close at 10,702 on 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Durable goods declined by $4.5 billion last month to a  
seasonally adjusted $194.4 billion. The drop is the biggest since a 
3.9 percent fall in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the decline came from a 36.4 percent decline in military  
orders. Defense orders rose 41.2 percent in March. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new orders were down in large part because of the sharp  
reversal in defense orders which are likely to get stronger as we 
move through the year given all the ammunition we have used up in 
Kosovo,'' said economist Paul Kasriel of Northern Trust Company of 
Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to defense, the other big source of weakness was a  
12.4 percent drop in demand for autos, aircraft and other 
transportation products. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you strip away transportation and defense, durable goods  
were actually up. And, that is more representative of what is going 
on in manufacturing,'' said Mark Zandi, economist at Regional 
Financial Associates in West Chester, Pa. ``Manufacturing has had a 
dismal couple of years, but I think there is light at the end of 
the tunnel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The global currency crisis has plunged one-third of the world  
into recession and contributed to the loss of more than 400,000 
U.S. manufacturing jobs over the past year. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite this weakness, the overall U.S. economy has continued to  
forge ahead, growing at an annual rate of 4.5 percent during the 
first three months of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The government will release a revised estimate for economic  
growth in the first quarter on Thursday. Many analysts believe it 
will show growth near the 4.5 percent level. 
</P>
<P>
	A key gauge of future economic activity, the Index of Leading  
Indicators, has risen for six straight months. While durable goods 
is a component of the index, analysts said the April drop should 
not have much effect because manufacturing has been weak for some 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, the steel industry, competing against a flood of  
cheap imports from countries such as Japan, has suffered. But in 
the April report showed that primary metals, the sector that 
includes steel, had a 1.3 percent increase -- offering hope of a 
rebound. 
</P>
<P>
	Orders for industrial machinery rose by 3.5 percent in April,  
the fourth increase in this sector in the past six months, while 
orders for electronic equipment dropped 0.7 percent in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipments of big-ticket durable goods, a sign of current demand,  
fell 0.6 percent in April. compared with a 1.9 percent increase the 
previous month. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
