<HEADLINE> Detroit Cops Have Toilet Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- An alleged toilet paper shortage at police  
stations prompted a radio station to donate rolls on Wednesday, but 
city officials say there's plenty of TP for the P.D. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're somebody in need at a particular time, and you're  
sitting there, it's an emergency to you, but we just have not been 
able to detect that there hasn't been toilet paper,'' said Greg 
Bowens, spokesman for Mayor Dennis Archer. 
</P>
<P>
	City Council Member Key Everett said Tuesday the situation is an  
example of a supply problem throughout city departments caused by 
Detroit's new computer system. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowens said that was news to him.  
</P>
<P>
	Precincts may have overreacted when they received partial cases  
of tissue instead of the customary full-case deliveries, 
authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	As word of the shortage spread Wednesday, officers in one  
precinct called a radio station in search of donations. The result: 
420 rolls. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the precinct never called building maintenance first to  
request toilet paper, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sgt. Roslyn Beard said: ``I've been carrying my own since I was  
a little girl ... My mama taught me that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
