<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Delphi Takes Final Step Away From GM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Delphi Automotive Systems Corp. declares its  
independence Friday, when General Motors Corp. distributes its 
remaining shares of the world's biggest auto parts manufacturer to 
sever Delphi's final ties to GM. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the move was planned well in advance, some GM  
shareholders may be surprised when they open up a newspaper stock 
table and see GM shares had drop nearly $15 overnight as a result 
of the spinoff. 
</P>
<P>
	But looks can be deceiving. While GM stock will drop about 17  
percent, or $14.42 a share, as a result of the spinoff, current 
stockholders essentially will have the same stock value because 
they will get Delphi shares. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the current shareholder there's no drop,'' said Mark  
Tanner, GM's director of financial communications. ``All other 
things being equal, you're going to have the same money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GM shareholders will get 0.69893 -- about seven-tenths -- of a  
share of Delphi common stock for each share of GM stock. About 
452.56 million shares of Delphi stock will be distributed to 
shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that as Delphi grows, then the stock will be of great  
value to me,'' said stockholder and GM retiree Ralph Drake. ``We're 
all going to be nicely rewarded for holding on to the stock.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investors gave a cool response to Delphi after details of the  
distribution were released. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange, Delphi was  
down more than 5 percent, or by $1.06 1/4, at $19.56 1/4 a share, while 
GM was up 25 cents at $84.87 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	In announcing the details of the spinoff, GM said its  
shareholders would effectively be getting a dividend increase. 
That's because GM said it intends to maintain its quarterly 
dividend at 50 cents a share of common stock, even though Delphi no 
longer will be part of its financial results, while Delphi intends 
to pay a dividend of 7 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Catherine Dunsby, a GM spokeswoman, said the terms of the  
spinoff were based on Tuesday's closing stock values. 
</P>
<P>
	GM first announced plans to spin off Troy-based Delphi in  
August. On Feb. 5, Delphi began trading on the New York Stock 
Exchange in an initial public offering. 
</P>
<P>
	J. T. Battenberg III, Delphi's chairman, chief executive officer  
and president, said independence from GM will make Delphi a 
completely different company. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the final step of a long journey,'' he said Wednesday.  
``We're going through quite an extensive cultural change. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be truly ... an all-new company.''  
</P>
<P>
	Tanner and Battenberg said they anticipated that GM and Delphi  
would experience growth after the split. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this is truly a win-win situation,'' Battenberg said.  
``(GM) should be able to focus very sharply on their car and truck 
business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to being the largest auto parts maker in the world,  
Delphi is the 36th largest U.S. company in terms of sales. GM, 
DaimlerChrysler, Fiat, Toyota and Volkswagen are its largest 
customers. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990526.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 13:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Vince Carter Named Top NBA Rookie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Vince Carter of the Toronto Raptors was the  
overwhelming choice today as the NBA's rookie of the year, 
capturing the award with 113 of 118 votes in a panel of media 
voting. 
</P>
<P>
	Sacramento's Jason Williams received three votes and Boston's  
Paul Pierce got two. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter was the fifth selection in the 1998 NBA draft and  
averaged 18.3 points, 5.7 rebounds and 3.0 assists for the Raptors. 
He was the team's leading scorer, hitting 20 or more points 20 
times and 30 or more three times. 
</P>
<P>
	An early entry player out of the University of North Carolina,  
Carter was drafted by Golden State and then swapped almost 
immediately to Toronto in exchange for cash and his college 
teammate, Antawn Jamison, who was the No. 4 pick. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter is the second Raptor to win the award. Damon Stoudamire,  
who was traded to the Portland Trail Blazers in 1998, was rookie of 
the year in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The award is sponsored by Schick.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
