<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charter To Buy Falcon Cable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen took a major  
step toward becoming a cable TV baron with a deal announced today 
to acquire Los Angeles-based cable company Falcon Communications. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, the latest in the rapidly consolidating cable TV  
industry, will make Allen's Charter Communications Inc. of St. 
Louis the nation's fourth-largest cable company with 5.5 million 
subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	Charter officials put the price of the deal at $3.6 billion in  
cash and stock but did not provide a breakdown or comment on how 
much assumed debt was included in the transaction. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition vaults Charter into the big leagues of the cable  
TV industry, behind AT&AMP;T, which became the industry leader with its 
purchases of TCI and MediaOne, and behind Time Warner and Comcast. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen, who co-founded Microsoft Corp. with Bill Gates in 1975,  
has been assembling a growing cable business over the past year. He 
also owns stakes in several technology companies, as well as 
football's Seattle Seahawks and basketball's Portland Trail 
Blazers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcon acquisition furthers Allen's goal of creating a  
powerful network to deliver telecommunications services to a wide 
base of subscribers. AT&AMP;T is also hoping to use the cable TV 
pipelines to deliver packages of network services that include 
local phone service, Internet connections as well as television. 
</P>
<P>
	``These properties, when combined with our other properties, are  
an excellent fit with Paul Allen's wired-world strategy,'' Charter 
president Jerald L. Kent said. 
</P>
<P>
	For Falcon, the deal with Charter gives the company the  
financial backing and technological expertise to upgrade its cable 
lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Falcon was founded in 1975 to provide bare-bones cable service  
to remote communities underserved by broadcast TV. Most of its 
systems can deliver just 35 channels, compared with the industry 
standard of more than 100. 
</P>
<P>
	The costs of upgrading systems in sparsely populated  
communities, however, have kept small operators such as Falcon 
behind the competitive curve, driving many to sell out. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifty-four percent of Falcon is controlled by founder Marc B.  
Nathanson, who will become vice chairman of Charter. The other 46 
percent of Falcon is owned by AT&AMP;T Broadband &AMP; Internet Services, 
which has approved the transaction. 
</P>
<P>
	Nathanson, who was appointed by President Clinton as chairman of  
U.S. International Broadcasting, said he was looking ``forward to 
helping Charter continue its rapid growth and devoting more time to 
my government duties.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
