<DOCNO> APW19990526.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks' Loss To Pacers Still Vivid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) -- The memory of the key moments in last  
year's playoff loss to the Indiana Pacers remains vivid in the 
minds of Chris Dudley and Jeff Van Gundy. 
</P>
<P>
	It was late in the fourth quarter of Game 4, the Knicks were  
ahead by seven points and had a chance to tie the series 2-2 with a 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Problem was, Rik Smits was unstoppable.  
</P>
<P>
	Dudley wanted to do something about it, but Van Gundy wouldn't  
let him as the coach stuck with an exhausted Patrick Ewing, who was 
playing just his third game after making a surprise comeback from a 
wrist injury. Smits easily outplayed him. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Dudley might get a chance to be the Smits stopper.  
</P>
<P>
	``I could see them playing together, but I can't see Patrick not  
playing down the stretch of a close game,'' Van Gundy said 
Wednesday after the team held a light workout in preparation for 
the Eastern Conference finals beginning Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Smits really hurt us in the fourth quarter of Game 4, and  
that's why we started (Dudley) him against him when we played him 
this season,'' Van Gundy said. ``Smits made a great adjustment 
against Chris and scored pretty easily the second time we played 
him at Indiana, so now it's up to Chris to adjust to what Smits did 
to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consider that a message from the coach to Dudley. If he wants to  
be the stopper in Game 6 or 7, he's better be a stopper in Game 1 
or 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Dudley was the hero of Game 3 in the second round against  
Atlanta with 14 points and 12 rebounds, but he is such an offensive 
liability that it's tough to leave him in down the stretch of close 
games. But with Ewing's mobility reduced by sore knees and Achilles 
tendinitis, Dudley might be the Knicks' best option to keep Smits 
from turning the series around as he did last year when he scored 
14 points in the fourth quarter of Game 4. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks led 100-93 with 3:47 left in that game before Smits  
scored twice and Reggie Miller hit a 3-pointer off an offensive 
rebound with 5.9 seconds left to force overtime. The Pacers went on 
to win the game and take a 3-1 lead in the second-round series they 
would eventually win 4-1. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, I'd relish to be given that challenge down the  
stretch to stop him, but I have confidence in him as well,'' Dudley 
said of Ewing. ``But I do hope I get put in that situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another big-man option for the Knicks is the frail Marcus Camby,  
who will be called upon to mix it up underneath with the brawny 
Davises, Antonio and Dale, while also trying to outrun them and 
score points in transition with New York's uptempo second unit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm confident. I mean those guys just hang around the basket  
getting putbacks and rebounds, so I definitely have to come 
prepared to battle on offensive and defensive rebounding,'' said 
Camby, who found out Wednesday that the Pacers' Antonio Davis had 
been knocking him. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis told reporters in Indianapolis that he liked the Charles  
Oakley trade because it makes the Knicks much less physical. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll see,'' Camby said. ``It's a long series, they've got to  
beat us four times and I'll be there. We'll see.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
