<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Panel To Examine Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A new ethics commission will examine 14 ``minor  
allegations'' of misconduct by IOC members during past Olympic 
bids. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Olympic Committee panel, set up in the wake of  
the Salt Lake City bribery scandal, studied replies from national 
Olympic committees for information on any improprieties during the 
bid process. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was determined 14 cases have not so far been addressed,''  
the IOC said in a statement Wednesday from Lausanne, Switzerland. 
``But, after a brief review, the commission noted most of them 
involved minor allegations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The names of the IOC members involved and details of the  
allegations were not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel established a set of rules and procedures to deal with  
each case ``rationally and fairly,'' and will submit its findings 
to the IOC executive board, the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	No specific timetable was given, but the IOC said the commission  
would meet again ``as soon as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC said the ethics panel has drafted a code of conduct that  
will be submitted for approval at the committee's general assembly 
in Seoul, South Korea, next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Six IOC members were expelled and four resigned after being  
accused of receiving improper inducements during Salt Lake's 
winning bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	In the wake of that scandal, the IOC asked for details on any  
other misconduct by members going back to the bidding for the 1996 
Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the case of embattled Australian IOC member Phil  
Coles may move toward a resolution next week. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber said the executive board  
will review the Coles case Monday and a special three-person 
investigative panel may meet Thursday to conclude its findings. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles received a severe warning from the IOC for accepting  
lavish travel and other benefits from Salt Lake bidders, and is now 
under investigation for further allegations of abusing his Olympic 
positions. 
</P>
<P>
	His ex-wife has told the IOC that the couple received jewelry  
valued at $6,000 from a businessman associated with the Athens bid 
for the 1996 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles also has been accused of compiling secret dossiers on IOC  
members for Sydney's successful 2000 bid. Those files were also 
passed on to Salt Lake bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has denied any wrongdoing.  
</P>
<P>
	IOC 2000, an 80-member task force set up to propose reforms and  
restructuring of the organization, will meet for the first time 
Tuesday and Wednesday in Lausanne. 
</P>
<P>
	In a sign of new openness, the IOC said the commission's plenary  
sessions would be beamed to the media via live closed-circuit 
television. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're more open,'' Servan-Schreiber said. ``We've broken a lot  
of tradition recently. We have nothing to hide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, there will be no break with tradition at the assembly  
in Seoul. 
</P>
<P>
	``The IOC session will remain closed,'' the spokesman said.  
``It's an important forum for debate of IOC procedures and internal 
issues.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
