<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Salad Plant Comes to North Dakota / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FARGO, N.D. (AP) -- In a state where beef and wheat rule, some  
agriculture officials hope to persuade farmers to try salad, too. 
</P>
<P>
	A vegetable growers' group is joining with a development  
organization to build a salad processing plant in North Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant would use area-grown vegetables and other products to  
produce a line of prepared deli salads for sale in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, there are few vegetable growers in the region, but that  
hasn't stopped organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we've done is to recognize that the processing and the  
markets for farmers have to come first,'' said Rod Holth, 
secretary-treasurer of Central Dakota Growers, one of the partners 
in the project. ``Once we have a processing facility in place, 
getting people to grow more vegetables won't be a problem at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Central Dakota Growers received a $39,000 grant from the North  
Dakota Agricultural Products Utilization Commission to prepare 
salad recipes, conduct taste tests and complete a feasibility 
study. 
</P>
<P>
	The project is a joint effort of Central Dakota Growers, the Red  
River Trade Council and a European company with similar processing 
facilities overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Holth declined to name the company, citing confidentiality  
agreements. But he said the company has been interested in 
developing partnerships to expand vegetable processing in the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Brent Sorenson, a senior associate for agri-industry with the  
Red River Trade Council, said his organization has been trying for 
a number of years to expand vegetable farming. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal has been to find markets in addition to the fresh  
produce market, which is pretty limited,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rudy Radke, an agricultural diversification specialist with the  
North Dakota State University Extension Service, has been helping 
with the project. He said the biggest hurdle may be convincing 
farmers in North Dakota that they can grow vegetables and make a 
profit. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not been established in North Dakota as a vegetable  
production area, but that doesn't mean we can't grow them here,'' 
he said. ``We know we can grow the products here. What we have to 
do is set up the markets and the processing to make it 
worthwhile.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sorenson said organizers of the processing plant already have  
conducted a number of ``positive'' marketing studies and now are 
studying the feasibility of building the processing facility. 
</P>
<P>
	The grant money also is being used to help pay for a private  
consultant who is conducting taste tests and developing a line of 
salad recipes. 
</P>
<P>
	Sorenson and Holth said it will be at least six months before  
organizers have a decision on whether to go ahead with the project. 
No decision has been made yet on its size, or how many people it 
might employ, or a specific site. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I'm very optimistic and excited about it,'' Holth said.  
``It might not be on a large scale to begin with, but I think once 
we have a processing facility and a market for growers, this thing 
could take off.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
