<DOCNO> APW19990526.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 12:02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Advocates Assess China Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Advocates of closer economic ties with China  
tried on Wednesday to gauge the damage of a House espionage report, 
even as some lawmakers sought to tighten restrictions on technology 
exports. 
</P>
<P>
	The fallout, at the least, could wind up delaying negotiations  
over China's long-sought entry into the World Trade Organization, a 
slowdown that open-trade advocates suggest could hurt American 
companies more than Chinese enterprises. 
</P>
<P>
	Some congressional conservatives were urging those talks be put  
on hold as overall U.S.-Chinese relations are reviewed. The talks 
had already been disrupted by Chinese anger over the mistaken 
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute could also make it harder for the Clinton  
administration to win congressional approval next month for 
renewing normal trade relations with China, a contentious vote even 
the best of times. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we should rush to judgment,'' Senate Majority  
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said in terms of overall U.S.-Chinese 
relations. ``We should understand the full ramifications of what 
happened here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, Lott asked the Senate to approve legislation  
designed to tighten export controls in trade with China to prevent 
more weapons technology from falling into Beijing's hands, and to 
strengthen Pentagon monitoring of Chinese missile launches. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott's proposals were among a rash of legislative measures  
expected to be offered in the coming days that target Beijing. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., an advocate of closer ties with China,  
said he hoped Congress could separate trade and security issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once members realize that we're not giving anything to China  
with WTO membership and that it's China that has been making all 
the concessions, this will turn out to be a temporary bump'' in 
trade relations with Beijing. ``It's for us, for America. It's 
China that has been making all the concessions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Geneva-based WTO oversees and facilitates international  
trade and referees disputes. So far, most trade between China and 
the United States has been one way, with Americans mostly buying 
Chinese goods. Last year, by U.S. accounting, the trade deficit 
with China soared to a record $57 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, the Chinese had made key concessions on  
opening their markets to U.S. goods in an effort to win U.S. 
backing for joining the WTO. U.S. Trade Representative Charlene 
Barshefsky told a group of senators on Tuesday that there had been 
little recent progress in those talks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being excluded from one of the world's fastest growing markets  
is not good for U.S. companies,'' said Lawrence Chimerine, an 
economist with the Economic Strategy Institute, which specializes 
in trade issues. ``There is no question that the embassy bombing 
and the spying charges have put a chill on relations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said he favors expanding trade with  
China. ``The scandal is not that China was spying on us. The 
scandal is here domestically,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new chill in relations comes just days before President  
Clinton was expected to seek annual renewal of trade benefits for 
Beijing. Clinton has until June 3 to notify Congress he's renewing 
the favorable trade status that gives China the lowest-possible 
tariffs on its exports. 
</P>
<P>
	This status -- formerly known as ``most favored nation'' but now  
called ``normal trade relations'' -- is extended permanently to most 
U.S. trading partners but must be renewed yearly for China. 
Congress has 90 days to block it. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration had planned to ask for permanent trade status  
for China with its ascension to the WTO. But, with those talks now 
in limbo, it is expected to go for yet another one-year renewal. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's clearly going to be a lot of political churning in  
Congress,'' said John Schott, an analyst with the Institute for 
International Economics. ``The administration is going to have to 
make a strong case on why a policy of engagement is in the overall 
U.S. interest.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
