<DOCNO> APW19990526.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 00:11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Congress Probing Chinese Spying  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bipartisan congressional report concludes  
that China stole information on the United States' most advanced 
thermonuclear weapons over 20 years of espionage and that thefts 
``almost certainly continue to the present.'' It also said the 
information stolen helped modernize China's nuclear program and 
that some U.S. weapon design technology may end up being 
incorporated in China's next generation of nuclear warheads. 
Committees in both the House and Senate are to learn details of the 
espionage findings at hearings Wednesday. 

</P>
<P>
	India Intensifies Kashmir Attacks  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Indian Air force jets launched  
airstrikes Wednesday in the disputed mountains of Kashmir, where 
the army has been exchanging mortar and heavy artillery fire with 
Pakistani forces, a domestic news agency reported. India and 
Pakistan have fought two of their three wars over Kashmir. More 
than 15,000 people have been killed in fighting between rebels and 
security forces in Kashmir in the last 10 years. The use of Indian 
air force jets was the most serious escalation of the conflict 
since both countries tested nuclear weapons in May 1998, prompting 
fears of a nuclear arms race in the subcontinent. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Takes Its Time on Gun Control  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Democrats said Tuesday they want their  
Republican colleagues to vote this week on the Senate's gun control 
restrictions. But GOP lawmakers are refusing to be rushed into a 
vote before mid-June. Democrats say that ignoring the urgency of 
the matter following two school shootings this year would mean 
defeat of a widely supported bill. Though Judiciary Committee 
Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill. says he supports ``common sense'' 
legislation that keeps guns away from children, he and other 
Republicans indicated they think changes in the Senate-passed 
measure are warranted. 

</P>
<P>
	Wales To Inaugurate New Assembly  
</P>
<P>
	CARDIFF, Wales (AP) -- A new Welsh Assembly will be inaugurated  
Wednesday, nearly 600 years after the last time it met. The 
60-member body will give Welsh lawmakers greater power over how 
their principality is run. The assembly will not have tax-raising 
or general legislative powers, but it will control distribution of 
the annual $13 billion grant from the British government. British 
Prime Minister Tony Blair proposed the assembly under a plan to 
surrender some power from the central government by giving Wales, 
Scotland and Northern Ireland more independence, while also 
preserving the British union. 

</P>
<P>
	Nazi Survivors Sue German Drug Firms  
</P>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A trio of lawsuits filed by Nazi death camp  
survivors accuses three German pharmaceutical companies of 
participating in gruesome and unscientific medical ``experiments'' 
by Dr. Joseph Mengele. The lawsuits filed May 13 against Bayer AG, 
Hoechst AG and Schering AG are among the first in the nation 
linking German companies to Nazi medical experiments. The 
Associated Press learned of the lawsuits Tuesday. They are the 
latest filings in a recent wave of litigation by survivors of Nazi 
death camps or slave labor factories aimed at European banks, 
insurance companies and industrial firms. 

</P>
<P>
	Americans Prefer To Live to 91  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A survey has found that most Americans have no  
interest in living to be 100. Only about one in four Americans 
hopes to reach the 100-year milestone, according to survey 
conducted for the American Association of Retired Persons. The 
respondents said they would prefer to live to about 91, on average. 
The reasons most often given for not wanting to live to 100 were 
worries about declining health, mentioned by 46 percent, and 
concerns about not having enough money to support themselves, 38 
percent. 

</P>
