<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Higher, Gold Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The dollar was up against most other major  
currencies in European trading Wednesday. Gold fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0504, down from $1.0591 Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Tuesday: 121.85 Japanese  
yen, down from 122.85; 1.5162 Swiss francs, up from 1.4997; and 
1.4680 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4593 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.5985, down from $1.6018.  
</P>
<P>
	Midday in New York, the dollar bought 121.90 yen, while the euro  
was worth $1.0465 and the pound traded at $1.5950. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar was worth: 1.8620 German marks, up from 1.8469; 
6.2448 French francs, up from 6.1941; 2.0980 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.0809; and 1,843.36 Italian lire, up from 1,828.39 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $269.60 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$271.70 on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $269.35, down from $271.65.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold fell $3.70 in Hong Kong to close at $269.55.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.08 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.06. 
</P>
