<HEADLINE> Wash. Man Accused of Abusing Wife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EVERETT, Wash. (AP) -- A man has been arrested for allegedly  
beating and starving his disabled wife for 17 years, hiding her 
from the world on a decrepit sailboat. 
</P>
<P>
	Victor Matthew David, 59, pleaded innocent Wednesday to charges  
of second-degree assault. He could get up to 10 years in prison. He 
was being held on $150,000 bail. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, police were called to the couple's sailboat by a social  
worker who was trying to determine whether David was fraudulently 
collecting his wife's disability checks. She has multiple 
sclerosis. 
</P>
<P>
	Police found Linda David, 50, wearing filthy, vomit-stained  
clothes in a room covered with dog feces, according to court 
papers. 
</P>
<P>
	She was almost blind and barely able to speak. Her face was  
badly scarred, and her arms had been broken and had healed without 
medical attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've talked to some of the officers who were involved at the  
time,'' police spokesman Elliot Woodall said Tuesday, ``and they 
said that it was among the worst conditions they'd ever seen a 
human living in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. David, who is now recovering in a nursing home, said: ``No  
way I could get off (the boat) to get help. That was home. I never 
had anywhere else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said David wasn't arrested for 2 1/2 more years because  
of the difficulty in building a case. He had kept his wife so 
well-hidden that neighbors thought she did not really exist, 
prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	David said any injuries his wife suffered came when she fell out  
of a truck. 
</P>
</TEXT>
