<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NY Cop Case Continues Without Volpe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A judge told jurors today that a white police  
officer had pleaded guilty to torturing a Haitian immigrant with a 
wooden stick, and rejected a motion for a mistrial by two 
co-defendants. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Eugene Nickerson did not detail Officer Justin Volpe's  
plea Tuesday other than to tell jurors he pleaded guilty. He 
cautioned the 12 jurors and six alternates that the development 
``can't be used as evidence in determining whether the other 
defendants are guilty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The jurors, who are not sequestered, had no visible reaction.  
The lead defendant was conspicuously absent when the jury returned 
to Brooklyn federal court today. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge rejected defense motions for a mistrial. Defense  
attorney John Patten, who represents Sgt. Michael Bellomo, said 
Tuesday that Volpe's departure creates ``a prejudice that adheres 
to everyone else at the defense table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday -- with his mid-trial bid for a plea bargain rejected  
and chances of an acquittal obliterated -- Volpe pleaded guilty to 
violating the civil rights of the prisoner, Abner Louima. 
</P>
<P>
	``There came a point in time where the evidence became  
overwhelming,'' said Volpe's attorney, Marvyn Kornberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe, 27, admitted ramming a stick into the handcuffed victim's  
rectum, pulling it out and putting it up to his face. He said he 
mistakenly believed Louima had punched him while police tried to 
quell a disturbance outside a nightclub on Aug. 9, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe's dramatic decision could land him in prison for the rest  
of his life. What it meant for his co-defendants was much less 
clear. 
</P>
<P>
	The spotlight could shift to Officer Charles Schwarz, who is  
accused of holding down Louima, 32, during the assault in the 
bathroom of the stationhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Schwarz and Officers Thomas Wiese and Thomas Bruder also are  
charged with beating Louima in a patrol car en route to the 70th 
police precinct after his arrest on false charges he punched Volpe. 
Bellomo, their supervisor, is charged with covering up the 
incident. 
</P>
<P>
	Louima has identified Schwarz as the second bathroom assailant.  
Two police officers also testified that they saw the officer 
searching Louima at the front desk of the station hours before 
marching him in the general direction of the bathroom. 
</P>
<P>
	During Tuesday's hearing, Volpe said another officer was present  
during the attack in the bathroom. When pressed by the judge, he 
said the other officer did not hit Louima but ``saw what was going 
on and did nothing to stop it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It was understood from the circumstances that the police  
officer would do nothing to stop me or report it to anyone,'' Volpe 
said. Volpe did not name the officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Schwarz has denied ever being in the bathroom.  
</P>
<P>
	The jury learned of Volpe's plea as the U.S. Civil Rights  
Commission began holding hearings this morning on the New York 
Police Department -- how it operates, trains its officers and deals 
with non-white citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Rudolph Giuliani testified that there had been fewer fatal  
shootings by police and fewer incidents of discharging weapons than 
in the past. His comments were met by hissing and groans from the 
audience. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor acknowledged that the police force does not reflect  
the city's racial makeup, but said there were new recruiting 
efforts, and he insisted that the police stop suspects based on 
descriptions given to them by victims, and not because of a policy 
of racial profiling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
