<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jazz Players Do Desperation Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Stick around as long as John Stockton and Karl Malone have, and  
little tricks become a big part of your arsenal. 
</P>
<P>
	They do desperation well.  
</P>
<P>
	Old age and treachery beat youth and skill Tuesday night, though  
it might be for the last time this season. Down 3-1 and facing 
elimination in their Western Conference semifinal against Portland, 
Stockton and Malone had enough up their sleeves to lead Utah to an 
88-71 win. 
</P>
<P>
	``They did everything better than we did -- physically, mentally,  
emotionally, spiritually,'' the Trail Blazers' Greg Anthony said. 
``They won every facet of the game. They out-everythinged us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That should have surprised no one. The Jazz are 6-1 the last  
seven times they faced elimination, including three times in the 
past 11 days. 
</P>
<P>
	The reason is simple. Like aging actors, the 37-year-old  
Stockton and the 35-year-old Malone -- with 29 postseasons between 
them -- are no longer capable of a command performance every night. 
But on any given night, they can take back as many seasons as they 
need to. 
</P>
<P>
	Malone was an inspiration from the outset Tuesday, scoring 11  
points and leveling Portland's Brian Grant with an elbow as the 
Jazz put together their best opening quarter this series. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I'm passive, I think they are,'' Malone said about his  
teammates. ``So I tried to be aggressive right off the bat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His attitude was infectious. The Jazz defended a little more  
ferociously, their cuts to the basket were sharper, their picks to 
free shooters a little more rattling. Everybody in a white jersey 
thrived from the increased contact, but no one more than Stockton. 
</P>
<P>
	Through the first four games, he seemed uncomfortable running  
the offense, always peeking over his shoulder for the bigger, 
younger, stronger defenders Portland kept throwing at him. But on 
this night, Stockton was the conductor in charge of his orchestra 
again. He remembered where everything was; and what he couldn't 
see, he sensed. 
</P>
<P>
	Stockton tracked Shandon Anderson weaving through traffic and  
threaded a bounce pass that met him at the intersection of baseline 
and basket. Or he drove the lane himself, sensed Bryon Russell 
parked in the corner and instinctively whipped the ball out for a 
3-pointer. Stockton finished with only six points, but he had 14 
assists -- four more than the entire Portland team -- and committed 
just two turnovers. 
</P>
<P>
	Malone's game was as confrontational as Stockton's was subtle.  
Coming down with a rebound in the first quarter, his elbow caught 
Grant above the right eye, opening a cut that would require six 
stitches. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think anything in that game was done intentionally,''  
the Trail Blazers' Jim Jackson said. ``It was just a really, really 
physical game with some hard play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA, of course, will have final say on the matter.  
</P>
<P>
	Malone was slapped with a $10,000 fine for elbowing Grant in  
Game 1. And though he would never admit as much, if the Mailman 
gets slapped for this second delivery, he would consider it money 
well spent. Because up until the moment Grant's face interrupted 
Malone's landing, the momentum in the series was flowing one way -- 
Portland's. 
</P>
<P>
	And like a delayed knockout, Grant didn't feel the blow's effect  
until nine minutes remained. With Portland trailing 72-58, he got 
whistled for swinging his elbows on a rebound and then, after the 
Jazz missed their next shot and Grant rebounded again, he got hit 
with a technical because he pretended to throw the ball at Malone's 
head. 
</P>
<P>
	That set Trail Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy after referee Ron  
Garretson, dragging two assistant coaches and Anthony along until 
Dunleavy got ejected. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunleavy acknowledged that for the moment, anyway, the Jazz had  
regained some of their edge. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have some momentum after this,'' Dunleavy said. ``It's  
our job to take it away from them, however we have to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because Portland is younger, deeper, just as tough and unlikely  
to get sucker-punched again, they will. 
</P>
<P>
	Too bad.  
</P>
<P>
	Malone and Stockton have shared the MVP award at an All-Star  
game, received gold medals at the Olympics together and stood 
side-by-side when the NBA's ``50 Greatest'' were assembled. 
</P>
<P>
	But they also walked off the floor in disappointment together  
when the Bulls and Michael Jordan won the championship the last two 
years. With the breakup in Chicago, this was supposed to be their 
year. But life is rarely fair. It might turn out that all those 
seasons of hard work bought Stockton and Malone, finally, was one 
more magnificent night. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at:jlitke@ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
