<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Informix, Ernst &AMP; Young Settle Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) -- Database software maker Informix Corp.  
and its former auditors today agreed to pay $142 million to settle 
allegations the company misstated revenues and traded on inside 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Informix and Ernst &AMP; Young LLP, the former auditors,  
reported the signing. The amount is more than twice what the 
company earned last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased that we have reached this settlement,'' said  
Bob Finocchio, chairman and chief executive officer for Informix. 
``It is a well-structured solution that allows Informix to move 
forward unhindered. We can now devote all of our efforts to 
building the new Informix.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Informix said the deal, which is subject to court approval,  
calls for the company to pay about $3.2 million in cash, $13.8 
million in insurance payments on behalf of several current and 
former officers, and 9 million shares of company stock worth about 
$91 million. Ernst &AMP; Young will pay $34 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ernst &AMP; Young LLP made a business decision to settle in order  
to eliminate the burden of further litigation,'' company spokesman 
Don Howarth said Wednesday. ``Our former client, Informix, also 
wished to settle so a global resolution to the matter made sense 
from a business perspective. There is no admission of wrongdoing 
from Ernst &AMP; Young in the settlement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The money will go to compensate those who held company stock  
from early 1995 to late 1997. During that period, Informix 
allegedly padded revenues with hundreds of millions of dollars in 
nonexistent sales to boost the company's stock price. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Chief Executive Officer Phillip E. White and former  
Informix Chief Financial Officer Howard Graham sold more than $15 
million worth of stock before the company announced in 1997 it was 
losing money. 
</P>
<P>
	The Securities and Exchange Commission questioned Informix and,  
in November 1997, the company restated its financial results for 
the previous 14 quarters, wiping out almost $240 million in 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Informix, based in Menlo Park, earned $57.7 million on sales of  
$735 million last year. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
